North American Market Conference (June 12, 2003)], speech transcript\n|-\n| [[Doris Meissner|Doris M. Meissner]]\n| [http://www.migrationpolicy.org/staff/index.php#Meissner Migration Policy Institute]\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20090211201017/http://www.carnegieendowment.org/experts/index.cfm?fa=expert_view&expert_id=105 Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]\n| [http://www.trilateral.org/ProjWork/tfrsums/tfr44.htm International Migration Challenges in a New Era]\n[http://www.migrationpolicy.org/task_force/new_chapter_summary.pdf Immigration and America's Future: A New Chapter by the Independent Task Force on Immigration and America's Future] sponsored by The Migration Policy Institute, The Manhattan Institute for Policy Research and the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars<br/>\n[http://www.9-11commission.gov/hearings/hearing7/witness_meissner.htm Statement of Doris Meissner to the National Commission on Terrorist Attacks Upon The United States]\n|-\n| [[Thomas M.T. Niles]]\n| [http://www.uscib.org/index.asp?documentID=1105 United States Council for International Business]\n| \n|-\n| [[Luis de la Calle Pardo]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Beatriz Paredes]]\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20090213070231/http://www.csis.org/component/option,com_csis_events/task,view/id,853/ Center for Strategic and International Studies]\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20090129050850/http://beatriz-paredes.org/sitio/ Beatriz Paredes election campaign in Mexico (Spanish only)]\n[http://www.fundacioncolosio.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=289&Itemid=114 Paredes video talk (Spanish only)]\n|-\n| [[Andr\u00e9s Rozental]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Luis Rubio]]\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20090211142227/http://www.csis.org/component/option,com_csis_experts/task,view/id,290/ Center for Strategic and International Studies]\n| \n|-\n| [[Jeffrey J. Schott]]\n| [http://www.iie.com/staff/author_bio.cfm?author_id=62 Peterson Institute for International Economics]\n| \n|-\n| [[Raul Yzaguirre]]\n| [http://www.asu.edu/feature/includes/spring05/readmore/yzaguirre.html Arizona State University]\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Consortium for North American Higher Education Collaboration]]\n* [[North American Free Trade Agreement|NAFTA - North American Free Trade Agreement]]\n* [[North American Competitiveness Council]]\n* [[North American currency union]]\n* [[North American Union]]\n* [[Security and Prosperity Partnership of North America]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://northamericaninstitute.org/ The North American Institute (NAMI)]\n\n{{Trilateral relations of Canada, Mexico, and United States}}\n{{Legislatures of the Americas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Independent Task Force On North America}}\n[[Category:Supranational unions]]\n[[Category:Continental unions]]\n[[Category:Canada\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Economy of North America]]\n[[Category:Task forces]]\n\n[[sv:Nordamerikanska Unionen]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_Task_Force_on_North_America"}
{"title_page": "Mutual Street Arena", "text_new": "{{Infobox Stadium\n| stadium_name        = Mutual Street Arena\n| nickname            = Arena Gardens <br> The Arena<br>The Terrace\n| image               = [[File:Mutual Street Arena interior.jpg|200px]]\n| fullname            =\n| location            = 68\u201388 Mutual Street,<br>[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|43|39|21|N|79|22|32|W|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground        =\n| built               =\n| opened              = 1912\n| renovated           = \n| expanded            = \n| closed              = \n| demolished          = 1989\n| owner               = The Arena Gardens of Toronto, Limited<ref name=\"shares-offering\">{{cite news |work=The Globe |title=Shares Offering |date=March 6, 1912 |page=12}}</ref>\n| operator            = \n| surface             = mechanically-frozen ice\n| construction_cost   = [[Canadian dollar|C$]]500,000\n| architect           = Ross and McFarlane of Montreal<ref name=\"shares-offering\"/>\n| structural engineer =\n| services engineer   =\n| general_contractor  = Peter Lyall & Sons Limited<ref name=\"shares-offering\"/>\n| project_manager     =\n| main_contractors    = \n| former_names        = Arena Gardens (name at opening)\n| tenants             = [[Toronto Tecumsehs]] ([[National Hockey Association|NHA]]) (1912-1913)<br>[[Toronto Blueshirts]] (NHA) (1912-1917)<br>[[Toronto Ontarios]] (NHA) (1913-1914)<br>[[Toronto Shamrocks]] (NHA) (1914-1915)<br>[[Toronto Aura Lee]], ([[Ontario Hockey Association|OHA]]) (1916-1926)<br>Toronto 228th Battalion (NHA) (1916-1917)<br>[[Toronto Arenas|Torontos/Toronto Arenas]]/[[Toronto St. Pats|St. Pats]]/[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1917-1931)<br>[[Toronto Marlboros]] (1926-1931)<br>Toronto Falcons ([[International Hockey League (1929-1936)|IHL]]) (1929-1930)<br>[[Toronto Tecumsehs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[International Lacrosse League|ILL]]) (1931)\n| seating_capacity    = seated: 6,000<br/>standing: 7,500 (hockey)\n| dimensions          =\n}}\n\n'''Mutual Street Arena,''' initially called '''Arena Gardens''' or just the '''Arena''', was an ice hockey arena and sports and entertainment venue in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. From 1912 until 1931, with the opening of [[Maple Leaf Gardens]], it was the premier site of [[ice hockey]] in Toronto, being home to teams from the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA), the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) and the [[International Hockey League (1929-1936)|International Hockey League]] (IHL).  It was the first home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], who played at the arena under various names for their first 13\u00bd seasons. The Arena Gardens was the third rink in Canada to feature a mechanically frozen or 'artificial' ice surface, and for eleven years was the only such facility in eastern Canada. In 1923, it was the site of the first radio broadcast of an ice hockey game, the first radio broadcast of an NHL game, and the first broadcast of an ice hockey game by long-time broadcaster [[Foster Hewitt]]. \n\nThe Arena was also used for musical concerts, gatherings and other sporting events, including professional [[boxing]], [[cycling]], [[wrestling]] and [[tennis]]. In 1962, it was converted to a [[curling]] club and [[roller skating]] rink known as '''The Terrace'''. The building was demolished in 1989 and the ''Cathedral Square'' residential complex and ''Arena Gardens'' municipal park now occupy the site. It was located on Mutual Street, just south of [[Dundas Street|Dundas Street East]] and two blocks east of [[Church Street (Toronto)|Church Street]] in downtown Toronto.\n\n==History==\nIt was constructed for a reported cost of {{CAD|500,000|link=yes}} and opened in 1912.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=22}} It was built on the site of the [[Mutual Street Rink]], used primarily for [[curling]] and [[ice skating]] between [[Dundas Street|Dundas Street East]] and Shuter Street. At the time, it was billed as the largest indoor arena in Canada and held about 7,500 for hockey. The rink was owned by the Toronto Arena Company, organized September 19, 1911, with [[Henry Pellatt|Sir Henry Pellatt]] as president, [[Lol Solman]] as managing director, and directors [[Aemilius Jarvis]], Joseph Kilgour, T.W. Horn, R.A. Smith, and Col. Carlson. There were two other directors from Montreal. W. J. Bellingham was the initial manager.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 10, 1912 |title=Arena in Full Swing; Perfect Sheet of Ice |page=4}}</ref>\n\nThe Arena opened with a performance by Nathan Franko's Orchestra on October 7, 1912, supporting a recital by Alice Neville, soprano of the [[Metropolitan Opera]], tenor Orville Harold and a company of opera singers from the [[Boston Opera Company]] organized by Neville. It was the first of a series called the ''Toronto Music Festival.''<ref name=\"world-opening\">{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 7, 1912 |title=No Confusion Over Arena Tickets |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=hqOjcs7Dif8C&dat=19121007&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |accessdate=August 10, 2011 |page=8}}</ref> Entrances to the various blue and red seating sections were indicated by corresponding blue and red lights on the outside of the building.<ref name=\"world-opening\"/> It was followed the next day by a recital by [[Johanna Gadski]] with Franko's orchestra.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 9, 1912 |page=1 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=g3UDAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uikDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1353%2C2906224 |title=Seven Thousand People Heard Gadski at Arena|accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> The festival continued all week, concluding on October 12 with a variety show headlined by Canadian theatre and film actress [[Marie Dressler]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 12, 1912 |page=8 |title=Marie Dressler Will Appear Tonight |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hnUDAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uikDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2766%2C3392560 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> Americans [[Yvonne de Tr\u00e9ville]], [[Charlotte Maconda]] and [[Rosa Olitzka]] sang arias from several operas while Dressler performed a comedic reading of the poem \"The Glove\" by [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]], singing \"burlesque opera solos\" to the accompaniment of [[Nathan Franko's Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 14, 1912 |page=8 |title=Grand Finale of Opera Week}}</ref>\n \nArena Gardens was initially home to two new teams in the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA): the [[Toronto Blueshirts|Toronto Hockey Club]] and the [[Toronto Tecumsehs|Tecumseh Hockey Club]]. Delays in construction meant that the teams could not play in the 1911-12 season, as was originally scheduled. The {{Convert|12|miles}} of piping for the artificial ice was installed improperly and had to be reinstalled in December 1912.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 3, 1912 |title=Rowing Club are to join junior hockey ranks |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 8, 1912 |title=Arena to be ready Monday |page=Sports p. 1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 9, 1912 |title=Arena Opens Today |page=4}}</ref> The first professional ice hockey game in the building was on December 21, 1912, an exhibition between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and [[Montreal Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 23, 1912 |title=Montreal Pros Show Class |page=4}}</ref> [[Sprague Cleghorn]] was suspended for four weeks and fined $65 by the NHA for assaulting the Canadiens' [[Newsy Lalonde]] in the game.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleghorn Fined And Suspended For Assault On Newsy Lalonde |work=Toronto World |date=December 23, 1912 |page=4}}</ref> The first official game was on December 25, 1912, a game between the Canadiens and the Torontos.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} Upon the suspension of the NHA in 1917, the professional franchise of the new [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) for Toronto was operated by the Toronto Arena itself. The franchise was operated by the Arena for two years before being sold to become the [[Toronto St. Patricks]]. The St. Pats became the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in 1927 and played at Arena Gardens until the completion of [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] in 1931. Until 1923, the Arena was the only facility east of [[Manitoba]] with artificial ice-making capability. With this in mind, the St. Pats often let other teams use the Arena as a neutral site during the early and late months of the season, when it was usually too warm for proper ice.{{sfn|Hunter|1997}}\n\nThe year 1922 saw the first professional wrestling bout at the Arena, between former world champion [[Stanislaus Zbyszko]] and Canadian champion George Walker. Professional wrestling would continue at the Arena until 1938. Promoter Ivan Mickailof began promoting weekly shows in 1929. Some of the names that Mickailof presented at the Arena included [[Strangler Lewis]] and [[Toots Mondt]], as well as reigning world champions [[Gus Sonnenberg]], [[Ed Don George]], [[Henri Deglane]], [[Jim Londos]], Ali Baba, Vic Christie, [[Everett Marshall]] and Billy Weidner, who all defended their titles at the Arena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garywill.com/toronto/arenagardens.htm |title=Arena Gardens: Toronto's original wrestling palace (1922-1938) |publisher=garywill.com |accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 1923, the first radio broadcast of an ice hockey game was made from the Arena by the [[Toronto Daily Star]]'s  [[CFCA (AM)|CFCA]] radio station. [[Norman Albert]] did the [[play-by-play]] of the third period of a game between North Toronto and [[Midland, Ontario|Midland]], won by North Toronto 16\u20134.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Star |date=February 9, 1923 |page=12 |author=Albert, Norman |title=Conacher Scored Six for North Toronto}}</ref> Later that season, [[Foster Hewitt]] made his first radio broadcasts from the Arena, also on CFCA. A game on February 14, 1923 featured the [[Toronto St. Pats]] and the [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]], and is the first [[National Hockey League|NHL]] game to be broadcast on radio.{{sfn|Kitchen|2008|p=246}} The [[Stanley Cup]] Final was played at Arena Gardens four times: [[1914 Stanley Cup Finals|1914]], [[1918 Stanley Cup Finals|1918]], [[1920 Stanley Cup Finals|1920]] and [[1922 Stanley Cup Finals|1922]]. Arena Gardens also hosted the [[Memorial Cup]] finals nine times from 1919 to 1931. The Gardens also hosted the [[Allan Cup]] final series.<ref>{{cite news |work=Montreal Gazette |date=March 29, 1930 |page=20 |title=M.A.A.A Confident on Eve of Second Allan Cup Match |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=znAtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M4wFAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=6524%2C4967335 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> A 1931 game between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and the Maple Leafs was filmed by the [[National Film Board of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hockeythenandnow.blogspot.com/2011/04/game-film-circa-1931.html |title=Game Film : Circa 1931 |last=Amodeo |first=Jim |accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Wilfrid Laurier's reception at Liberal meeting, Arena Gardens.jpg|thumb|right|1913 Liberal Party Reception for [[Wilfrid Laurier]] at Arena Gardens]]\n[[File:United Church of Canada inauguration 1925.jpg|thumb|right|Photograph of United Church inaugural service]]\nThe building was also used for mass assemblies. An assembly was held for [[Sir Wilfrid Laurier]] in 1913 by the [[Liberal Party of Canada]]. On June 10, 1925, this building was used as the venue for the inaugural service of the [[United Church of Canada]], which united four existing denominations: the [[Presbyterian Church in Canada|Presbyterian]]s, the [[Methodist Church]] of Canada, the [[Congregational church|Congregational Union of Canada]], and the Association of Local Union Churches. On December 3, 1933, 7,000 persons attended a memorial service for Sir [[Arthur Currie]], commander of the Canadian Corps in World War I.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Star |title=Thousands mourn loss of Canadian Corps commander |date=December 4, 1933 |p=3}}</ref> On October 9, 1936, it was the site of a mass assembly by the [[Communist Party of Canada]].\n\nAfter the Maple Leafs left in 1931, the building no longer was a venue for professional ice hockey but remained open as a venue for sports and entertainment. Some of the other sports included bicycle racing, professional boxing and tennis.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} By 1934, revenues did not keep up with interest on bonds on the property, property taxes and the expenses of operating the arena.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |date=July 28, 1934 |page=16 |title=Summon Meeting of Arena Creditors |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sV4_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4381%2C574007 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> The bondholders made it known that the building was for sale.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |date=September 1, 1934 |page=8 |title=Will Consider Sale of Toronto Arena |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tl4_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4239%2C1291291 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> By 1937, with $200,000 of bonds in default, and  the Arena in default of 1933 and 1934 taxes of nearly $16,000, and a similar amount estimated for 1936 and 1937, the Arena was listed for sale by the City of Toronto.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |title=Tax Sale Threatens Toronto Arena Gardens |page=5 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NGc_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=u1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4579%2C194385 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1938, the Arena was leased to Edward \"Ted\" Dickson who turned it into a recreation facility offering ice skating in winter and [[roller skating]] in summer. The name was changed that year to the Mutual Street Arena.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} The [[Glenn Miller]] big band played at the Arena in January 1942, Miller's only appearance in Toronto. [[Frank Sinatra]] made his first appearance in Toronto here in 1949.<ref>{{cite book |title=Let's dance: a celebration of Ontario's dance halls and summer dance pavilions |last=Young |first=Peter |page=23 |year=2002 |isbn=1-896219-02-0}}</ref> [[Roller hockey]] was introduced to the Arena in the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The Billboard |date=March 6, 1948 |page=80 |title=Toronto's Hell on Wheels Paying Off at Box Office}}</ref> [[Hank Williams Sr]] played a concert at the Arena in 1952. The city's first boat show was held in 1954. The ''Melody Fair'' theatre-in-the-round operated at the Arena in 1954.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}}\n\nDickson bought the building in 1945 and it remained in the family for the next 43 years. The arena was renovated for $3 million in 1962, adding 18 [[curling]] sheets, year-round roller skating, a parking garage and a new facade.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} The Arena was renamed \"The Terrace\", a name it kept until it was sold in 1988. It closed its doors on April 30, 1989 and was demolished a few months later. The site was converted into a residential development with some of the site reserved for a city park. The Terrace name was retained for one of the residential buildings. In May 2011, the name of the city park on the site was changed from ''Cathedral Square Park'' to ''Arena Gardens''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2011/te/bgrd/backgroundfile-37996.pdf |title=Proposed renaming of Cathedral Square Park to \"Arena Gardens\" |author=Brenda Patterson, General Manager, Parks, Forestry and Recreation |date=May 4, 2011 |work=Staff Report |publisher=City of Toronto  |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\nThis list is incomplete.\n* October 7, 1912 - Grand opening\n* March 14\u201319, 1914 - Toronto Blueshirts \u2013 Victoria Aristocrats Stanley Cup series\n* March 20\u201330, 1918 - Torontos - Vancouver Millionaires Stanley Cup series\n* March 30\u2013April 1, 1920 - Two games of Ottawa Senators - Seattle Metropolitans Stanley Cup series\n* March 17\u201328, 1922 - Toronto St. Patricks - Vancouver Millionaires Stanley Cup series\n* February 8, 1923 - First radio broadcast of an ice hockey game\n* February 14, 1923 - First radio broadcast of an NHL game\n* June 10, 1925 - Inaugural service of United Church of Canada\n* December 3, 1933 - Memorial service for Sir Arthur Currie\n* January 23, 1942 - Only Toronto appearance by Glenn Miller and big band\n* May 6, 1952 - concert by Hank Williams Sr and the Grand Ole Opry Show.\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons cat|Mutual Street Arena}}\n* [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n* [[Air Canada Centre]]\n* [[Ricoh Coliseum]]\n* [[Varsity Arena]]\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Hewitt, Foster |title=Foster Hewitt: His Own Story |publisher=Ryerson Press |location=Toronto, Ontario |year=1967 |ref=harv}}\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Mike Filey |author=Filey, Mike |title=Like no other in the world: the story of the Toronto' Skydome |year=1989 |publisher=Sun Controlled Ventures |location=Toronto, Ontario |isbn=0-919233-31-7 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/likenootherinwor0000file }}\n*{{cite book |title=Champions: The Illustrated History of Hockey's Greatest Dynasties |last=Hunter |first=Douglas |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1997 |publisher=Triumph Books |location=[[Chicago]] |isbn=1-57243-213-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |author=Kitchen, Paul |title=Win, Lose or Wrangle: The Inside Story of the Old Ottawa Senators - 1883-1935 |publisher=Penumbra Press |location=Manotick, Ontario |year=2008 |ref=harv}}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hockey.ballparks.com/NHL/TorontoMapleLeafs/oldindex.htm Ballparks: Mutual Street Arena]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160814054828/http://www.garywill.com/toronto/arenagardens.htm Arena Gardens: Toronto's original wrestling palace (1922-1938)] (archived copy)\n* [http://www.tmlfever.com/MUTUALSTREETARENA.html TMLfever: Mutual Street Arena]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the<br>[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Toronto Arenas/St. Pats/Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1917 &ndash; 1931\n | before = first arena\n | after = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Blueshirts}}\n{{Former NHL arenas}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1912]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1989]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blueshirts]]\n[[Category:Toronto Tecumsehs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Marlboros]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Stadium\n| stadium_name        = Mutual Street Arena\n| nickname            = Arena Gardens <br> The Arena<br>The Terrace\n| image               = [[File:Mutual Street Arena interior.jpg|200px]]\n| fullname            =\n| location            = 68\u201388 Mutual Street,<br>[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|43|39|21|N|79|22|32|W|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground        =\n| built               =\n| opened              = 1912\n| renovated           = \n| expanded            = \n| closed              = \n| demolished          = 1989\n| owner               = The Arena Gardens of Toronto, Limited<ref name=\"shares-offering\">{{cite news |work=The Globe |title=Shares Offering |date=March 6, 1912 |page=12}}</ref>\n| operator            = \n| surface             = mechanically-frozen ice\n| construction_cost   = [[Canadian dollar|C$]]500,000\n| architect           = Ross and McFarlane of Montreal<ref name=\"shares-offering\"/>\n| structural engineer =\n| services engineer   =\n| general_contractor  = Peter Lyall & Sons Limited<ref name=\"shares-offering\"/>\n| project_manager     =\n| main_contractors    = \n| former_names        = Arena Gardens (name at opening)\n| tenants             = [[Toronto Tecumsehs]] ([[National Hockey Association|NHA]]) (1912-1913)<br>[[Toronto Blueshirts]] (NHA) (1912-1917)<br>[[Toronto Ontarios]] (NHA) (1913-1914)<br>[[Toronto Shamrocks]] (NHA) (1914-1915)<br>[[Toronto Aura Lee]], ([[Ontario Hockey Association|OHA]]) (1916-1926)<br>Toronto 228th Battalion (NHA) (1916-1917)<br>[[Toronto Arenas|Torontos/Toronto Arenas]]/[[Toronto St. Pats|St. Pats]]/[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1917-1931)<br>[[Toronto Marlboros]] (1926-1931)<br>Toronto Falcons ([[International Hockey League (1929-1936)|IHL]]) (1929-1930)<br>[[Toronto Tecumsehs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[International Lacrosse League|ILL]]) (1931)\n| seating_capacity    = seated: 6,000<br/>standing: 7,500 (hockey)\n| dimensions          =\n}}\n\n'''Mutual Street Arena,''' initially called '''Arena Gardens''' or just the '''Arena''', was an ice hockey arena and sports and entertainment venue in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. From 1912 until 1931, with the opening of [[Maple Leaf Gardens]], it was the premier site of [[ice hockey]] in Toronto, being home to teams from the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA), the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) and the [[International Hockey League (1929-1936)|International Hockey League]] (IHL).  It was the first home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], who played at the arena under various names for their first 13\u00bd seasons. The Arena Gardens was the third rink in Canada to feature a mechanically frozen or 'artificial' ice surface, and for eleven years was the only such facility in eastern Canada. In 1923, it was the site of the first radio broadcast of an ice hockey game, the first radio broadcast of an NHL game, and the first broadcast of an ice hockey game by long-time broadcaster [[Foster Hewitt]]. \n\nThe Arena was also used for musical concerts, gatherings and other sporting events, including professional [[boxing]], [[cycling]], [[wrestling]] and [[tennis]]. In 1962, it was converted to a [[curling]] club and [[roller skating]] rink known as '''The Terrace'''. The building was demolished in 1989 and the ''Cathedral Square'' residential complex and ''Arena Gardens'' municipal park now occupy the site. It was located on Mutual Street, just south of [[Dundas Street|Dundas Street East]] and two blocks east of [[Church Street (Toronto)|Church Street]] in downtown Toronto.\n\n==History==\nIt was constructed for a reported cost of {{CAD|500,000|link=yes}} and opened in 1912.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=22}} It was built on the site of the [[Mutual Street Rink]], used primarily for [[curling]] and [[ice skating]] between [[Dundas Street|Dundas Street East]] and Shuter Street. At the time, it was billed as the largest indoor arena in Canada and held about 7,500 for hockey. The rink was owned by the Toronto Arena Company, organized September 19, 1911, with [[Henry Pellatt|Sir Henry Pellatt]] as president, [[Lol Solman]] as managing director, and directors [[Aemilius Jarvis]], Joseph Kilgour, T.W. Horn, R.A. Smith, and Col. Carlson. There were two other directors from Montreal. W. J. Bellingham was the initial manager.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 10, 1912 |title=Arena in Full Swing; Perfect Sheet of Ice |page=4}}</ref>\n\nThe Arena opened with a performance by Nathan Franko's Orchestra on October 7, 1912, supporting a recital by Alice Neville, soprano of the [[Metropolitan Opera]], tenor Orville Harold and a company of opera singers from the [[Boston Opera Company]] organized by Neville. It was the first of a series called the ''Toronto Music Festival.''<ref name=\"world-opening\">{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 7, 1912 |title=No Confusion Over Arena Tickets |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=hqOjcs7Dif8C&dat=19121007&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |accessdate=August 10, 2011 |page=8}}</ref> Entrances to the various blue and red seating sections were indicated by corresponding blue and red lights on the outside of the building.<ref name=\"world-opening\"/> It was followed the next day by a recital by [[Johanna Gadski]] with Franko's orchestra.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 9, 1912 |page=1 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=g3UDAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uikDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1353%2C2906224 |title=Seven Thousand People Heard Gadski at Arena|accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> The festival continued all week, concluding on October 12 with a variety show headlined by Canadian theatre and film actress [[Marie Dressler]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 12, 1912 |page=8 |title=Marie Dressler Will Appear Tonight |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hnUDAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uikDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2766%2C3392560 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> Americans [[Yvonne de Tr\u00e9ville]], [[Charlotte Maconda]] and [[Rosa Olitzka]] sang arias from several operas while Dressler performed a comedic reading of the poem \"The Glove\" by [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]], singing \"burlesque opera solos\" to the accompaniment of [[Nathan Franko's Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=October 14, 1912 |page=8 |title=Grand Finale of Opera Week}}</ref>\n \nArena Gardens was initially home to two new teams in the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA): the [[Toronto Blueshirts|Toronto Hockey Club]] and the [[Toronto Tecumsehs|Tecumseh Hockey Club]]. Delays in construction meant that the teams could not play in the 1911-12 season, as was originally scheduled. The {{Convert|12|miles}} of piping for the artificial ice was installed improperly and had to be reinstalled in December 1912.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 3, 1912 |title=Rowing Club are to join junior hockey ranks |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 8, 1912 |title=Arena to be ready Monday |page=Sports p. 1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 9, 1912 |title=Arena Opens Today |page=4}}</ref> The first professional ice hockey game in the building was on December 21, 1912, an exhibition between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and [[Montreal Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto World |date=December 23, 1912 |title=Montreal Pros Show Class |page=4}}</ref> [[Sprague Cleghorn]] was suspended for four weeks and fined $65 by the NHA for assaulting the Canadiens' [[Newsy Lalonde]] in the game.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleghorn Fined And Suspended For Assault On Newsy Lalonde |work=Toronto World |date=December 23, 1912 |page=4}}</ref> The first official game was on December 25, 1912, a game between the Canadiens and the Torontos.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} Upon the suspension of the NHA in 1917, the professional franchise of the new [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) for Toronto was operated by the Toronto Arena itself. The franchise was operated by the Arena for two years before being sold to become the [[Toronto St. Patricks]]. The St. Pats became the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in 1927 and played at Arena Gardens until the completion of [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] in 1931. Until 1923, the Arena was the only facility east of [[Manitoba]] with artificial ice-making capability. With this in mind, the St. Pats often let other teams use the Arena as a neutral site during the early and late months of the season, when it was usually too warm for proper ice.{{sfn|Hunter|1997}}\n\nThe year 1922 saw the first professional wrestling bout at the Arena, between former world champion [[Stanislaus Zbyszko]] and Canadian champion George Walker. Professional wrestling would continue at the Arena until 1938. Promoter Ivan Mickailof began promoting weekly shows in 1929. Some of the names that Mickailof presented at the Arena included [[Strangler Lewis]] and [[Toots Mondt]], as well as reigning world champions [[Gus Sonnenberg]], [[Ed Don George]], [[Henri Deglane]], [[Jim Londos]], Ali Baba, Vic Christie, [[Everett Marshall]] and Billy Weidner, who all defended their titles at the Arena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garywill.com/toronto/arenagardens.htm |title=Arena Gardens: Toronto's original wrestling palace (1922-1938) |publisher=garywill.com |accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 1923, the first radio broadcast of an ice hockey game was made from the Arena by the [[Toronto Daily Star]]'s  [[CFCA (AM)|CFCA]] radio station. [[Norman Albert]] did the [[play-by-play]] of the third period of a game between North Toronto and [[Midland, Ontario|Midland]], won by North Toronto 16\u20134.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Star |date=February 9, 1923 |page=12 |author=Albert, Norman |title=Conacher Scored Six for North Toronto}}</ref> Later that season, [[Foster Hewitt]] made his first radio broadcasts from the Arena, also on CFCA. A game on February 14, 1923 featured the [[Toronto St. Pats]] and the [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]], and is the first [[National Hockey League|NHL]] game to be broadcast on radio.{{sfn|Kitchen|2008|p=246}} The [[Stanley Cup]] Final was played at Arena Gardens four times: [[1914 Stanley Cup Finals|1914]], [[1918 Stanley Cup Finals|1918]], [[1920 Stanley Cup Finals|1920]] and [[1922 Stanley Cup Finals|1922]]. Arena Gardens also hosted the [[Memorial Cup]] finals nine times from 1919 to 1931. The Gardens also hosted the [[Allan Cup]] final series.<ref>{{cite news |work=Montreal Gazette |date=March 29, 1930 |page=20 |title=M.A.A.A Confident on Eve of Second Allan Cup Match |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=znAtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M4wFAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=6524%2C4967335 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> A 1931 game between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and the Maple Leafs was filmed by the [[National Film Board of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hockeythenandnow.blogspot.com/2011/04/game-film-circa-1931.html |title=Game Film : Circa 1931 |last=Amodeo |first=Jim |accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Wilfrid Laurier's reception at Liberal meeting, Arena Gardens.jpg|thumb|right|1913 Liberal Party Reception for [[Wilfrid Laurier]] at Arena Gardens]]\n[[File:United Church of Canada inauguration 1925.jpg|thumb|right|Photograph of United Church inaugural service]]\nThe building was also used for mass assemblies. An assembly was held for [[Sir Wilfrid Laurier]] in 1913 by the [[Liberal Party of Canada]]. On June 10, 1925, this building was used as the venue for the inaugural service of the [[United Church of Canada]], which united four existing denominations: the [[Presbyterian Church in Canada|Presbyterian]]s, the [[Methodist Church]] of Canada, the [[Congregational church|Congregational Union of Canada]], and the Association of Local Union Churches. On December 3, 1933, 7,000 persons attended a memorial service for Sir [[Arthur Currie]], commander of the Canadian Corps in World War I.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Star |title=Thousands mourn loss of Canadian Corps commander |date=December 4, 1933 |p=3}}</ref> On October 9, 1936, it was the site of a mass assembly by the [[Communist Party of Canada]].\n\nAfter the Maple Leafs left in 1931, the building no longer was a venue for professional ice hockey but remained open as a venue for sports and entertainment. Some of the other sports included bicycle racing, professional boxing and tennis.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} By 1934, revenues did not keep up with interest on bonds on the property, property taxes and the expenses of operating the arena.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |date=July 28, 1934 |page=16 |title=Summon Meeting of Arena Creditors |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sV4_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4381%2C574007 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> The bondholders made it known that the building was for sale.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |date=September 1, 1934 |page=8 |title=Will Consider Sale of Toronto Arena |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tl4_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4239%2C1291291 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> By 1937, with $200,000 of bonds in default, and  the Arena in default of 1933 and 1934 taxes of nearly $16,000, and a similar amount estimated for 1936 and 1937, the Arena was listed for sale by the City of Toronto.<ref>{{cite news |work=Financial Post of Canada |title=Tax Sale Threatens Toronto Arena Gardens |page=5 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NGc_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=u1MMAAAAIBAJ&dq=arena-gardens&pg=4579%2C194385 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1938, the Arena was leased to Edward \"Ted\" Dickson who turned it into a recreation facility offering ice skating in winter and [[roller skating]] in summer. The name was changed that year to the Mutual Street Arena.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} The [[Glenn Miller]] big band played at the Arena in January 1942, Miller's only appearance in Toronto. [[Frank Sinatra]] made his first appearance in Toronto here in 1949.<ref>{{cite book |title=Let's dance: a celebration of Ontario's dance halls and summer dance pavilions |last=Young |first=Peter |page=23 |year=2002 |isbn=1-896219-02-0}}</ref> [[Roller hockey]] was introduced to the Arena in the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The Billboard |date=March 6, 1948 |page=80 |title=Toronto's Hell on Wheels Paying Off at Box Office}}</ref> [[Hank Williams Sr]] played a concert at the Arena in 1952. The city's first boat show was held in 1954. The ''Melody Fair'' theatre-in-the-round operated at the Arena in 1954.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}}\n\nDickson bought the building in 1945 and it remained in the family for the next 43 years. The arena was renovated for $3 million in 1962, adding 18 [[curling]] sheets, year-round roller skating, a parking garage and a new facade.{{sfn|Filey|1989|p=23}} The Arena was renamed \"The Terrace\", a name it kept until it was sold in 1988. It closed its doors on April 30, 1989 and was demolished a few months later. The site was converted into a residential development with some of the site reserved for a city park. The Terrace name was retained for one of the residential buildings. In May 2011, the name of the city park on the site was changed from ''Cathedral Square Park'' to ''Arena Gardens''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2011/te/bgrd/backgroundfile-37996.pdf |title=Proposed renaming of Cathedral Square Park to \"Arena Gardens\" |author=Brenda Patterson, General Manager, Parks, Forestry and Recreation |date=May 4, 2011 |work=Staff Report |publisher=City of Toronto  |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\nThis list is incomplete.\n* October 7, 1912 - Grand opening\n* March 14\u201319, 1914 - Toronto Blueshirts \u2013 Victoria Aristocrats Stanley Cup series\n* March 20\u201330, 1918 - Torontos - Vancouver Millionaires Stanley Cup series\n* March 30\u2013April 1, 1920 - Two games of Ottawa Senators - Seattle Metropolitans Stanley Cup series\n* March 17\u201328, 1922 - Toronto St. Patricks - Vancouver Millionaires Stanley Cup series\n* February 8, 1923 - First radio broadcast of an ice hockey game\n* February 14, 1923 - First radio broadcast of an NHL game\n* June 10, 1925 - Inaugural service of United Church of Canada\n* December 3, 1933 - Memorial service for Sir Arthur Currie\n* January 23, 1942 - Only Toronto appearance by Glenn Miller and big band\n* May 6, 1952 - concert by Hank Williams Sr and the Grand Ole Opry Show.\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons cat|Mutual Street Arena}}\n* [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n* [[Air Canada Centre]]\n* [[Ricoh Coliseum]]\n* [[Varsity Arena]]\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Hewitt, Foster |title=Foster Hewitt: His Own Story |publisher=Ryerson Press |location=Toronto, Ontario |year=1967 |ref=harv}}\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Mike Filey |author=Filey, Mike |title=Like no other in the world: the story of the Toronto' Skydome |year=1989 |publisher=Sun Controlled Ventures |location=Toronto, Ontario |isbn=0-919233-31-7 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/likenootherinwor0000file }}\n*{{cite book |title=Champions: The Illustrated History of Hockey's Greatest Dynasties |last=Hunter |first=Douglas |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1997 |publisher=Triumph Books |location=[[Chicago]] |isbn=1-57243-213-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |author=Kitchen, Paul |title=Win, Lose or Wrangle: The Inside Story of the Old Ottawa Senators - 1883-1935 |publisher=Penumbra Press |location=Manotick, Ontario |year=2008 |ref=harv}}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hockey.ballparks.com/NHL/TorontoMapleLeafs/oldindex.htm Ballparks: Mutual Street Arena]\n* [http://www.garywill.com/toronto/arenagardens.htm Arena Gardens: Toronto's original wrestling palace (1922-1938)]\n* [http://www.tmlfever.com/MUTUALSTREETARENA.html TMLfever: Mutual Street Arena]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the<br>[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Toronto Arenas/St. Pats/Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1917 &ndash; 1931\n | before = first arena\n | after = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Blueshirts}}\n{{Former NHL arenas}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1912]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1989]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blueshirts]]\n[[Category:Toronto Tecumsehs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Marlboros]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "PKT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_Street_Arena"}
{"title_page": "Univa Grid Engine", "text_new": "{{short description|Batch-queuing system to schedule resources in a data center}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title                  = \n| name                   = Univa Grid Engine Software\n| logo                   = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| logo caption           = \n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Univa]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = 8.6.11\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|03|17|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n| genre                  = [[Grid computing]] [[Supercomputing]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] [[commercial software]]<ref>[http://www.univa.com/resources/licenses/univa-support-and-term-software Univa Support and Term Software license]</ref>\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|www.univa.com/products}}\n}}\n'''[[Univa]] Grid Engine''' is a [[batch-queuing system]], forked from [[Sun Grid Engine]] (SGE).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcinthecloud.com/features/Grid-Engine-Finds-Safe-Harbor-in-Univa-114125534.html | title=Grid Engine Finds Safe Harbor at Univa | work=HPC in the Cloud | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Gentzsch, Wolfgang}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/01/18/univa_forks_oracle_grid_engine/ | title=Univa forks Oracle's Sun Grid Engine | work=The Register | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Morgan, Timothy Prickett}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | title=Univa Rescues Grid Engine From Oracle | work=HPCwire | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Feldman, Michael | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124052006/http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | archive-date=January 24, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The software schedules resources in a [[data center]] and applies policy management tools. The product can be deployed to run on-premises, using [[cloud computing]] or in a hybrid cloud environment.\n\n== History ==\nThe roots of Grid Engine as a commercial product date back to 1993 (under the names CODINE and later, in a variation of the product, GRD). A more comprehensive genealogy of the product is described in [[Sun Grid Engine]]. Grid Engine was first distributed by Genias Software and from 1999, after a company merger, by Gridware, Inc. In 2000, [[Sun Microsystems]] acquired Gridware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2000-07/sunflash.20000724.3.xml|title=Gridware's resource management software increases efficiency and productivity in compute-intensive technical computing environments|date=2000-07-24|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>  Sun renamed CODINE/GRD as Sun Grid Engine later that year, and released it as [[open-source software|open-source]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2001-07/sunflash.20010723.1.xml|title=Sun Microsystems makes SUN GRID ENGINE software available to open source community|date=2001-07-23|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] acquired Sun and thus renamed SGE to [[Oracle Grid Engine]].  The Oracle Grid Engine 6.2u6 source code was not included with the binaries, and changes were not put back to the project's source repository.  In response to this, the Grid Engine community started the ''Open Grid Scheduler'' and the ''Son of Grid Engine'' projects to continue to develop and maintain a free implementation of Grid Engine.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/gridscheduler/ Open Grid Scheduler]</ref><ref>[https://arc.liv.ac.uk/trac/SGE Son of Grid Engine]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-mag.com/id/7850|title=The State of Oracle/Sun Grid Engine|first=Douglas|last=Eadline, Ph.D.|date=September 1, 2010|accessdate=2011-01-18|publisher=Linux Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmail.org/message/hcxond5s4cywe5dv|title=Changes for a Bright Future at Oracle|first=Daniel|last=Templeton|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, [[Univa]] announced that it had hired the principal engineers from the Sun Grid Engine team.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/| title=Univa Acquires Grid Engine Expertise | publisher=Univa | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  Univa Grid Engine development is led by CTO Fritz Ferstl, who founded the Grid Engine project and ran the business within Sun/Oracle for the past 10 years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/about/| title=Biography of Fritz Ferstl | publisher=Univa | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2013 [[Univa]] announced that it had acquired Oracle Grid Engine assets and intellectual property making it the sole commercial provider of Grid Engine software.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2013/10222013.php| title=Univa completes acquisition of Grid Engine assets | publisher=Univa | date=2013-10-22 | accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2018 [[Univa]] announced massive scalability operating a single cluster with over 1 million cores on [[Amazon Web Services|AWS]].<ref>{{cite blog | url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/06/univa-demonstrates-extreme-scale-automation-by-deploying-more-than-one-million-cores-in-a-single-univa-grid-engine-cluster-using-aws/ | title=Univa Demonstrates Extreme Scale Automation by Deploying More Than One Million Cores in a Single Univa Grid Engine Cluster using AWS | publisher=Univa | date=2018-06-24 | accessdate=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0 was the first version, released on April 12, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110412005977/en/Univa-Grid-Engine-8.0 | title=Univa Grid Engine 8.0 Now Available | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  It was [[Fork (software development)|forked]] from SGE 6.2u5, the last open source release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wheregridenginelives.com/content/rebirth-continuity-and-expansion-univa-grid-engine-v80 | title=Rebirth, Continuity and Expansion - Univa Grid Engine v8.0 | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Ferstl, Fritz}}</ref>  It adds improved third party application integration, license and policy management, enhanced support for software and hardware platforms, and cloud management tools.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0.1 was released on October 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/news/| title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap | publisher=Univa | date=2011-10-04 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>  It adds improved support for multi-core hardware, integration with NVIDIA GPUs, new job submission verifier extensions, and additional bug fixes.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.0 has been announced on May 2 and has updated it to the latest release level 8.1.3 in Nov 15 2012. The 8.1.x releases deliver important new functionality such as Job Classes, PostGres Spooling, Resource Maps, Fair Urgency, deterministic Wildcard PE Selection, improved Diagnostics, pre-configured MPI integations and improved Apache Hadoop Integration <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/resources/| title=Univa Grid Engine Integration for Hadoop | publisher=Univa}}</ref> as well as many bug fixes and performance improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.6 has been announced on Oct 14, 2013. The update include improvements to the Grid Engine scheduler for larger clusters and Qmaster stability improvements for spooling and qalter commands.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.2.0 was released on Sept 02, 2014. The new Univa Grid Engine version 8.2 includes native Windows support .\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.0 was released on June 22, 2015. The new Preemption feature in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 allows users to set priorities on different work so that, if a higher priority application must use resources currently allocated to a lower priority application, the lower priority application will effectively be \u201cpaused\u201d\u2014not lost\u2014and work will automatically resume once the higher priority application is completed. Among a handful of other new features added to Grid Engine 8.3.0 to improve the overall reliability and efficiency of the cluster, is the new Run Time Modification of Resources feature. The Run Time Modification of Resources feature means much more efficient use of cluster resources.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.1 was released on August 28, 2015. This release contained all of the new features in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 and additional fixes and enhancements identified since the release of 8.3.0.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.4.0 was released on May 31, 2016. This release supports [[Docker (software)|Docker]] containers and will automatically dispatch and run jobs with a user specified Docker Image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2016/05312016.php|title=New Version of Univa Grid Engine|last=univa|website=www.univa.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.5.0 was released on March 7, 2017. This release of Univa Grid Engine is 2x faster than open source Grid Engine 6.2u5. Grid Engine 8.5.0 also includes significant improvement to Docker support including mobility of GPU apps within the cluster.\n\n8.6.0 was released on July 17, 2018. Univa Grid Engine now supports NVIDIA Docker 2.0. The new Univa Grid Engine Docker integration allows for more flexibility when running Docker containers in a Univa Grid Engine environment.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.1 was released on August 8, 2018, providing improved control over GPU devices, and new affinity features, allowing jobs to gravitate towards, or away from, certain compute nodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/08/introducing-univa-grid-engine-8-6-1-next-level-enterprise-grade-workload-management/|title=Introducing Univa Grid Engine 8.6.1: Next-Level Enterprise Grade Workload Management|website=blogs.univa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n\n8.6.2 was released on August 16, 2018. Univa Grid Engine performance and scalability has been improved in several key areas: network communications, job submission, memory allocation, and scheduler optimizations. This update also improved Univa Grid Engine job dispatch information.\n\n8.6.3 was released on September 27, 2018. The new update provided bulk configuration changes for Univa Grid Engine hosts. The new bulk configuration commands perform operations on many hosts simultaneously, which makes it easier to manage a large Univa Grid Engine cluster.\n\n8.6.4 was released on November 23, 2018, providing new core binding strategies to make it easier to distribute nodes and cores for jobs while also providing more flexibility. A new affinity-based job placement policy was included in this update. Jobs submitted using an affinity will either be packed close together with a \u201cpositive affinity\u201d or \u201cnegative affinity\u201d across the cluster, based on the resources requested. A new Univa Grid Engine Resource Maps can now control access to host devices such as NVIDIA GPUs. This allows jobs to request GPUs and that GPU is exclusively assigned to the job. Univa Grid Engine now also directly communicates with NVIDIA Data Center GPU Manager to collect GPU metrics for scheduling and accounting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.5 was released on May 6, 2019. The new key features are:\n\n* Support for IBM Power 9 on Linux\n* Many improvements to Docker support on Univa Grid Engine including supporting the latest Docker versions\n* Very large cluster hostname management where IP for host is contained in the hostname\n* Integration with Linux Out of Memory (OOM) Notification API ensuring that Univa Grid Engine is automatically notified of jobs that are terminated by the Linux kernel\n* Improved responsiveness in heavily loaded cluster for Grid Engine administrator commands\n* Performance improvements to Univa Grid Engine automatic job rescheduling\n* Thread deadlock detection for Univa Grid Engine qmaster\n* Updated support for NVIDIA DCGM versions up to 1.6.3\n* GPU/CPU affinity can be specified as a hard or soft request\n\n8.6.7 was released on August 5, 2019. Among the numerous enhancements, Univa Grid Engine 8.6.7 offers Red Hat Linux 8 support and NVIDIA GPU DCGM job usage.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.9 was released on February 10, 2020. It included enhancements made to qconf and improved information and messaging collection.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.11 was released on March 17, 2020. Among the many enhancements, this version delivers improved Docker compatibility, job reporting and monitoring and increased support for the latest version of DCGM.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Job scheduler#Batch queuing for HPC clusters|Job Scheduler and Batch Queuing for Clusters]]\n<!-- sort alphabetically: -->\n* [[Beowulf cluster]]\n* [[Maui Cluster Scheduler]]\n* [[Open Source Cluster Application Resources]] (OSCAR)\n* [[Slurm Workload Manager]]\n* [[TORQUE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.univa.com/products/}}\n* [http://linuxappfinder.com/package/gridengine pointer to repository for old Debian and Ubuntu packages]\n\n[[Category:Grid computing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Batch-queuing system to schedule resources in a data center}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title                  = \n| name                   = Univa Grid Engine Software\n| logo                   = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| logo caption           = \n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Univa]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = 8.6.11\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|03|17|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n| genre                  = [[Grid computing]] [[Supercomputing]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] [[commercial software]]<ref>[http://www.univa.com/resources/licenses/univa-support-and-term-software Univa Support and Term Software license]</ref>\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|www.univa.com/products}}\n}}\n'''[[Univa]] Grid Engine''' is a [[batch-queuing system]], forked from [[Sun Grid Engine]] (SGE).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcinthecloud.com/features/Grid-Engine-Finds-Safe-Harbor-in-Univa-114125534.html | title=Grid Engine Finds Safe Harbor at Univa | work=HPC in the Cloud | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Gentzsch, Wolfgang}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/01/18/univa_forks_oracle_grid_engine/ | title=Univa forks Oracle's Sun Grid Engine | work=The Register | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Morgan, Timothy Prickett}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | title=Univa Rescues Grid Engine From Oracle | work=HPCwire | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Feldman, Michael | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124052006/http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | archive-date=January 24, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The software schedules resources in a [[data center]] and applies policy management tools. The product can be deployed to run on-premises, using [[cloud computing]] or in a hybrid cloud environment.\n\n== History ==\nThe roots of Grid Engine as a commercial product date back to 1993 (under the names CODINE and later, in a variation of the product, GRD). A more comprehensive genealogy of the product is described in [[Sun Grid Engine]]. Grid Engine was first distributed by Genias Software and from 1999, after a company merger, by Gridware, Inc. In 2000, [[Sun Microsystems]] acquired Gridware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2000-07/sunflash.20000724.3.xml|title=Gridware's resource management software increases efficiency and productivity in compute-intensive technical computing environments|date=2000-07-24|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>  Sun renamed CODINE/GRD as Sun Grid Engine later that year, and released it as [[open-source software|open-source]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2001-07/sunflash.20010723.1.xml|title=Sun Microsystems makes SUN GRID ENGINE software available to open source community|date=2001-07-23|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] acquired Sun and thus renamed SGE to [[Oracle Grid Engine]].  The Oracle Grid Engine 6.2u6 source code was not included with the binaries, and changes were not put back to the project's source repository.  In response to this, the Grid Engine community started the ''Open Grid Scheduler'' and the ''Son of Grid Engine'' projects to continue to develop and maintain a free implementation of Grid Engine.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/gridscheduler/ Open Grid Scheduler]</ref><ref>[https://arc.liv.ac.uk/trac/SGE Son of Grid Engine]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-mag.com/id/7850|title=The State of Oracle/Sun Grid Engine|first=Douglas|last=Eadline, Ph.D.|date=September 1, 2010|accessdate=2011-01-18|publisher=Linux Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmail.org/message/hcxond5s4cywe5dv|title=Changes for a Bright Future at Oracle|first=Daniel|last=Templeton|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, [[Univa]] announced that it had hired the principal engineers from the Sun Grid Engine team.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/| title=Univa Acquires Grid Engine Expertise | publisher=Univa | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  Univa Grid Engine development is led by CTO Fritz Ferstl, who founded the Grid Engine project and ran the business within Sun/Oracle for the past 10 years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/about/| title=Biography of Fritz Ferstl | publisher=Univa | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2013 [[Univa]] announced that it had acquired Oracle Grid Engine assets and intellectual property making it the sole commercial provider of Grid Engine software.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2013/10222013.php| title=Univa completes acquisition of Grid Engine assets | publisher=Univa | date=2013-10-22 | accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2018 [[Univa]] announced massive scalability operating a single cluster with over 1 million cores on [[Amazon Web Services|AWS]].<ref>{{cite blog | url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/06/univa-demonstrates-extreme-scale-automation-by-deploying-more-than-one-million-cores-in-a-single-univa-grid-engine-cluster-using-aws/ | title=Univa Demonstrates Extreme Scale Automation by Deploying More Than One Million Cores in a Single Univa Grid Engine Cluster using AWS | publisher=Univa | date=2018-06-24 | accessdate=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0 was the first version, released on April 12, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110412005977/en/Univa-Grid-Engine-8.0 | title=Univa Grid Engine 8.0 Now Available | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  It was [[Fork (software development)|forked]] from SGE 6.2u5, the last open source release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wheregridenginelives.com/content/rebirth-continuity-and-expansion-univa-grid-engine-v80 | title=Rebirth, Continuity and Expansion - Univa Grid Engine v8.0 | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Ferstl, Fritz}}</ref>  It adds improved third party application integration, license and policy management, enhanced support for software and hardware platforms, and cloud management tools.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0.1 was released on October 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/news/| title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap | publisher=Univa | date=2011-10-04 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>  It adds improved support for multi-core hardware, integration with NVIDIA GPUs, new job submission verifier extensions, and additional bug fixes.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.0 has been announced on May 2 and has updated it to the latest release level 8.1.3 in Nov 15 2012. The 8.1.x releases deliver important new functionality such as Job Classes, PostGres Spooling, Resource Maps, Fair Urgency, deterministic Wildcard PE Selection, improved Diagnostics, pre-configured MPI integations and improved Apache Hadoop Integration <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/resources/| title=Univa Grid Engine Integration for Hadoop | publisher=Univa}}</ref> as well as many bug fixes and performance improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.6 has been announced on Oct 14, 2013. The update include improvements to the Grid Engine scheduler for larger clusters and Qmaster stability improvements for spooling and qalter commands.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.2.0 was released on Sept 02, 2014. The new Univa Grid Engine version 8.2 includes native Windows support .\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.0 was released on June 22, 2015. The new Preemption feature in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 allows users to set priorities on different work so that, if a higher priority application must use resources currently allocated to a lower priority application, the lower priority application will effectively be \u201cpaused\u201d\u2014not lost\u2014and work will automatically resume once the higher priority application is completed. Among a handful of other new features added to Grid Engine 8.3.0 to improve the overall reliability and efficiency of the cluster, is the new Run Time Modification of Resources feature. The Run Time Modification of Resources feature means much more efficient use of cluster resources.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.1 was released on August 28, 2015. This release contained all of the new features in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 and additional fixes and enhancements identified since the release of 8.3.0.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.4.0 was released on May 31, 2016. This release supports [[Docker (software)|Docker]] containers and will automatically dispatch and run jobs with a user specified Docker Image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2016/05312016.php|title=New Version of Univa Grid Engine|last=univa|website=www.univa.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.5.0 was released on March 7, 2017. This release of Univa Grid Engine is 2x faster than open source Grid Engine 6.2u5. Grid Engine 8.5.0 also includes significant improvement to Docker support including mobility of GPU apps within the cluster.\n\n8.6.0 was released on July 17, 2018. Univa Grid Engine now supports NVIDIA Docker 2.0. The new Univa Grid Engine Docker integration allows for more flexibility when running Docker containers in a Univa Grid Engine environment.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.1 was released on August 8, 2018, providing improved control over GPU devices, and new affinity features, allowing jobs to gravitate towards, or away from, certain compute nodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/08/introducing-univa-grid-engine-8-6-1-next-level-enterprise-grade-workload-management/|title=Introducing Univa Grid Engine 8.6.1: Next-Level Enterprise Grade Workload Management|website=blogs.univa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n\n8.6.2 was released on August 16, 2018. Univa Grid Engine performance and scalability has been improved in several key areas: network communications, job submission, memory allocation, and scheduler optimizations. This update also improved Univa Grid Engine job dispatch information.\n\n8.6.3 was released on September 27, 2018. The new update provided bulk configuration changes for Univa Grid Engine hosts. The new bulk configuration commands perform operations on many hosts simultaneously, which makes it easier to manage a large Univa Grid Engine cluster.\n\n8.6.4 was released on November 23, 2018, providing new core binding strategies to make it easier to distribute nodes and cores for jobs while also providing more flexibility. A new affinity-based job placement policy was included in this update. Jobs submitted using an affinity will either be packed close together with a \u201cpositive affinity\u201d or \u201cnegative affinity\u201d across the cluster, based on the resources requested. A new Univa Grid Engine Resource Maps can now control access to host devices such as NVIDIA GPUs. This allows jobs to request GPUs and that GPU is exclusively assigned to the job. Univa Grid Engine now also directly communicates with NVIDIA Data Center GPU Manager to collect GPU metrics for scheduling and accounting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.5 was released on May 6, 2019. The new key features are:\n\n* Support for IBM Power 9 on Linux\n* Many improvements to Docker support on Univa Grid Engine including supporting the latest Docker versions\n* Very large cluster hostname management where IP for host is contained in the hostname\n* Integration with Linux Out of Memory (OOM) Notification API ensuring that Univa Grid Engine is automatically notified of jobs that are terminated by the Linux kernel\n* Improved responsiveness in heavily loaded cluster for Grid Engine administrator commands\n* Performance improvements to Univa Grid Engine automatic job rescheduling\n* Thread deadlock detection for Univa Grid Engine qmaster\n* Updated support for NVIDIA DCGM versions up to 1.6.3\n* GPU/CPU affinity can be specified as a hard or soft request\n\n8.6.7 was released on August 5, 2019. Among the numerous enhancements, Univa Grid Engine 8.6.7 offers Red Hat Linux 8 support and NVIDIA GPU DCGM job usage.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Job scheduler#Batch queuing for HPC clusters|Job Scheduler and Batch Queuing for Clusters]]\n<!-- sort alphabetically: -->\n* [[Beowulf cluster]]\n* [[Maui Cluster Scheduler]]\n* [[Open Source Cluster Application Resources]] (OSCAR)\n* [[Slurm Workload Manager]]\n* [[TORQUE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.univa.com/products/}}\n* [http://linuxappfinder.com/package/gridengine pointer to repository for old Debian and Ubuntu packages]\n\n[[Category:Grid computing]]\n", "name_user": "Nbendov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReleases", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univa_Grid_Engine"}
{"title_page": "Cleon F. Thompson", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Dr. Cleon F. Thompson\n| image        =\n| order        = 7th\n| title        = Chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]]\n| term_start   = 1980\n| term_end     = 1981\n| predecessor  = [[Lewis C. Dowdy]]\n| successor    = [[Edward B. Fort]]\n| order2       = 8th\n| title2       = Chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]\n| term_start2  = 1985\n| term_end2    = 1995\n| predecessor2 = Haywood L. Wilson\n| successor2   = Gerald McCants\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| alma_mater   = [[North Carolina Central University]]<br>[[Duke University]]\n| profession   = Educator\n| spouse       = Edwina White Thompson\n}}\n'''Cleon Franklin Thompson Jr.''' is an [[United States|American]] [[educator]] best known for holding office as the seventh chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]] and the eighth chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]].\n\n== Early life and education==\nThompson was born in [[New York City|New York, New York]], but received his public school education in [[Bennettsville, South Carolina|Bennettsville]], [[South Carolina]]. Thompson attended [[North Carolina Central University]], where he earned the [[Bachelor of Science]] and the [[Master of Science]] degrees in [[biology]]. In 1977, he would go on to earn his Doctor of Education Administration from [[Duke University]], with minor degrees in [[political science]], [[economics]], and educational law.<ref name=Chancellors>{{cite web|title=Presidents & Chancellors|url=http://www.library.ncat.edu/resources/archives/leaders.html|work=F.D. Bluford Library at NC A&T State University|publisher=NC A&T State University|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduation from North Carolina Central University, Thompson worked in a number of capacities at several institutions. From 1956 to 1960, he worked as a senior research assistant at the Medical School at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]; from 1960-1961 he was an assistant professor of biology at [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University|North Carolina A&T State University]]; from 1961-1965 he was assistant professor and acting chairman of the Biology Department at [[Tuskegee University]]; and from 1965-1983 he served as a professor of biology, chairman of the Division of Natural Science, vice president for academic affairs, provost, and finally as acting president of [[Shaw University]].<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\">{{cite web|title=Cleon Franklin Thompson Jr.|url=http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/presidents-chancellors/cleon-f-thompson-jr.aspx|work=C.G. O'Kelly Library Archives website|publisher=Winston-Salem State University|accessdate=21 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220729/http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/presidents-chancellors/cleon-f-thompson-jr.aspx|archivedate=27 May 2014}}</ref> During his tenure at Shaw University, Thompson befriended former [[Governor of North Carolina]], and President of [[Duke University]], [[Terry Sanford]]. It was Sanford who encouraged Thompson to enroll in a doctoral program at Duke University, which had been developed to train potential college presidents. As a part of a class assignment, Thompson interviewed former [[University of North Carolina]] President [[William Friday]]. Friday was so impressed with Thompson that he offered him a part-time job in the department.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/> In 1975, Thompson was appointed Vice President for Student Services and Special Programs of the [[University of North Carolina]], and began the process of resolving the university's desegregation dispute with the federal government.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/>\n\nOn November 1, 1980, Thompson was appointed as interim Chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]], where he served for one year.<ref name=Chancellors/> In 1985, partially upon the recommendation of Dr. Friday, Thompson was selected as the 8th chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]. The Thompson administration focused on the improvements of academics  through the recruitment of quality faculty, improvement of admission requirements for students, enhancement of the general studies program, and working to meet and surpass accreditation standards. In addition, the school of nursing was revitalized, the university increased its focus on undergraduate research; and collaborations were established within the private sector, government, and fellow universities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2012|title=Accelerating Growth|url=http://issuu.com/wssuarchway/docs/archway_summer2012_now/11|journal=WSSU Archway Magazine|volume=12|issue=2|page=11|accessdate=23 May 2014|via=}}</ref> In 1995, Thompson concluded ten years of service to the university upon his resignation to continue work within the University of North Carolina System.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Cleon F. Thompson center, on the campus of Winston-Salem State is named in his Honor. Completed in 1996, the Thompson Center houses the university's post office, bookstore, Financial Aid Department, Registrars Office, Office of Admissions, Division of Student Affairs, and Kennedy Dining Hall.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Archives\">{{cite web|title=Cleon F. Thompson Center|url=http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/buildings/thompson-center-m.aspx|work=C.G. O'kelly Library Archives website|publisher=Winston-Salem State University|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220608/http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/buildings/thompson-center-m.aspx|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before = Haywood L. Wilson\n| title  = {{nowrap|Chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]}}\n| after  = Gerald McCants\n| years  = 1985-1995\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Lewis C. Dowdy]]\n| title  = {{nowrap|[[List of Leaders of North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University|Chancellor of the North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]]}}\n| after  = [[Edward B. Fort]]\n| years  = 1980-1981\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{N.C. A&T leaders |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Cleon F.}}\n[[Category:North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University leaders]]\n[[Category:Winston-Salem State University]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina administrators]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Central University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Dr. Cleon F. Thompson\n| image        =\n| order        = 7th\n| title        = Chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]]\n| term_start   = 1980\n| term_end     = 1981\n| predecessor  = [[Lewis C. Dowdy]]\n| successor    = [[Edward B. Fort]]\n| order2       = 8th\n| title2       = Chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]\n| term_start2  = 1985\n| term_end2    = 1995\n| predecessor2 = Haywood L. Wilson\n| successor2   = Gerald McCants\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| alma_mater   = [[North Carolina Central University]]<br>[[Duke University]]\n| profession   = Educator\n| spouse       = Edwina White Thompson\n}}\n'''Cleon Franklin Thompson Jr.''' is an [[United States|American]] [[educator]] best known for holding office as the seventh chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]] and the eighth chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]].\n\n== Early life and education==\nThompson was born in [[New York City|New York, New York]], but received his public school education in [[Bennettsville, South Carolina|Bennettsville]], [[South Carolina]]. Thompson attended [[North Carolina Central University]], where he earned the [[Bachelor of Science]] and the [[Master of Science]] degrees in [[biology]]. In 1977, he would go on to earn his Doctor of Education Administration from [[Duke University]], with minor degrees in [[political science]], [[economics]], and educational law.<ref name=Chancellors>{{cite web|title=Presidents & Chancellors|url=http://www.library.ncat.edu/resources/archives/leaders.html|work=F.D. Bluford Library at NC A&T State University|publisher=NC A&T State University|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduation from North Carolina Central University, Thompson worked in a number of capacities at several institutions. From 1956 to 1960, he worked as a senior research assistant at the Medical School at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]; from 1960-1961 he was an assistant professor of biology at [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University|North Carolina A&T State University]]; from 1961-1965 he was assistant professor and acting chairman of the Biology Department at [[Tuskegee University]]; and from 1965-1983 he served as a professor of biology, chairman of the Division of Natural Science, vice president for academic affairs, provost, and finally as acting president of [[Shaw University]].<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\">{{cite web|title=Cleon Franklin Thompson Jr.|url=http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/presidents-chancellors/cleon-f-thompson-jr.aspx|work=C.G. O'Kelly Library Archives website|publisher=Winston-Salem State University|accessdate=21 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220729/http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/presidents-chancellors/cleon-f-thompson-jr.aspx|archivedate=27 May 2014}}</ref> During his tenure at Shaw University, Thompson befriended former [[Governor of North Carolina]], and President of [[Duke University]], [[Terry Sanford]]. It was Sanford who encouraged Thompson to enroll in a doctoral program at Duke University, which had been developed to train potential college presidents. As a part of a class assignment, Thompson interviewed former [[University of North Carolina]] President [[William Friday]]. Friday was so impressed with Thompson that he offered him a part-time job in the department.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/> In 1975, Thompson was appointed Vice President for Student Services and Special Programs of the [[University of North Carolina]], and began the process of resolving the university\u2019s desegregation dispute with the federal government.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/>\n\nOn November 1, 1980, Thompson was appointed as interim Chancellor of [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]], where he served for one year.<ref name=Chancellors/> In 1985, partially upon the recommendation of Dr. Friday, Thompson was selected as the 8th chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]. The Thompson administration focused on the improvements of academics  through the recruitment of quality faculty, improvement of admission requirements for students, enhancement of the general studies program, and working to meet and surpass accreditation standards. In addition, the school of nursing was revitalized, the university increased its focus on undergraduate research; and collaborations were established within the private sector, government, and fellow universities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2012|title=Accelerating Growth|url=http://issuu.com/wssuarchway/docs/archway_summer2012_now/11|journal=WSSU Archway Magazine|volume=12|issue=2|page=11|accessdate=23 May 2014|via=}}</ref> In 1995, Thompson concluded ten years of service to the university upon his resignation to continue work within the University of North Carolina System.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Library\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Cleon F. Thompson center, on the campus of Winston-Salem State is named in his Honor. Completed in 1996, the Thompson Center houses the university's post office, bookstore, Financial Aid Department, Registrars Office, Office of Admissions, Division of Student Affairs, and Kennedy Dining Hall.<ref name=\"O'Kelly Archives\">{{cite web|title=Cleon F. Thompson Center|url=http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/buildings/thompson-center-m.aspx|work=C.G. O'kelly Library Archives website|publisher=Winston-Salem State University|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220608/http://www.wssu.edu/cg-okelly-library/services/archives/core/buildings/thompson-center-m.aspx|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before = Haywood L. Wilson\n| title  = {{nowrap|Chancellor of [[Winston-Salem State University]]}}\n| after  = Gerald McCants\n| years  = 1985-1995\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Lewis C. Dowdy]]\n| title  = {{nowrap|[[List of Leaders of North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University|Chancellor of the North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]]}}\n| after  = [[Edward B. Fort]]\n| years  = 1980-1981\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{N.C. A&T leaders |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Cleon F.}}\n[[Category:North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University leaders]]\n[[Category:Winston-Salem State University]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina administrators]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Central University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleon_F._Thompson"}
{"title_page": "SS Pere Marquette", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:SS ''Pere Marquette''}}\n[[File:Pere Marquette carferry 1896.jpg|thumb|upright 1.0|''Pere Marquette'' carferry <br/> being launched in 1896]]\nThe '''SS ''Pere Marquette''''' (also '''''Pere Marquette 15''''') was the world's first steel [[train ferry]]. It sailed on [[Lake Michigan]] and provided service between the ports of [[Ludington, Michigan]], and [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]], for the [[Pere Marquette Railway]] from 1897 to 1930. The railway used the named ''Pere Marquette'' for many of its ships and ferries, adding a number to the end of the name. \n\n==Railroad car ferry==\n[[File:SS Pere Marquette propeller.jpg|thumb|upright 1.0|Carferry propeller (<small>''Pere Marquette 10''</small>) at Ludington harbor compared to 6 foot tall man]]\nThe carferry was built by the [[Frank W. Wheeler|Wheeler Shipyards]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], in 1896 at a cost of $300,000. The vessel was built for the [[Flint and Pere Marquette Railroad]] and complete when launched, except for a few finishing items needed for the cabins. It left Bay City on December 30, 1896, and arrived first in Milwaukee for a day's public inspection.<ref name=PublicInspec> {{cite web |url=http://www.carferries.com/pm/PM15/ |title= Pere Marquette 15 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2005 |website=The Carferries of the Great Lakes |publisher= M. Hanley |access-date= June 21, 2017 |quote=}} </ref> It then continued onto Ludington from there and arrived on January 13, 1897. The ship had split cabins, one in front of the smoke stacks and one behind them. They provided [[Berth (sleeping)|sleeping berth]]s for the officers and ten passengers.<ref name=SteelCarferry> {{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Paul S. |date=March 18, 1997 |title=First steel carferry is the Pere Marquette |url= |work=[[Ludington Daily News]] |department = Steam & Steel Section B |page=3 |access-date=}} </ref>\n\nThe steamship was {{convert|350|feet}} long and {{convert|56|feet}} wide. It measured 2,443 [[gross register tons]] and had two twelve foot propellers for its driving force. There were two compound engines that produced 2,500 horsepower.<ref>*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Keefe |first = William Ford |title = Voices from Sweetwater Seas |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=InrhAAAAMAAJ |year =  1998 |publisher = Action Research Institute |isbn = 978-0-9635609-8-8 |page = 283 }}</ref> The ship had electricity from stem to stern that was controlled at the pilot house.  The inside deck had four railroad tracks with a capacity of 30 freight [[boxcar]]s. Fully loaded the carferry had a displacement of some 4,050 tons on a {{convert|12.25|foot}} draft of water. The vessel traveled in both the summer and winter and was capable of handling severe gales.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Simmons-Boardman|first=|title=Marine Engineering/log|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxM4AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA6|year=1897|publisher=Simmons-Boardman Publishing Corporation |page = 6 }}</ref> Its hull was constructed to break up heavy ice.<ref name=IceBreaker> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Marine History|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11901053/ |work=Daily News |location=Ludington, Michigan |date=June 24, 1943 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] }}</ref> It was unique in that it was first steel train ferry constructed in the world.<ref name=WorldFirst> {{cite news |last=Mac Loren |first=Agnes |date=January 4, 1957 |title=This & That from History |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11699276/ |work= Ludington Daily News |page= 2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |quote=The Pere Marquette, which was the widest steamer on the Great Lakes, was the first steel carferry in the world.}}</ref><ref name=WorldHistoryFirst> {{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 13, 1943 |title=Sunday Marks 45th Birthday of World's First Steel Carferry |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11699668/the_ludington_daily_news/ |work=  Ludington Daily News |page = 1  |via= Newspapers.com }}</ref><ref name=Stem&Steel> {{cite news |last=MacLaren |first=Agnes |date=February 19, 1952 |title= First steel Carferry made Maiden Voyage 55 Years Ago Today |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11759864/|work=Ludington Daily News |via= Newspapers.com |quote=Fifty five years ago, on Feb 19, 1897, there steamed out of Ludington's harbor the first steel carferry in the world, departing on her maiden voyage. }}</ref><ref name=\"Bagley\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-06-07/columns/053.html |title=Autos Across Mackinac: Pere Marquette Makes New Home in St. Ignace |work=[[St. Ignace News]] |first1=Les |last1=Bagley |date=June 7, 2007 |accessdate=July 9, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002948/http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-06-07/columns/053.html |archivedate=July 29, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe vessel carried railroad cars and passengers and went into service as a cross-lake train ferry going across Lake Michigan. It made its official maiden voyage from Ludington to Manitowoc on the night of February 16, 1897. It carried 22 railroad freight boxcars and traveled all night at a speed of 14 knots and arrived at its destination at 7:00 A.M. on February 17, 1897.<ref>{{cite book |last = Hilton |first = George Woodman |title = The Great Lakes Car Ferries |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=x1BjhmhfFeoC |date =  2003 |publisher = Montevallo Historical Press |isbn = 978-0-9658624-3-1 |page = 117 |ref = harv }}</ref> On February 21, 1897, it struck and sank the fishing steamer {{SS|T. W. Ferry||2}} docked at the [[Pere Marquette Railway]] Company dock in [[Ludington, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite book |author = United States Steamboat-Inspection Service |year = 1898 |url = https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=72 |title = Annual Report of the Supervising Inspector-General Steamboat-Inspection Service, Year Ending June 30, 1898 |location = Washington, DC |publisher = Government Printing Office |page = 66 |oclc = 5151984 |access-date = April 7, 2020 |via = Haithi Trust }}</ref> The steamship was originally called the ''Pere Marquette'' and renamed the ''Pere Marquette No. 15'' in 1924.<ref>{{harvp|Hilton|2003|pp=100, 203}}.</ref><ref>*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Simmons-Boardman|first=|title=Marine Engineering Review |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wW3mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Pere+Marquette+15%22+built+1896+first+steel&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+15%22+built+1896+first+steel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc7pOo6b_UAhXBRSYKHW63BjkQ6AEIMDAD |year=1936|publisher=Simmons-Boardman Publishing Company |page = 200 }}</ref>\n\nThe naval architect who designed the steamship was [[Robert Logan (naval architect)|Robert Logan]]. He designed six car ferries for the Flint and Pere Marquette Railroad between 1895 and 1910. He was born in Scotland and started shipbuilding in Canada in 1888.<ref name=Scottish_man> {{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Paul S. |date=March 18, 1997 |title=Scottish man designs six of the local fleet|url= |work=Ludington Daily News |department = Steam & Steel Section B |page = 3 |access-date= }} </ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[commons:Category:Ships named Pere Marquette|Ships named ''Pere Marquette'']]\n*[[Ferries in Michigan]]\n*[[SS Badger|SS ''Badger'']]\n*[[SS Spartan|SS ''Spartan'']]\n*[[SS John Sherman|SS ''John Sherman'']]\n*[[SS City of Midland 41|SS ''City of Midland 41'']]\n*[[SS City of Milwaukee|SS ''City of Milwaukee'']]\n*[[William L. Mercereau]], superintendent of the carferry steamship system out of [[Ludington, Michigan]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Extern links ==\n*{{commons category-inline|''Pere Marquette'' (ship, 1897)}}\n\n[[Category:Train ferries]]\n[[Category:Pere Marquette Railway]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bay City, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:SS ''Pere Marquette''}}\n[[File:Pere Marquette carferry 1896.jpg|thumb|upright 1.0|''Pere Marquette'' carferry <br/> being launched in 1896]]\nThe '''SS ''Pere Marquette''''' (also '''''Pere Marquette 15''''') was the world's first steel [[train ferry]]. It sailed on [[Lake Michigan]] and provided service between the ports of [[Ludington, Michigan]], and [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]], for the [[Pere Marquette Railway]] from 1897 to 1930. The railway used the named ''Pere Marquette'' for many of its ships and ferries, adding a number to the end of the name. \n\n==Railroad car ferry==\n[[File:SS Pere Marquette propeller.jpg|thumb|upright 1.0|Carferry propeller (<small>''Pere Marquette 10''</small>) at Ludington harbor compared to 6 foot tall man]]\nThe carferry was built by the [[Frank W. Wheeler|Wheeler Shipyards]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], in 1896 at a cost of $300,000. The vessel was built for the [[Flint and Pere Marquette Railroad]] and complete when launched, except for a few finishing items needed for the cabins. It left Bay City on December 30, 1896, and arrived first in Milwaukee for a day's public inspection.<ref name=PublicInspec> {{cite web |url=http://www.carferries.com/pm/PM15/ |title= Pere Marquette 15 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2005 |website=The Carferries of the Great Lakes |publisher= M. Hanley |access-date= June 21, 2017 |quote=}} </ref> It then continued onto Ludington from there and arrived on January 13, 1897. The ship had split cabins, one in front of the smoke stacks and one behind them. They provided [[Berth (sleeping)|sleeping berth]]s for the officers and ten passengers.<ref name=SteelCarferry> {{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Paul S. |date=March 18, 1997 |title=First steel carferry is the Pere Marquette |url= |work=[[Ludington Daily News]] |department = Steam & Steel Section B |page=3 |access-date=}} </ref>\n\nThe steamship was {{convert|350|feet}} long and {{convert|56|feet}} wide. It measured 2,443 [[gross register tons]] and had two twelve foot propellers for its driving force. There were two compound engines that produced 2,500 horsepower.<ref>*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Keefe |first = William Ford |title = Voices from Sweetwater Seas |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=InrhAAAAMAAJ |year =  1998 |publisher = Action Research Institute |isbn = 978-0-9635609-8-8 |page = 283 }}</ref> The ship had electricity from stem to stern that was controlled at the pilot house.  The inside deck had four railroad tracks with a capacity of 30 freight [[boxcar]]s. Fully loaded the carferry had a displacement of some 4,050 tons on a {{convert|12.25|foot}} draft of water. The vessel traveled in both the summer and winter and was capable of handling severe gales.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Simmons-Boardman|first=|title=Marine Engineering/log|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxM4AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA6|year=1897|publisher=Simmons-Boardman Publishing Corporation |page = 6 }}</ref> Its hull was constructed to break up heavy ice.<ref name=IceBreaker> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Marine History|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11901053/ |work=Daily News |location=Ludington, Michigan |date=June 24, 1943 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] }}</ref> It was unique in that it was first steel train ferry constructed in the world.<ref name=WorldFirst> {{cite news |last=Mac Loren |first=Agnes |date=January 4, 1957 |title=This & That from History |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11699276/ |work= Ludington Daily News |page= 2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |quote=The Pere Marquette, which was the widest steamer on the Great Lakes, was the first steel carferry in the world.}}</ref><ref name=WorldHistoryFirst> {{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 13, 1943 |title=Sunday Marks 45th Birthday of World's First Steel Carferry |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11699668/the_ludington_daily_news/ |work=  Ludington Daily News |page = 1  |via= Newspapers.com }}</ref><ref name=Stem&Steel> {{cite news |last=MacLaren |first=Agnes |date=February 19, 1952 |title= First steel Carferry made Maiden Voyage 55 Years Ago Today |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11759864/|work=Ludington Daily News |via= Newspapers.com |quote=Fifty five years ago, on Feb 19, 1897, there steamed out of Ludington's harbor the first steel carferry in the world, departing on her maiden voyage. }}</ref><ref name=\"Bagley\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-06-07/columns/053.html |title=Autos Across Mackinac: Pere Marquette Makes New Home in St. Ignace |work=[[St. Ignace News]] |first1=Les |last1=Bagley |date=June 7, 2007 |accessdate=July 9, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002948/http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-06-07/columns/053.html |archivedate=July 29, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe vessel carried railroad cars and passengers and went into service as a cross-lake train ferry going across Lake Michigan. It made its official maiden voyage from Ludington to Manitowoc on the night of February 16, 1897. It carried 22 railroad freight boxcars and traveled all night at a speed of 14 knots and arrived at its destination at 7:00 A.M. on February 17, 1897.<ref>{{cite book |last = Hilton |first = George Woodman |title = The Great Lakes Car Ferries |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=x1BjhmhfFeoC |date =  2003 |publisher = Montevallo Historical Press |isbn = 978-0-9658624-3-1 |page = 117 |ref = harv }}</ref> On 21 February, 1897 she struck and sank the fishing steamer  {{SS|T. W. Ferry||2}}  ({{flag|United States|1896}})  docked at the  [[Pere Marquette Railway]] Company dock, [[Ludington, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=72 |page={{#expr:72-6}} |title=Annual report of the Supervising Inspector-general Steamboat-inspection Service, Year ending June 30, 1898 ||location=Washington |publisher=Government Printing Office |date=1898|via=Haithi Trust |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The steamship was originally called the ''Pere Marquette'' and renamed the ''Pere Marquette No. 15'' in 1924.<ref>{{harvp|Hilton|2003|pp=100, 203}}.</ref><ref>*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Simmons-Boardman|first=|title=Marine Engineering Review |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wW3mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Pere+Marquette+15%22+built+1896+first+steel&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+15%22+built+1896+first+steel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc7pOo6b_UAhXBRSYKHW63BjkQ6AEIMDAD |year=1936|publisher=Simmons-Boardman Publishing Company |page = 200 }}</ref>\n\nThe naval architect who designed the steamship was [[Robert Logan (naval architect)|Robert Logan]]. He designed six car ferries for the Flint and Pere Marquette Railroad between 1895 and 1910. He was born in Scotland and started shipbuilding in Canada in 1888.<ref name=Scottish_man> {{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Paul S. |date=March 18, 1997 |title=Scottish man designs six of the local fleet|url= |work=Ludington Daily News |department = Steam & Steel Section B |page = 3 |access-date= }} </ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[commons:Category:Ships named Pere Marquette|Ships named ''Pere Marquette'']]\n*[[Ferries in Michigan]]\n*[[SS Badger|SS ''Badger'']]\n*[[SS Spartan|SS ''Spartan'']]\n*[[SS John Sherman|SS ''John Sherman'']]\n*[[SS City of Midland 41|SS ''City of Midland 41'']]\n*[[SS City of Milwaukee|SS ''City of Milwaukee'']]\n*[[William L. Mercereau]], superintendent of the carferry steamship system out of [[Ludington, Michigan]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Extern links ==\n*{{commons category-inline|''Pere Marquette'' (ship, 1897)}}\n\n[[Category:Train ferries]]\n[[Category:Pere Marquette Railway]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bay City, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRailroad car ferry:c/e last edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Pere_Marquette"}
{"title_page": "Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Brooklyn", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant\n| settlement_type                 = [[Neighborhoods of Brooklyn|Neighborhood of Brooklyn]]\n| image_skyline                   = Bedstuybrownstone1.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image                           = <!-- other image (specify File: or Image: namespace) -->\n| nickname                        = Bed-Stuy, Do or Die\n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = {{maplink|frame=y|plain=y|frame-align=center|zoom=12|type=shape|from=Neighbourhoods/New York City/Bedford-Stuyvesant.map}}<!--{{maplink|frame=y|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.705|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.687|-73.941}}}}-->\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location in New York City\n| pushpin_map                     = <!--USA New York City#USA New York#USA-->\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = <!--Location-->\n<!-- location ------------------>| coordinates                     = {{coord|40.687|-73.941|type:city_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|New York}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2               = {{flagicon image|Flag of New York City.svg}} [[New York City]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name3               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Borough of Brooklyn.png}} [[Brooklyn]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Community boards of Brooklyn|Community District]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Brooklyn Community Board 3|Brooklyn 3]],<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/3|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Brooklyn Community Board 8|Brooklyn 8]]<ref name=\"NYCPlanning8\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/8|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- area ---------------------->| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604003-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-3-bedford-stuyvesant-puma-ny|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 2.782\n<!-- population ---------------->| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"stats\"/>\n| population_total                = 157,530\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_density_km2          = <!-- for automatic calculation of any density field, use: auto -->\n| population_density_sq_mi        = auto\n| population_note                 = \n| population_demonym              = <!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1              = Ethnicity\n| demographics1_footnotes         = \n| demographics1_title1            = Black\n| demographics1_info1             = 49%\n| demographics1_title2            = White\n| demographics1_info2             = 27%\n| demographics1_title3            = Hispanic\n| demographics1_info3             = 19%\n| demographics1_title4            = Asian\n| demographics1_info4             = 3%\n| demographics1_title5            = Others\n| demographics1_info5             = 2%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->| demographics_type2              = Economics\n| demographics2_footnotes         = <ref name=\"CB3PUMA\"/>\n| demographics2_title1            = [[Median household income|Median income]]\n| demographics2_info1             = $51,907\n<!-- postal codes, area code --->| timezone1                       = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset1                     = \u22125\n| timezone1_DST                   = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST                 = \u22124\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code                     = 11205, 11206, 11216, 11221, 11233, 11238\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 718, 347, and 929|718, 347, 929]], and [[Area code 917|917]]\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u025b|d|f|\u0259r|d||\u02c8|s|t|a\u026a|v|\u0259|s|\u0259n|t}}), colloquially known as '''Bed\u2013Stuy'''<ref name=\"woodsworth\">{{cite book| last = Woodsworth| first = Michael| title = Battle for Bed-Stuy: The Long War on Poverty in New York City| publisher = Harvard University Press| edition = illustrated| date = May 6, 2016| url = https://books.google.com/?id=rZK-CwAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9780674545069}}</ref>, is a [[neighborhood]] in the north-central portion of the [[New York City]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]]. Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is bordered by [[Flushing Avenue]] to the north (bordering [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]]), Classon Avenue to the west (bordering [[Clinton Hill, Brooklyn|Clinton Hill]]), [[Broadway (Brooklyn)|Broadway]] to the east (bordering [[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]] and [[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]]), and [[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]] to the south (bordering [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn|Crown Heights]] and [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]]).<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/lucds/bk3profile.pdf \"Brooklyn Community District 3\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514131351/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/lucds/bk3profile.pdf |date=May 14, 2008 }} (pdf). ''[[New York City Department of City Planning]]''. December 2007. Accessed April 25, 2008.</ref>   The main shopping street, Fulton Street runs east\u2013west the length of the neighborhood and intersects high-traffic north\u2013south streets including [[Bedford Avenue]], [[Nostrand Avenue]], and Stuyvesant Avenue. Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant contains four smaller neighborhoods: Bedford, Stuyvesant Heights, [[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]], and [[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] (also part of Crown Heights). Part of [[Clinton Hill, Brooklyn|Clinton Hill]] was once considered part of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant has the largest collection of intact and largely untouched Victorian architecture in the country, with roughly 8,800 buildings built before 1900.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/13/realestate/bedford-stuyvesant-diverse-and-changing.html|title=Bedford-Stuyvesant: Diverse and Changing|last=Gregor|first=Alison|date=2014-07-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Its building stock includes many historic [[brownstone]]s. These homes were developed for the expanding middle- to upper-middle class from the 1890s to the late 1910s. These homes contain highly ornamental detailing throughout their interiors and have classical architectural elements, such as brackets, [[Quoin (architecture)|quoins]], [[Fluting (architecture)|fluting]], [[finial]]s, and elaborate frieze and cornice banding.\n\nSince the late 1930s the neighborhood has been a major cultural center for [[Brooklyn]]'s [[African American]] population. Following the construction of the [[IND Fulton Street Line|Fulton Street subway line]] ({{NYCS trains|Fulton}})<ref name=\"urbanology\">Echanove, Matias. [http://urbanology.org/BedStuy/ \"Bed-Stuy on the Move\"]. Master thesis. Urban Planning Program. ''Columbia University''. Urbanology.org. 2003.</ref> in 1936, African Americans left an overcrowded [[Harlem]] for greater housing availability in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. From Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, African Americans have since moved into the surrounding areas of Brooklyn, such as [[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]], [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn|Crown Heights]], [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]], and [[Fort Greene, Brooklyn|Fort Greene]]. \n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is mostly part of [[Brooklyn Community Board 3|Brooklyn Community District 3]], though a small part is also in [[Brooklyn Community Board 8|Community District 8]]. Its primary [[ZIP Code]]s are 11205, 11206, 11216, 11221, 11233, and 11238.<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\"/><ref name=\"NYCPlanning8\"/> Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is patrolled by the 79th and 84th Precincts of the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"NYPD 79th Precinct\"/><ref name=\"NYPD 81st Precinct\"/> Politically it is represented by the New York City Council's 36th District.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n===Founding{{anchor|Early history}}===\n\nThe neighborhood's name combines the names of the [[Political subdivisions of New York State#Village|Village]] of Bedford and the Stuyvesant Heights neighborhoods.  ''Stuyvesant'' is derived from [[Peter Stuyvesant]], the last governor of the colony of [[New Netherland]].\n\n====17th and 18th centuries====\nIn the second half of the 17th century, the lands which constitute the present neighborhood belonged to three Dutch settlers: Dirck Janse Hooghland, who operated a ferryboat on the East River, and farmers Jan Hansen, and Leffert Pietersen van Haughwout. In pre-[[American Revolutionary War|revolutionary]] Kings County, Bedford was the first, major settlement east of the Village of Brooklyn on the ferry road to the town of [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]] and eastern [[Long Island]]. Stuyvesant Heights, however, was farmland; the area became a community after the American Revolutionary War.\n\nFor most of its early history, Stuyvesant Heights was part of the outlying farm area of the small hamlet of Bedford, settled by the Dutch during the 17th century within the incorporated town of Breuckelen. The hamlet had its beginnings when a group of Breuckelen residents decided to improve their farm properties behind the Wallabout section, which gradually developed into an important produce center and market. The petition to form a new hamlet was approved by Governor Stuyvesant in 1663. Its leading signer was Thomas Lambertsen, a carpenter from Holland. A year later, the British capture of New Netherland signaled the end of Dutch rule. In [[Richard Nicolls|Governor Nicolls']] Charter of 1667 and in the Charter of 1686, Bedford is mentioned as a settlement within the Town of Brueckelen. Bedford hamlet had an inn as early as 1668, and, in 1670, the people of Breuckelen purchased from the [[Canarsie Indians]] an additional area for common lands in the surrounding region.\n\nBedford Corners, approximately located where the present [[Bedford Avenue]] meets [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]], and only three blocks west of the present Historic District, was the intersection of several well traveled roads. The Brooklyn and Jamaica Turnpike, constructed by a corporation founded in 1809 and one of the oldest roads in Kings County, ran parallel to the present Fulton Street, from the East River ferry to the village of Brooklyn, thence to the hamlet of Bedford and on toward Jamaica via Bed\u2013Stuy. Farmers from New Lots and Flatbush used this road on their way to Manhattan. Within the Stuyvesant Heights Historic District, the Turnpike ran along the approximate line of Decatur Street. Cripplebush Road to Newtown and the Clove Road to Flatbush also met at Bedford Corners. Hunterfly Road, which joined the Turnpike about a mile to the east of Clove Road, also served as a route for farmers and fishermen of the Canarsie and New Lots areas.\n\nAt the time of the Revolution, Leffert's son Jakop was a leading citizen of Bedford and the town clerk of Brooklyn.  His neighbor, Lambert Suydam, was captain of the Kings County cavalry in 1776. An important part of the [[Battle of Long Island]] took place in and near the Historic District. In 1784, the people of the Town of Brooklyn held their first town meeting since 1776.\n\n====19th century{{anchor|Establishment as an urban neighborhood}}====\n[[File:MacDonoughStreetSH.jpg|thumb|287px|right|Row houses on MacDonough Street]]\nIn 1800, Bedford was designated one of the seven districts of the Town of Brooklyn, and, in 1834, it became part of the seventh and ninth wards of the newly incorporated City of Brooklyn. With the building of the [[Brooklyn and Jamaica Railroad]] in 1833, along [[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]], Bedford was established as a railroad station near the intersection of current Atlantic Avenue and Franklin Avenues. In 1836, the Brooklyn and Jamaica Railroad was taken over by the [[Long Island Rail Road]] (LIRR), which in 1878 would gain a connection to the [[BMT Brighton Line|Brooklyn, Flatbush and Coney Island Railway]]'s northern terminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Early_Rapid_Transit_in_Brooklyn,_1878-1913#The_Brooklyn.2C_Flatbush_and_Coney_Island_Railroad_.28The_Brighton_Line.29.2FThe_New_York_and_Manhattan_Beach_Railroad|title=The Brooklyn, Flatbush and Coney Island Railroad (The Brighton Line)/The New York and Manhattan Beach Railroad|work=nycsubway.org|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> The [[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] subsection, founded in 1838, was recognized as one of the first, free [[African American|African-American]] communities in the United States.<ref>Ramirez, Anthony.[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/05/nyregion/05weeksville.html?_r=1&oref=slogin \"Haven for Blacks in Civil War Riots Now Safeguards History\"], ''The New York Times'', June 5, 2005. Accessed November 17, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe present [[street grid]] was laid out in 1835, as shown by the Street Commissioners map of 1839, and the blocks were divided into lots  The new [[street grid]] led to the abandonment of the Brooklyn and Jamaica Turnpike in favor of a continuation of Brooklyn's Fulton Street, though the lands for the street grid were not sold to the City of Brooklyn until 1852. When Charles C. Betts purchased Maria Lott's tract of land the same year, this marked the end of two centuries of Dutch patrimonial holdings. Most of the streets were not opened until the 1860s, at which point Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's streets were named after prominent figures in American history. The Dripps Map of 1869 shows that the area was still largely rural with a few freestanding houses mostly on MacDonough Street. The real development of the district began slowly at first, accelerating between 1885 and 1900, and gradually tapering off during the first two decades of the 20th century.\n\n[[File:Brooklyn brownstones in Stuyvesant Heights built between 1870-1899.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Along Stuyvesant Avenue]]\n\nConstruction of masonry row houses in the 1870s began to transform the rural district into an urban area. The first row of masonry houses in Stuyvesant Heights was built in 1872 on MacDonough Street for developer Curtis L. North. In the 1880s and 1890s, more rows were added, most of the Stuyvesant Heights north of Decatur Street looked much as it does today. Stuyvesant Heights was emerging as a neighborhood entity with its own distinctive characteristics. The houses had large rooms, high ceilings and large windows, and were built primarily by German immigrants.<ref name=\"Gregor 2014\">{{cite web |last=Gregor |first=Alison |title=Bedford-Stuyvesant: Diverse and Changing |website=The New York Times |date=July 13, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/13/realestate/bedford-stuyvesant-diverse-and-changing.html |access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> The people who bought these houses were generally upper-middle-class families, mostly lawyers, shopkeepers, and merchants of German and Irish descent, with a sprinkling of English people; there were also a few professionals. A contemporary description calls it a very well kept residential neighborhood, typical of the general description of Brooklyn as \"a town of homes and churches.\"\n\nBuilt in 1863, the [[Capitoline Grounds]] were the home of the [[Brooklyn Atlantics]] baseball team.<ref name=\"covehurst\">{{cite web |url=http://www.covehurst.net/ddyte/brooklyn/capitoline.html |title=Capitoline Grounds |last=Ross |first=Andrew |author2=David Dyte |publisher=covehurst.net |accessdate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> The grounds were bordered by Nostrand Avenue, Halsey Street, Marcy Avenue, and Putnam Avenue.<ref name=covehurst/> During the winters, the operators would flood the area and open an ice-skating arena. The grounds were demolished in 1880.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n[[File:Ch of Pilgrim Holiness 24 Arlington Pl Bk jeh.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Macon Street and Arlington Place]]\n\nIn 1890, the [[city of Brooklyn]] founded another subsection [[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]], a working-class predominantly Italian enclave. In the last decades of the 19th century, with the advent of electric [[tram|trolleys]] and the [[Kings County Elevated Railway|Fulton Street Elevated]], Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant became a [[working class|working-class]] and [[middle class|middle-class]] [[commuter town|bedroom community]] for those working in downtown Brooklyn and [[Manhattan]] in New York City. At that time, most of the pre-existing wooden homes were destroyed and replaced with [[brownstone]] [[Terraced house|rowhouses]].\n\n===20th century===\n\n====1900s to 1950s====\nIn 1907, the completion of the [[Williamsburg Bridge]] facilitated the immigration of Jews and Italians from the [[Lower East Side]] of Manhattan.<ref name=\"rfk\">{{cite book |last=Newfield |first=Jack |title=Robert Kennedy: A Memoir |publisher=Penguin Group |edition=reprint |date=1988 |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyme000newf/page/87 87\u2013109] |isbn=0-452-26064-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyme000newf/page/87 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1930s, major changes took place due to the [[Great Depression]] years. Immigrants from the American South and the [[Caribbean]] brought the neighborhood's black population to around 30,000, making it the second largest [[Black people|Black]] community in the city at the time. During [[World War II]], the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]] attracted many black New Yorkers to the neighborhood as an opportunity for employment, while the relatively prosperous war economy enabled many of the Jewish and Italian residents to move to Queens and Long Island. By 1950, the number of black residents had risen to 155,000, comprising about 55 percent of the population of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.<ref name= rfk/> In the 1950s, [[real estate agents]] and [[Speculation|speculators]] employed [[blockbusting]] to turn a profit. As a result, formerly middle-class white homes were being turned over to poorer black families. By 1960, eighty-five percent of the population was black.<ref name= rfk/>\n\n====1960s====\n[[File:Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant riot of 1964.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Confrontation between black protesters and police at Fulton Street and Nostrand Avenue during the 1964 riot]]\nGang wars erupted in 1961 in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, and Alfred E. Clark of ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to it as \"Brooklyn's Little [[Harlem]].\"<ref>Clark, Alfred E. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1961/05/02/archives/gang-wars-upset-area-in-brooklyn-bedford-stuyvesant-tense-following.html GANG WARS UPSET AREA IN BROOKLYN; Bedford&nbsp;\u2013 Stuyvesant Tense Following Two Slayings].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. Tuesday May 2, 1961. Page 31. Retrieved on January 22, 2010.</ref> One of the first urban [[riot]]s of the era took place there due to [[Society|social]] and [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] divisions in the city contributed to the tensions. Race riots  between the NYPD and the city's black community were strained due to perceptions of the NYPD as being oppressive and racially biased, and at that time, few black policemen were present on the force.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873963-6,00.html \"No Place Like Home\"]. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]].'' July 31, 1964.</ref> Predominantly black neighborhoods received disproportionate rates of arrests and prosecutions for drug-related crimes, and the NYPD's 79th Precinct in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant was one of the only three police precincts in the NYPD where black police officers were allowed to patrol.<ref>Darien, Andrew. [http://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/CLD_RLR_s00_police.pdf \"Police Fraternity and the Politics of Race and Class in New York City, 1941\u20131960\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021083109/http://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/CLD_RLR_s00_police.pdf |date=October 21, 2013 }}. ''Regional Labor Review''. Spring 2000.</ref> Race riots followed in 1967 and 1968, as part of the [[political]] and racial tensions in the United States of the era, aggravated by continued high unemployment among blacks, continued [[de facto]] [[segregation in housing]], and the failure to enforce [[civil rights]] laws.\n\n[[File:Kennedy discusses school with young Ricky Taggart.jpg|thumb|250px|Senator [[Robert F. Kennedy]] speaks with a boy while touring Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant]]With the help of local activists and politicians, such as Civil Court Judge [[Thomas R. Jones (judge)|Thomas Jones]], grassroots organizations of community members and businesses willing to aid were formed and began the rebuilding of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. In 1965, [[Andrew W. Cooper]], a journalist from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, brought suit under the [[Voting Rights Act]] against racial [[gerrymandering]]<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2002_Jan_30/ai_82336550 |title=The City Sun Editor-in-Chief Andrew W. Cooper dies |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |date=January 30, 2002 |publisher=Business Wire}}</ref> under the grounds that Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant was divided among five [[congressional district]]s, each with a white [[United States House of Representatives|representative]].<ref name=\"Answers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.answers.com/topic/andrew-w-cooper |title=Andrew W. Cooper |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |publisher=Answers.com}}</ref> It resulted in the creation of [[New York's 12th Congressional District]] and the election in 1968 of [[Shirley Chisholm]], the [[List of African-American firsts|first black woman]] and [[West Indian American]] ever elected to the [[United States Congress|US Congress]].<ref name=\"Lueck\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/30/nyregion/andrew-w-cooper-74-pioneering-journalist.html |title=Andrew W. Cooper, 74, Pioneering Journalist |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |last=Lueck |first=Thomas J. |date=January 30, 2002 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, [[Robert F. Kennedy]], U.S. senator for New York state, launched a study of problems facing the urban poor in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, which received almost no federal aid and was the city's largest non-white community.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paul F. O'Rourke |title=A Health Project for Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant |quote= |newspaper=RFK Senate Legislature Papers (SLP), Box 11, [[JFK Library]] |year=1968 |pages= |url=https://www.zotero.org/andrewcummins/items/itemKey/M4ZFRHE5 |accessdate=February 5, 2012|author-link=Paul F. O'Rourke }}</ref><ref>Schlesinger, Arthur{{cite book |title=Robert Kennedy and his times |page=[https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyhis01schl/page/786 786] |isbn=0-618-21928-5 |last1=Schlesinger |first1=Arthur Meier |year=2002 |url=https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyhis01schl/page/786 }}</ref> Under Kennedy's leadership and with the help of activists, the [[Bedford Stuyvesant Restoration Corporation]] was established as the United States\u2019 first community development corporation.<ref name=\"Spellen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.brownstoner.com/history/walkabout-savin-3/ |title=Bed Stuy Brooklyn History |work=Brownstoner |author=Spellen, Suzanne |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2016}}</ref> The Manhattan-based Development and Services Corporation (D&S) was established with business, banking and professional leaders which advised and raised private funding for the BSRC's projects.<ref name=\"Spellen\" /> The abandoned Sheffield Milk bottling plant on Fulton Street was turned into the BSRC offices in 1967,<ref name=Spellen /> and the BSRC bought and renovated many housing units as well as administered a $73 million mortgage assistance program to encourage African-American homeownership.<ref name=Spellen /> The BSRC also implemented a controversial plan by [[I.M. Pei]] to close off St. Marks Avenue and Prospect Place, between Kingston and Albany Avenues, and convert these into community spaces.<ref name=\"Spellen\" />\n\n====1970s and 1980s====\n[[File:Children at Kosciusko pool.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Youth play in an adventure playground at the \"K-pool\" public swimming pool in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant in July 1974.  Photo by [[Danny Lyon]].]]\n\nIn the late 1980s, resistance to illegal drug-dealing included, according to Rita Webb Smith, following police arrests with a civilian [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]] 40-day patrol of several blocks near a mosque, the same group having earlier evicted drug sellers at a landlord's request, although that also resulted in arrests of the Muslims for \"burglary, menacing and possession of weapons\", resulting in a [[probation]]ary sentence.<ref>Smith, Rita Webb, & Tony Chapelle, ''The Woman Who Took Back Her Streets: One Woman Fights The Drug Wars And Rebuilds Her Community'' (Far Hills, New Jersey: New Horizon Press, 1991 ({{ISBN|0-88282-065-6}})), pp.&nbsp;289\u2013291 (quoting p.&nbsp;290) (author Smith leader of a [[Harlem]] anti-drug campaign).</ref>\n\n=== Recent history{{anchor|Recent trends}} ===\n====2000s{{anchor|Early 2000s gentrification}}====\nBeginning in the 2000s, the neighborhood began to experience [[gentrification]].<ref name=urbanology/> The two significant reasons for this were the affordable housing stock consisting of [[brownstone]] [[Terraced house|rowhouses]] located on quiet tree-lined streets, as well as the marked decrease of crime in the neighborhood. Many properties were renovated after the start of the 21st century, and new retailers began moving to the neighborhood. There was a belief that neighborhood change would benefit all residents of the area, bringing with it greater neighborhood safety, more local jobs, and retail demand on major commercial strips. As such, both the Fulton Street and Nostrand Avenue commercial corridors became part of the Bed-Stuy Gateway Business Improvement District, bringing along with it a beautification project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.restorationplaza.org/about/news/beautification-of-bed-stuy|title=Beautification of the Bed-Stuy Gateway streetscape receives major financial support - Bedford Stuyvesant Restoration|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806221226/http://www.restorationplaza.org/about/news/beautification-of-bed-stuy|archive-date=August 6, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Through a series of \"wallscapes\" (large outdoor [[mural]]s), the campaign honored famous community members, including community activist and poet [[June Jordan]], activist [[Hattie Carthan]], and rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]<ref>Notorious B.I.G.'s residence: {{cite news|url=http://www.theinsider.com/news/1548004_Much_change_in_Biggie_Smalls_neighborhood|title=Much change in Biggie Smalls' neighborhood|last=Franklin|first=Marcus|date=January 17, 2009|accessdate=October 10, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212112344/http://www.theinsider.com/news/1548004_Much_change_in_Biggie_Smalls_neighborhood|archivedate=February 12, 2010|publisher=The Insider|agency=Associated Press}}<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;Other than Notorious B.I.G.'s residence: [https://web.archive.org/web/20060303221200/http://gothamgazette.com/community/36/news/1340 Grace, Melissa, ''New P.R. Campaign: \"Bed-Stuy and Proud of it\"'', in ''Gotham Gazette'', March 10, 2005, from ''Daily News'', at ''Wayback Machine'', March 3, 2006, 10:12:00 p.m.], as accessed October 20, 2013.</ref> The campaign sought to show off the area's positive accomplishments.<ref>Grace, Melissa, ''New P.R. Campaign: \"Bed-Stuy and Proud of it\"'', ''op. cit.''</ref>[[File:Bedstuybrownstone1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A row of brownstones on Jefferson Avenue between Lewis and Stuyvesant Avenues in Bedford Stuyvesant, 2006]]\n\nSeveral long-time residents and business owners expressed concern that they would be priced out by newcomers, whom they disparagingly characterize as \"[[yuppie]]s and [[buppie]]s [black urban professionals]\", according to one neighborhood blog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2013/01/bed_stuy_billboards.html|title=Series of Brooklyn Billboards Put Racial Inequity on Display|last=admin|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> They feared that the neighborhood's ethnic character would be lost. However, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's population has experienced much less displacement of the black population than other areas of Brooklyn, such as [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]] and [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn|Cobble Hill]].<ref>http://66.111.110.102/newyork/DetailsAr.do?file=features/499/499.thebattlefor.html {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928055859/http://66.111.110.102/newyork/DetailsAr.do?file=features%2F499%2F499.thebattlefor.html |date=September 28, 2007 }}  \"The Battle for Bed-Stuy: The Price of Art\" [[Time Out (company)|Time Out New York]] April 2005</ref> Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant saw more foreign-born [[Afro-Caribbean]] and [[Ethnic groups of Africa|African]] residents as well as  [[upwardly mobile]] [[middle class|middle-income]] [[African-American|African American]] families, as well as immigrants from [[Africa]] and the [[Caribbean]]. Surrounding neighborhoods in northern and eastern Brooklyn have a combined population of about 940,000 and are roughly 82% black, making them the largest concentration of African Americans in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=ChangeGeoContext&geo_id=86000US11203&_geoContext=01000US%7C04000US36%7C05000US36047&_street=&_county=&_cityTown=&_state=04000US36&_zip=11203&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=010&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null%3Anull&_keyword=&_industry= |title=American FactFinder |publisher=Factfinder.census.gov |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2005, the NYPD designated the Fulton Street\u2013Nostrand Avenue business district in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant as an \"Impact Zone\", which directed significantly increased levels of police protection and resources to the area for two consecutive 6-month periods, resulting in a 15% decrease in crime within one year. Despite the improvements and increasing stability of the community, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant has continued to be stigmatized in some circles. In March 2005 a campaign was launched to supplant the \"Bed-Stuy, Do-or-Die\" slogan with \"Bed-Stuy, and Proud of It\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Grace|first=Melissa|title=Say It Loud: Bed-stuy And Proud|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2005-03-10/local/18287657_1_new-slogan-bed-stuy-proud|publisher=NY Daily News|accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> Violent crime also remains a problem in the area, and the two precincts that cover Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant reported a combined 37 murders in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs079pct.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220350/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs079pct.pdf |archivedate=May 27, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs081pct.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140917190508/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs081pct.pdf |archivedate=September 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lafayette Patchen jeh.JPG|thumb|right|220px|The view southeast across Lafayette Avenue, looking toward Patchen Avenue]]\n\n====2010s{{anchor|Early 2010s gentrification}}====\nDespite the [[Great Recession|largest recession]] to hit the United States in the last 70 years, gentrification continued steadily, and the blocks north of the Nostrand Avenue/Fulton Street intersection and west of Fulton Street and Stuyvesant Avenue were particularly impacted. In 2011, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant listed three [[Zagat]]-rated restaurants for the first time. Today there are over ten Zagat-rated establishments,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zagat.com/search/place/?text=bedford-stuyvesant |title=Best Places in New York City &#124; Foodie, Nightlife & Shopping News |publisher=Zagat.com |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> and in June 2013, 7 Arlington Place, the setting for [[Spike Lee]]'s 1994 film ''[[Crooklyn]],'' was sold for over its asking price, at $1.7 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130617/bed-stuy/crooklyn-house-sells-for-17m-reflection-of-bed-stuy-real-estate-boom|title='Crooklyn' House Sells for $1.7M, a Reflection of Bed-Stuy Real Estate Boom|date=June 17, 2013|publisher=DNAinfo.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324033710/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130617/bed-stuy/crooklyn-house-sells-for-17m-reflection-of-bed-stuy-real-estate-boom|archivedate=March 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA diverse mix of students, [[hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipsters]], artists, creative professionals, architects, and attorneys of all races continue to move to the neighborhood. A business improvement district has been launched along the Fulton and Nostrand Corridor with a redesigned streetscape to include new street trees, street furniture, [[paver (flooring)|pavers]], and signage and improved cleanliness in an effort to attract more business investment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycedc.com/project/bedford-stuyvesant-streetscape-project |title=Bedford-Stuyvesant Streetscape Project |publisher=NYCEDC |date=January 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Major infrastructure upgrades have been performed or are in progress, such as [[Select Bus Service]] [[bus rapid transit]] on the {{NYC bus link|B44}} route along Nostrand and Bedford Avenues, which began operating in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/brt/html/routes/nostrand.shtml |title=Bus Rapid Transit - Nostrand/Rogers Avenues |publisher=Nyc.gov |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Other infrastructure upgrades in the neighborhood includes major sewer and water modernization projects,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkanplumbing.com/new-sewer-water-lines-brooklyn-ny-installation/ |title=New Brooklyn Sewer Connections, New Brooklyn Water Lines |publisher=Balkanplumbing.com |date=October 10, 2012 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> as well as fiber-optic and cable service upgrades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newscenter.verizon.com/press-releases/verizon/2010/verizon-continues-rollout-of.html |title=Verizon &#124; Verizon Continues Rollout of FiOS TV in New York City |publisher=Newscenter.verizon.com |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Improved natural and organic produce continue to become available at local delis and grocers, the farmer's market on Malcolm X Boulevard, and through the Bed-Stuy Farm Share.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bed Stuy Farm Share |url=http://www.bedstuyfarmshare.org/ |title=Bed Stuy Farm Share |publisher=Bed Stuy Farm Share |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> [[FreshDirect]] services the neighborhood, and a large member constituency of the adjacent Greene-Hill Food Coop are from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.\n\n==Subsections==\n\n===Neighborhoods===\nBedford is located toward the western end of Bedford-Stuyvesant. Before the [[American Revolutionary War]] times, it was the first settlement to the east of the [[Political subdivisions of New York State|Village]] of Brooklyn. It was originally part of the old village of Bedford, which was centered near today's Bedford Avenue\u2013Fulton Street intersection. The area \"extends from Monroe Street on the north to Macon Street and Verona Place on the south, and from just east of Bedford Avenue eastward to Tompkins Avenue,\" according to the Landmarks Preservation Commission.<ref>[http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2514.pdf Bedford Historic District: Designation Report], December 8, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/05/nyregion/in-bedford-stuyvesant-a-black-stronghold-a-growing-pool-of-whites.html|title=Striking Change in Bedford-Stuyvesant as the White Population Soars|author=Sam Roberts|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 4, 2011|quote=The extent of racial integration, so far, has been mixed in the more rapidly changing Bedford section, which the city's Planning Department defines roughly as bounded by Throop, Classon and Flushing Avenues and Fulton Street.}}</ref> Bedford is adjacent to Williamsburg, Crown Heights, and Clinton Hill.<ref name=\"Freudenheim\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RuUCDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA64#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Brooklyn Experience: The Ultimate Guide to Neighborhoods & Noshes, Culture & the Cutting Edge|author=Ellen Freudenheim|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2016|page=64|isbn=9780813577456}}</ref>\n\nStuyvesant Heights is located toward the southern-central section of Bedford-Stuyvesant. It has historically been an African-American enclave. It derives its name from Stuyvesant Avenue, its principal thoroughfare. It was originally part of the outlying farm area of Bedford for most of its early history. A low-rise residential district of three- and four-story masonry row houses and apartment buildings with commercial ground floors, it was developed mostly between 1870 and 1920,<ref name=\"Freudenheim\" /><ref>[http://home2.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/STUYVESANT_HEIGHTS_HISTORIC_DISTRICT.pdf Stuyvesant Heights Historic District: Designation Report], September 14, 1971.</ref><ref>[https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/plans/bedford-stuyvesant/bed_stuy.pdf Bedford-Stuyvesant South Rezoning - Approved!]</ref> mainly between 1895 and 1900.<ref name=\"Expanded\" /> The Stuyvesant Heights Historic District is located within the area bounded roughly by Tompkins Avenue on the west, Macon and Halsey Streets on the north, [[Utica Avenue|Malcolm X Boulevard]] on the east, and [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]] on the south.<ref name=\"Expanded\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/28/archives/-real-nice-community-now-historic.html|title='Real Nice' Community Now 'Historic'|author=Michael J. Hall|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 28, 1971}}</ref>\n\n[[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]] is located toward the eastern end Ocean Hill received its name in 1890 for being slightly hilly. Hence it was [[Subdivision (land)|subdivided]] from the larger community of Stuyvesant Heights. From the beginning of the 20th century to the 1960s Ocean Hill was an Italian enclave. By the late 1960s Ocean Hill and Bedford-Stuyvesant proper together formed the largest [[African American]] community in the [[United States]].\n\n[[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] is located toward the southeast. Weeksville was named after an ex-slave<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/save-americas-treasures/success-stories/weeksville.html |title=Plan your next trip with the National Trust &#124; National Trust for Historic Preservation |accessdate=April 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222185205/http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/save-americas-treasures/success-stories/weeksville.html |archivedate=December 22, 2014 }}</ref> from [[Virginia]], who in 1838<ref name=\"nytimes_20050605\">{{cite news |last=Ramirez |first=Anthony |title=Haven for Blacks in Civil War Riots Now Safeguards History |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 5, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/05/nyregion/05weeksville.html |accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> bought a plot of land and founded Weeksville.\n\n===Historic district===\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Stuyvesant Heights Historic District\n| nrhp_type      = hd\n| image          = Decatur Stuyvesant Heights HD 2.JPG\n| caption        = On Decatur Street\n| location       = Roughly bounded by Macon, Tompkins, Decatur, Lewis, Chauncey, and Stuyvesant, [[New York, New York]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|40|40|52|N|73|56|14|W|display=inline}}\n| locmapin       = New York City\n| built          = 1870\n| architecture   = Italianate, Queen Anne, Romanesque\n| added          = December 4, 1975\n| area           = {{convert|42|acre|sigfig=2}}\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum         = 75001193<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Stuyvesant Heights Historic District (Boundary Increase)\n| embed          = yes\n| nrhp_type      = hd\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| location       = Roughly, Decatur St. from Tompkins to Lewis Aves., [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| architect      = multiple\n| architecture   = Italianate, Second Empire, Queen Anne\n| added          = November 15, 1996\n| area           = {{convert|10|acre|sigfig=2}}\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum         = 96001355<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n| nocat          = yes\n}}\n}}\nThe Stuyvesant Heights [[Historic district (United States)|Historic District]] in Bedford-Stuyvesant comprises 577 contributing residential buildings built between about 1870 and 1900.  The district encompasses 17 individual blocks (13 identified in 1975 and four new in 1996).  The buildings within the district primarily comprise two- and three-storey [[Terraced houses|rowhouses]] with high basements, with a few multiple dwellings and institutional structures. The district includes the [[Our Lady of Victory Church (Brooklyn, New York)|Our Lady of Victory Catholic Church]], the [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Romanesque Revival]] style Mount Lebanon Baptist Church, and St. Phillip's Episcopal Church.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3289|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Stuyvesant Heights Historic District|date=August 1972|accessdate=March 19, 2011|author=Stephen Lash and Betty Ezequelle|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019112759/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3289|archivedate=October 19, 2012}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3287|title=Accompanying nine photos|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924141549/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3287|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3359|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Stuyvesant Heights Historic District (Boundary Increase)|date=September 1996|accessdate=March 19, 2011|author=Peter D. Shaver|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019112822/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3359|archivedate=October 19, 2012}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3360|title=Accompanying seven photos|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924141629/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3360|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1975 and expanded in 1996.<ref name=\"nris\"/> Bedford Stuyvesant/Expanded Stuyvesant Heights Historic District was designated on April 16, 2013 and extended the district north to Jefferson Ave, east to Malcolm X Blvd, and west to Tompkins Avenue.<ref name=\"Expanded\">{{cite web|url = http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2496.pdf|title = Bedford Stuyvesant/Expanded Stuyvesant Heights Historic District \u2013 Designation Report|date = April 16, 2013|accessdate = April 20, 2015|website = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160313091831/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2496.pdf|archive-date = March 13, 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"100px\">\nFile:Miracle Temple Brooklyn.JPG|Miracle Temple\nFile:Decatur Stuyvesant Heights HD 1.JPG|On Decatur Street\nFile:200 block Decatur Brooklyn.JPG |On Decatur Street\nFile:St Philips Brooklyn.JPG|St. Phillip's Episcopal Church\nFile:Mt Lebanon Brooklyn 2.JPG |Mt. Lebanon Baptist Church\nFile:Mt Lebanon Brooklyn 1.JPG |Mt. Lebanon Baptist Church\nFile:On Lewis Brooklyn.JPG|On Lewis Street\n</gallery>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nThe entirety of Community Board 3 had 152,403 inhabitants as of [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|NYC Health]]'s 2018 Community Health Profile, with an average life expectancy of 76.8 years.<ref name=\"CHP2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/data/2018chp-bk3.pdf|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant (Including Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Kensington and Ocean Parkway)|last=|first=|date=2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=NYC Health|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|2, 20}} This is lower than the median life expectancy of 81.2 for all New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/tcny/community-health-assessment-plan.pdf|title=2016-2018 Community Health Assessment and Community Health Improvement Plan: Take Care New York 2020|last=|first=|date=2016|website=[[government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]]|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|53 (PDF p. 84)}}<ref>{{cite web | title=New Yorkers are living longer, happier and healthier lives | website=New York Post | date=June 4, 2017 | url=https://nypost.com/2017/06/04/new-yorkers-are-living-longer-happier-and-healthier-lives/ | access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Most inhabitants are middle-aged adults and youth: 24% are between the ages of 0\u201317, 33% between 25\u201344, and 22% between 45\u201364. The ratio of college-aged and elderly residents was lower, at 10% and 11% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}}\n\nAs of 2016, the median [[household income]] in Community Board 3 was $51,907.<ref name=\"CB3PUMA\">{{cite web|url=http://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604003-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-3-bedford-stuyvesant-puma-ny/|title=Census profile: NYC-Brooklyn Community District 3--Bedford-Stuyvesant PUMA, NY|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, an estimated 23% of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant residents lived in poverty, compared to 21% in all of Brooklyn and 20% in all of New York City. One in eight residents (13%) were unemployed, compared to 9% in the rest of both Brooklyn and New York City. Rent burden, or the percentage of residents who have difficulty paying their rent, is 53% in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, higher than the citywide and boroughwide rates of 52% and 51% respectively. Based on this calculation, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is considered to be [[gentrification|gentrifying]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n===Demographic trends===\nThe 1790 census records of Bedford lists 132 freemen and 72 slaves. Rapid population growth followed major improvements to public transportation. By 1873, Bed-Stuy's (predominantly white) population was 14,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theweeklynabe.com/2012/06/23/bed-stuy-brooklyn-a-very-brief-history/|title=Bed-Stuy: a very brief history|last=Williams|first=Keith|website=The Weekly Nabe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> In the early 1900s, prosperous black families began buying up the mansions of Bed-Stuy, many of which were designed by prominent architects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.6sqft.com/bed-stuy-from-harlem-and-hip-hop-to-hipsters-hassids-and-high-rents/|title=Bed-Stuy: From Harlem and Hip-Hop to Hipsters, Hassids and High Rents|website=6sqft|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> The population was quick to grow, but it wasn't until the 1930s that Bed-Stuy's black population boomed. Following the introduction of the IND Fulton Street Line (a.k.a. the A/C line) in 1936, African-Americans left crowded Harlem in search of better housing opportunities. Bed-Stuy quickly became the second destination for black New Yorkers and the ''New York Times'' even dubbed it \u201cLittle Harlem\u201d in 1961.\n\nAfter a large decline during the 1970s (mirroring the citywide decline), the population in Bedford Stuyvesant grew by 34 percent between 1980 and 2015 (faster than the citywide growth rate of 21 percent) to reach 150,900 residents. The population has increased by 25 percent in just the past 15 years, more than three times faster than the citywide rate. The ethnic and racial mix of the population has undergone dramatic changes in the past 15 years as the neighborhood has attracted new residents. According to data from the U.S. Census Bureau, three-quarters of the residents identified as black or African-American in 2000, but this share had declined to less than half of the population by 2015. In 2015 (the latest year for which census data are available), one-quarter of the residents were white and nearly one-fifth were Hispanic. By comparison, in 2000, less than 3 percent of the population was white (the Hispanic share of the population has remained relatively unchanged). The Asian population has grown, but remains relatively small, making up less than 3 percent of the neighborhood<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osc.state.ny.us/osdc/rpt5-2018.pdf|title=An Economic Snapshot of the Bedford-Stuyvesant Neighborhood|last=DiNapoli|first=Thomas P.|date=September 2017|website=Office of the New York State Comptroller|access-date=August 8, 2019}}</ref> According to the US Census Bureau, in 2016 the population was 49% Black, 27% [[Non-Hispanic whites|White]], 19% Hispanic, 3% Asian, and 2% other or from two or more races.<ref name=\"CB3PUMA\"/>\n\n== Politics ==\nThe neighborhood is part of [[New York's 8th congressional district]],<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012c/CD_map_rep_08.pdf Congressional District 8], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012c/CD_nyc.pdf New York City Congressional Districts], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> represented by Democrat [[Hakeem Jeffries]] {{as of|2013|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. House Election Results 2018 | website=The New York Times | date=January 28, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-house-elections.html | access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref> It is also part of the 18th and 25th [[New York State Senate|State Senate]] districts,<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_map_rep_18.pdf Senate District 18], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_map_rep_25.pdf Senate District 25], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_nyc.pdf 2012 Senate District Maps: New York City], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed November 17, 2018.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Julia Salazar]] and [[Velmanette Montgomery]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/district/18|title=NY Senate District 18|author=|date=|website=NY State Senate|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/district/25|title=NY Senate District 25|author=|date=|website=NY State Senate|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> and the 54th, 55th, and 56th [[New York State Assembly|State Assembly]] districts,<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_054.pdf Assembly District 54], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_055.pdf Assembly District 55], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_056.pdf Assembly District 56], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_nyc.pdf 2012 Assembly District Maps: New York City], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed November 17, 2018.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Erik Dilan]], [[Latrice Walker]], and [[Tremaine Wright]].<ref>{{cite web | title=New York State Assembly Member Directory | website=Assembly Member Directory | url=https://nyassembly.gov/mem/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Bed-Stuy is located in the [[New York City Council]]'s 36th and 41st districts,<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dc/downloads/pdf/brooklyn.pdf Current City Council Districts for Kings County], [[New York City]]. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Robert Cornegy]] and [[Alicka Ampry-Samuel]].<ref>{{cite web | title=District 36 | website=[[New York City Council]] | date=March 25, 2018 | url=https://council.nyc.gov/district-36/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=District 41 | website=[[New York City Council]] | date=March 25, 2018 | url=https://council.nyc.gov/district-41/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Police and crime ==\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is patrolled by two precincts of the [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Find Your Precinct and Sector - NYPD | website=www.nyc.gov | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/find-your-precinct.page | access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref> The 81st Precinct is located at 30 Ralph Avenue, serving the area east of Marcus Garvey Boulevard,<ref name=\"NYPD 81st Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/81st-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 81st Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> and the 79th Precinct is located at 263 Tompkins Avenue, serving the area west of Marcus Garvey Boulevard.<ref name=\"NYPD 79th Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/79th-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 79th Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe area collectively covered by the 79th and 81st Precincts ranked 62nd safest out of 69 patrol areas for per-capita crime in 2010. While total crime has decreased since the 1990s, it is still higher in Bed-Stuy than in much of the rest of the city.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/bedford-stuyvesant|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant \u2013 DNAinfo.com Crime and Safety Report|website=www.dnainfo.com|access-date=October 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430140105/http://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/bedford-stuyvesant/|archive-date=April 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, in 2016, major crime dropped 11 percent in the 81st Precinct, marking the greatest reduction in north Brooklyn's 10 precincts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170113/bed-stuy/safety-eastern-bed-stuy-stuyvesant-heights-81st-precinct|title=Bed-Stuy Precinct Leads North Brooklyn in Major Crime Decrease, Police Say|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=2019-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716045938/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170113/bed-stuy/safety-eastern-bed-stuy-stuyvesant-heights-81st-precinct/|archive-date=July 16, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>  With a non-fatal assault rate of 117 per 100,000 people, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's rate of violent crimes per capita is greater than that of the city as a whole. The incarceration rate of 1,045 per 100,000 people is higher than that of the city as a whole.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\nThe 79th Precinct has a lower crime rate than in the 1990s, with crimes across all categories having decreased by 78.8% between 1990 and 2018. The precinct saw 9 murders, 27 rapes, 309 robberies, 343 felony assaults, 301 burglaries, 484 grand larcenies, and 72 grand larcenies auto in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-079pct.pdf|title=79th Precinct CompStat Report|date=|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The 81st Precinct had a relatively smaller crime decrease of 73.9% between 1990 and 2018. The precinct saw 10 murders, 25 rapes, 234 robberies, 274 felony assaults, 218 burglaries, 399 grand larcenies, and 48 grand larcenies auto in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-081pct.pdf|title=81st Precinct CompStat Report|date=|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Fire safety ==\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] (FDNY) operates seven fire stations in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant:<ref>{{cite web | title=NYPD Precincts & Firehouses - Brooklyn CB 3 | website=Welcome to NYC.gov | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/brooklyncb3/resources/nypd-precincts-firehouses.page | access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite FDNY locations}}</ref>\n* Ladder Co. 102 \u2013 850 Bedford Avenue \n* Engine Co. 230 \u2013 701 Park Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 230 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e230.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Battalion 57/Engine Co. 235 \u2013 206 Monroe Street<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 235/Battalion 7 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e235.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 217 \u2013 940 DeKalb Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 217 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e217.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 214/Ladder Co. 111 \u2013 495 Hancock Street<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 214/Ladder Company 111 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e214.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Battalion 37/Engine Co. 222 \u2013 32 Ralph Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 222/Battalion 37 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e222.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 233/Ladder Co. 176/Field Comm Unit 1 \u2013 25 Rockaway Avenue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e233.htm|title=Engine Company 233/Ladder Company 176/Field Comm Unit 1|website=FDNYtrucks.com|access-date=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Health ==\n[[Preterm birth|Preterm]] and teenage births are more common in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant than in other places citywide. In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, there were 95 preterm births per 1,000 live births (compared to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and 26.9 teenage births per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide).<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|11}} Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant has a relatively low population of residents who are [[Health insurance coverage in the United States|uninsured]], or who receive healthcare through [[Medicaid]].<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.health.ny.gov/health_care/medicaid/redesign/dsrip/pps_applications/docs/maimonides_medical_center/3.8_maimonides_cna.pdf New York City Health Provider Partnership Brooklyn Community Needs Assessment: Final Report], [[New York Academy of Medicine]] (October 3, 2014).</ref> In 2018, this population of uninsured residents was estimated to be 11%, which is slightly lower than the citywide rate of 12%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|14}}\n\nThe concentration of [[particulates|fine particulate matter]], the deadliest type of [[air pollution|air pollutant]], in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is {{convert|0.0081|mg/m3|oz/ft3}}, higher than the citywide and boroughwide averages.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|9}} Nineteen percent of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant residents are [[Smoking|smokers]], which is higher than the city average of 14% of residents being smokers.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, 29% of residents are [[Obesity|obese]], 13% are [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetic]], and 34% have [[hypertension|high blood pressure]]\u2014compared to the citywide averages of 24%, 11%, and 28% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|16}} In addition, 22% of children are obese, compared to the citywide average of 20%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|12}}\n\nEighty-four percent of residents eat some fruits and vegetables every day, which is slightly lower than the city's average of 87%. In 2018, 76% of residents described their health as \"good,\" \"very good,\" or \"excellent,\" slightly less than the city's average of 78%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} For every supermarket in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, there are 57 [[convenience store|bodegas]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|10}}\n\nThere are several hospitals in the Bed-Stuy area, including the [[Woodhull Medical Center]] and the [[Interfaith Medical Center]].<ref name=\":14\"/>{{rp|19\u201320}}\n\n== Post offices and ZIP codes ==\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is covered by four primary [[ZIP Code]]s (11206, 11216, 11221, 11223) and parts of three other ZIP Codes (11205, 11213, and 11233). The northern part of the neighborhood is covered by 11206; the central part, by 11221; the southwestern part, by 11216; and the southeastern part, by 11223. In addition, the ZIP Code 11205 covers several blocks in the northwestern corner of Bed-Stuy, and 11213 includes several blocks in the extreme southern portion of the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bedford-Stuyvesant, New York City-Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY) | website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA) | url=https://www.zipmap.net/New_York/Kings_County/Z_Bedford-Stuyvesant.htm | access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] operates four post offices nearby: the Restoration Plaza Station at 1360 Fulton Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Location Details: Restoration Plaza | website=USPS.com | url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1379126&locationName=RESTORATION+PLAZA&address2=&address1=1360+FULTON+ST+STE+1 | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> the Shirley A Chisholm Station at 1915 Fulton Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Location Details: Shirley A Chisholm | website=USPS.com | url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1383815&locationName=SHIRLEY+A+CHISHOLM&address2=&address1=1915+FULTON+ST | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> the Bushwick Station at 1369 Broadway,<ref>{{cite web|title=Location Details: Bushwick|url= https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1356467&locationName=BUSHWICK&address2=&address1=1369+BROADWAY|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> and the Halsey Station at 805 MacDonough Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=Location Details: Halsey|url= https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1366006&locationName=HALSEY&address2=&address1=805+MACDONOUGH+ST|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant generally has a lower ratio of college-educated residents than the rest of the city. While 35% of residents age 25 and older have a college education or higher, 21% have less than a high school education and 43% are high school graduates or have some college education. By contrast, 40% of Brooklynites and 38% of city residents have a college education or higher.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} The percentage of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant students excelling in reading and math has been increasing, with reading achievement rising from 32 percent in 2000 to 37 percent in 2011, and math achievement rising from 23 percent to 47 percent within the same time period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://furmancenter.org/files/sotc/BK_03_11.pdf|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant \u2013 BK 03|last=|first=|date=2011|website=|publisher=[[Furman Center for Real Estate and Urban Policy]]|access-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant's rate of elementary school student absenteeism is higher than the rest of New York City. In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, 30% of elementary school students missed twenty or more days per [[school year]], compared to the citywide average of 20% of students.<ref name=\":21\" />{{Rp|24 (PDF p. 55)}}<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} Additionally, 70% of high school students in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant graduate on time, lower than the citywide average of 75% of students.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}}\n\n=== Schools ===\n[[File:PS93 Prescott Nostrand Av Herkimer St jeh.jpg|thumb|PS 93, Prescott School|alt=]]\nSeveral public schools serve Bedford-Stuyvesant. The zoned high school for the neighborhood is [[Boys and Girls High School]] on [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]]. The Brooklyn Brownstone School, a public elementary school located in the MS 35 campus on MacDonough Street, and was developed in 2008 by the Stuyvesant Heights Parents Association and the New York City Board of Education. At the eastern edge of the neighborhood is [[Paul Robeson High School for Business and Technology]].\n\nMany public schools are named after prominent African-Americans and, as stated by [[Nikole Hannah-Jones]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'', were  \"intended to evoke black uplift\".<ref name=HannahJonesneighbsch>{{cite web|author=Hannah-Jones, Nikole|authorlink=Nikole Hannah-Jones|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/12/magazine/choosing-a-school-for-my-daughter-in-a-segregated-city.html?_r=0|title=Choosing a School for My Daughter in a Segregated City|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2016-06-09|accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref> Hannah-Jones wrote in 2016 that many wealthier residents choose to use [[magnet schools]] or [[private schools]] instead of neighborhood schools.<ref name=HannahJonesneighbsch/>\n\nFor the early grades Ember Charter School for Mindful Education and [[Success Academy Charter Schools|Success Academy Bed-Stuy 1 and 2]] are charter schools. Bed-Stuy is also home to the [[Brooklyn Waldorf School]], which moved to Claver Castle (at 11 Jefferson Avenue) in 2011.\n\nOther institutions include:\n* [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High School]]\n* [[Girl's High School]]\n* [[Pratt Institute]]\n* [[Brooklyn Brownstone Elementary School]]\n* [[Weeksville Heritage Center]]\n* [[Bedford Academy High School]]\n\n=== Libraries ===\nThe [[Brooklyn Public Library]] (BPL) has four branches in Bedford-Stuyvesant:\n* The Bedford branch and Bedford Learning Center, at 496 Franklin Avenue near Fulton Street. The branch opened in 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/bedford|title=Bedford Library|date=August 17, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Marcy branch, at 617 DeKalb Avenue near Nostrand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/marcy|title=Marcy Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Macon Library|Macon branch]], at 361 Lewis Avenue near Macon Street. The branch is a [[Carnegie library]] that opened in 1907. It contains the Dionne Mack-Harvin Center, a collection dedicated to African American culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/macon|title=Macon Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Saratoga branch, at 8 Thomas S. Boyland Street near Macon Street. The branch is a Carnegie library that opened in 1909.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/saratoga|title=Saratoga Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Bedford-Nostrand_Avenues_-_Queens_Bound_Platform.jpg\n|caption1=The [[Bedford\u2013Nostrand Avenues station]] of the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Crosstown Line]]\n|image2=LIRR 9944 (6029110921).jpg\n|caption2=The [[Nostrand Avenue station (LIRR)|Nostrand Avenue station]] of the [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n}}\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is served by the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Fulton Street Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Fulton}}), which opened in 1936. This underground line replaced the earlier, elevated [[BMT Fulton Street Line]] on May 31, 1940. The [[IND Crosstown Line]] ({{NYCS trains| Crosstown}}), running underneath Lafayette Avenue and Marcy Avenue, opened for service in 1937. The elevated [[BMT Jamaica Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Jamaica west}}) also serves the neighborhood, running alongside its northern boundary at Broadway. Additionally, the elevated [[BMT Lexington Avenue Line]] served Lexington Avenue until 1950 and the elevated [[BMT Myrtle Avenue Line]] served [[Myrtle Avenue]] to the north until 1969.\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is also served by the [[Nostrand Avenue (LIRR station)|Nostrand Avenue]] station of the [[Long Island Rail Road]].\n\nSeveral bus routes, operated by [[MTA Regional Bus Operations]], run through Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. The {{NYC bus link|B7|B15|B43|B44|B44 SBS|B46|B46 SBS|B47|B48|B60|prose=y}} routes run primarily north to south through the neighborhood, while the {{NYC bus link|B25|B26|B38|B52|B54|prose=y}} run primarily west to east, and the {{NYC bus link|Q24}}, B46, and B47 run northwest to southeast on Broadway.<ref>{{Cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n<!-- Add only people from Bed-Stuy itself, not people who only say they are. Add only if notable, in other words, qualified for their own article in Wikipedia; see [[WP:REDLINK]] for more information. -->\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em|small=yes|rules=yes}}\n* [[Aaliyah]] (1979\u20132001), Grammy-nominated singer.<ref>Farley, Christopher John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=rwlBoSSahkYC&pg=PA20 ''Aaliyah: More Than a Woman''], p. 20. Accessed July 2, 2016. [[Simon and Schuster]], 2002. {{ISBN|9780743455664}}. \"She was born on January 16, 1979, in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood of Brooklyn, but, at the age of four, her parents relocated to the Motor City where Aaliyah spent her formative years.\"</ref>\n* [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]] (born 1994), drag queen and performer\n* [[Big Daddy Kane]] (born 1968), rapper.<ref>Gill, Lauren. [http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/39/27/dtg-bb-big-daddy-kane-concert-2016-07-01-bk.html \"Legendary Bed-Stuy rapper Big Daddy Kane performs outside former Albee Square Mall\"], ''[[The Brooklyn Paper]]'', June 28, 2016. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"Legendary Bedford-Stuyvesant-born rapper Big Daddy Kane entertained shoppers and commuters with a free show on Fulton Mall on Friday, and the wordsmith showed off just as much charisma as when he used to spit his rhymes in rap battles in Kings County\u2019s streets, according to organizers.\"</ref>\n* [[Memphis Bleek]] (born 1978), rapper.<ref>Avalone, Blake. [http://www.dubmagazine.com/home/stars/item/8449-memphis-bleek-and-the-young-gunz \"Memphis Bleek and the Young Gunz\"], ''[[DUB (magazine)]]'', May 16, 2005. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"For years, fans came to recognize the gritty Bleek as an heir to Jay\u2019s throne. With consistently impressive rhymes focusing on the contrast between the grim realities of the Bedford Stuyvesant streets and the glitz and glamour of a recording career, Memphis Bleek did not disappoint.\"</ref>\n* [[Mark Breland]] (born 1963), boxer.<ref>[[Ira Berkow|Berkow, Ira]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/28/sports/boxing-breland-returns-to-ring-modestly-in-brooklyn.html \"BOXING; Breland Returns to Ring Modestly in Brooklyn\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 28, 1996. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"Breland was back in Brooklyn, where he had started his career, coming out of the tough Tompkins projects in Bedford-Stuyvesant and going on to become a five-time New York Golden Gloves champion, the 1984 Olympic gold-medal champion, and twice the world's welterweight champ.\"</ref>\n* [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]] (born 1978), rapper{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n* [[Lil Cease]] (born 1977), rapper<ref>http://www.mtv.com/artists/lil-cease/ Lil' Cease], [[MTV]]. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Rapper Lil' Cease was born and raised in Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant area, at age 15 becoming a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of the Notorious B.I.G.\"</ref>\n* [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), congresswoman<ref>http://history.house.gov/People/Listing/C/CHISHOLM,-Shirley-Anita-(C000371)/ CHISHOLM, Shirley Anita], [[United States House of Representatives]] History, Art & Archives. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Elected in 1968 because of her roots in the Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant neighborhood, Chisholm was catapulted into the national limelight by virtue of her race, gender, and outspoken personality.\"</ref>\n* [[Imani Coppola]] (born 1978), singer-songwriter<ref>Lester, Paul. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/03/bandoftheday.culture \"No 344: Little Jackie; Today's new artist sounds like Lily Allen meets Lauryn Hill - seriously, what's not to like?\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 3, 2008. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Coppola's songs are as idiosyncratically infectious as Allen's, only instead of observations about life in LDN she's focused on the antics and mores of the Big Apple in general and the area surrounding her Bedford-Stuyvesant (Chris Rock's old stomping ground) apartment in particular.\"</ref>\n* [[Alan Dale (singer)|Alan Dale]] (1925\u20132002), singer and star of [[The Alan Dale Show]]<ref>O'Kane, Jim. Jefferson Avenue: Stories from a Brooklyn Boyhood 1941-1958. New York: Createspace, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Deemi]] (born 1980), singer<ref>Hamilton, Tiffany. [http://allhiphop.com/2005/09/23/deemi-diamond-in-the-rough/ \"Deemi: Diamond In The Rough\"], [[AllHipHop]], September 23, 2005. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Although she is from the streets, Deemi is not an emcee \u2013 and she's definitely not your usual R&B diva. Born and raised in Bedford Stuyvesant, the 24-year-old songstress definitely has a story to tell.\"</ref>\n* [[Desiigner]] (born 1997), rapper<ref>Weiner, Natalie. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7400285/desiigner-on-panda-difficult-past-kanye-west-advice \"Desiigner on His Difficult Past and How His No. 1 Hit 'Panda' Gave Him a Way Out\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)]]'', June 9, 2016. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"'Out' means out of Bedford-Stuyvesant, the Brooklyn neighborhood where Desiigner grew up.\"</ref>\n* Nelson Erazo (born 1977), professional wrestler better known by his ring name [[Homicide (wrestler)|Homicide]]{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Fabolous]] (born 1977), rapper<ref>Vasquez, Emily. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/18/nyregion/18rapper.html \"Brooklyn-Born Rapper Is Arrested After Being Shot\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 18, 2005. Accessed October 7, 2007. \"Mr. Jackson, raised in the Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, became famous in late 2001 with his debut single, \"I Can\u2019t Deny It.\"\"</ref>\n* [[Bobby Fischer]] (1943\u20132008), eleventh [[World Chess Championship|World Chess Champion]]{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[William Forsythe (actor)|William Forsythe]] (born 1955), actor\n* [[Jackie Gleason]] (1916\u201387), actor, comedian<ref>[http://www.upi.com/topic/Jackie_Gleason/ \"Jackie Gleason\"], ''[[United Press International]]''. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Carl Gordon (actor)|Carl Gordon]] (1932\u20132010), actor<ref>[[Margalit Fox|Fox, Margalit]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/23/arts/23gordon.html \"Carl Gordon, a Late-Blooming Actor, Dies at 78\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 23, 2010. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Rufus Carl Gordon Jr. was born on Jan. 20, 1932, in Goochland, Va.; he later jettisoned the 'Rufus.' When he was a child his family moved to Brooklyn, where he grew up in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.\"</ref>\n* [[Kadeem Hardison]] (born 1965), actor, portrays [[Dwayne Wayne]] on ''[[A Different World]]''<ref>Staff. [http://humormillmag.com/on-this-day-in-comedy-in-1965-kadeem-hardison-was-born/ \"On This Day In Comedy\u2026 In 1965 Kadeem Hardison Was Born!\"], Humor Mill, July 24, 2015. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Actor, director, Kadeem Hardison was born in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn New York.\"</ref>\n* [[Richie Havens]] (1941\u20132013), musician and poet<ref>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/23/arts/music/richie-havens-guitarist-and-singer-dies-at-72.html \"Richie Havens, Folk Singer Who Riveted Woodstock, Dies at 72\"], ''[[The New York Times]]', April 22, 2013. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Richard Pierce Havens was born on Jan. 21, 1941, in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, where he grew up.\"</ref>\n* [[Connie Hawkins]] (1942-2017), [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] player<ref>Segal Jonathan B. [https://www.nytimes.com/1972/03/26/archives/foul-the-connie-hawkins-story-by-david-wolf-400-pp-new-york-holt.html \"Foul!\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 26, 1972. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"To fill in the details a bit, Hawkins, the subject of ''Foul!,'' was a great black schoolyard basketball player from New York's Bedford\u2010Stuyvesant section who became, in the jivin', hand\u2010slapping, pressure\u2010cooker world of ghetto ball, a revered figure for his spectacular and flashy play.\"</ref>\n* [[Lena Horne]] (1917\u20132010), actress and singer<ref>Gavin, James. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/19/books/excerpt-stormy-weather.html \"'Stormy Weather'\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 17, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"'I came from what was called one of the First Families of Brooklyn,' Horne explained. They shunned discussing the slave ancestry that had spawned them all \u2014 'yet it was the rape of slave women by their masters which accounted for our white blood, which, in turn, made us Negro \"society.\"' Home was an immaculate four-story brownstone in Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant section.\"</ref>\n* [[Jay Z|Shawn \"Jay-Z\" Carter]] (born 1969), rapper, who lived in the [[Marcy Houses|Marcy Housing Projects]] for most of his childhood<ref>Pareles, Jon. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/arts/music/13pare.html \"An Overdog to Root For\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 9, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"His songs have told and retold the poverty-to-bling story of Shawn Carter, Jay-Z\u2019s real name, who grew up in the tough Marcy Houses in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, and dealt drugs before turning to hip-hop.\"</ref>\n* [[Jaz-O]] (born 1964), rapper{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Joey Badass]] (born 1995), rapper<ref>Tempey, Nathan. [http://gothamist.com/2015/06/06/joey_badass_is_not_excited_about_ge.php \"Interview: Joey Badass Is Not Excited About Gentrification\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025124441/http://gothamist.com/2015/06/06/joey_badass_is_not_excited_about_ge.php |date=October 25, 2016 }}, [[Gothamist]], June 6, 2015. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Joey Badass grew up Jo-Vaughn Scott in Bedford-Stuyvesant.\"</ref>\n* [[Norah Jones]] (born 1979), singer<ref>Eldredge, Barbara. [http://www.brownstoner.com/brooklyn-life/norah-jones-eat-pray-love-house-brooklyn-172-pacific-street-renovation/ \"Norah Jones Is Renovating Her Movie-Worthy, Landmarked Cobble Hill Carriage House\"], Brownstoner, March 8, 2016. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Famous musician and Bed Stuy native Norah Jones is renovating the sweet Pacific Street stable she bought last fall.\"</ref>\n* [[June Jordan]] (1936\u20132002), Caribbean American poet, novelist, journalist, biographer, dramatist, teacher and activist<ref>Lee, Felicia R. [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/04/books/a-feminist-survivor-with-the-eyes-of-a-child.html \"A Feminist Survivor With the Eyes Of a Child\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 4, 2000. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Ms. Jordan grew up in Harlem and Brooklyn, reading Shakespeare and Edgar Allan Poe before she turned 5, she says. Her family moved from a Harlem housing project to the Bedford-Stuyvesant area in Brooklyn because it seemed like a better place to raise a family.\"</ref>\n* [[Wee Willie Keeler]] (1872\u20131923), Baseball Hall-of-Famer<ref>[http://thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_K/Keeler.Willie.Obit.html \"Willie Keeler Dies of Heart Disease\"\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 2, 1923. Accessed October 29, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Brian Kokoska]] (born 1988), artist{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Talib Kweli]] (born 1975), emcee{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Lil' Kim]] (born 1974), rapper<ref>Ogunnaike, Lola. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/nyregion/20kim.html \"A Flourish, and Lil' Kim Goes From Star to Inmate\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 20, 2005. Accessed October 19, 2007. \"Ms. Jones spoke about her rise from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, to stardom and about her deepening relationship with God.\"</ref>\n* [[Maino]] (born 1973), rapper<ref>Mlynar, Phillip. [http://www.villagevoice.com/music/qanda-maino-on-growing-up-in-bed-stuy-hearing-rumors-about-himself-and-his-song-that-isnt-about-lil-kim-6620028 \"Q&A: Maino On Growing Up In Bed-Stuy, Hearing Rumors About Himself, And His Song That Isn't About Lil Kim\"], ''[[Village Voice]]'', February 27, 2012. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"For the early part of his career, the Bedford-Stuyvesant-born Maino was better known as another New York City rapper with a nefarious background (he saw out a ten year jail bid for attempted kidnap) who traded in block-corner crime rhymes to the extent that he was as much someone in the street who also happened to rap as anyone approaching an artist.\"</ref>\n* [[Masta Ace]] (born 1966), rapper{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Frank McCourt]] (1930\u20132009), a writer, and [[Malachy McCourt]] (born 1931), an actor, writer and politician. Frank's autobiographical bestseller ''[[Angela's Ashes]]'' describes their early childhood life in a working-class apartment building on Classon Avenue.<ref>[[William Grimes (journalist)|Grimes, William]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/20/books/20mccourt.html \"Frank McCourt, Whose Irish Childhood Illuminated His Prose, Is Dead at 78\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 19, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Francis McCourt was born Aug. 19, 1930, on Classon Avenue on the edge of the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, where his Irish immigrant parents had hoped to make a better life.\"</ref>\n* [[Frank Mickens]] (1946\u20132009), educator<ref>Hevesi, Dennis. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/11/nyregion/11mickens.html \"Frank Mickens, Who Brought Success to a Tough Brooklyn High School, Dies at 63\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 10, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Frank Nathaniel Mickens was born in Bedford-Stuyvesant on June 22, 1946, the only child of John and Hortense Mickens.\"</ref>\n* [[Stephanie Mills]] (born 1957), singer\n* [[Sauce Money]], rapper\n* [[Tracy Morgan]] (born 1968), comedian and actor<ref>Staff. [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=114009203 \"Tracy Morgan On Being 'The New Black'\"], [[National Public Radio]], October 22, 2009. Accessed July 23, 2010.</ref>\n* [[Mos Def]] (aka [[Yasiin Bey]]) (born 1973), rapper\n* [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (born 1970), DJ, producer and member of [[A Tribe Called Quest]]<ref>Torres, Andre. [https://linearlabsmusic.com/artist/ali-shaheed-muhammad/ \"Ali Shaheed Muhammad \u2013 About\"], Linear Labs, Accessed February 27, 2019. \"The soft-spoken and contemplative Brooklyn native began a life of music at an early age, spending years DJing parties in his Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood before co-founding Tribe in 1985.\"</ref>\n* [[Jack Newfield]] (1938\u20132004), journalist<ref name= rfk/>\n* [[Harry Nilsson]] (1941-1994), musician, songwriter and author<ref>Staff. [http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/harry-nilssons-childhood-home \"Harry Nilsson's Childhood HomeThe childhood home of one of America's greatest unsung troubadours still stands in a much changed Brooklyn neighborhood\"], ''[[Atlas Obscura]]''. Accessed June 17, 2017. \"The crooner was born to a poor family in the Bed-Stuy section of Brooklyn on June 15th, 1941. He lived on the top floor of 762 Jefferson Avenue, a simple Romanesque Revival-style apartment building constructed in 1901, until the family fled to California a decade later.\"</ref>\n* [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] (1972\u201397), rapper, grew up near the Clinton Hill-Bed Stuy border, previously considered part of the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.<ref name=\"100BestOpenLineRapHistory2-Complex\">[http://www.complex.com/music/2013/02/the-100-best-opening-lines-in-rap-history-part-2-50-1/notorious-big-unbelievable \"The 100 Best Opening Lines in Rap History, Part 2: 50 - 1\"], in ''ComplexMusic'', February 21, 2013, as accessed September 15, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"Biggie's 'One-Room Shack' in Bed-Stuy Now up for Sale\">{{cite web|author=Bed-Stuy |url=http://bed-stuy.patch.com/groups/real-estate/p/biggie-s-one-room-shack-in-bed-stuy-now-up-for-sale |title=Biggie's 'One-Room Shack' in Bed-Stuy Now up for Sale - Real Estate - Bed-Stuy, NY Patch |publisher=Bed-stuy.patch.com |date=April 3, 2013 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Oddisee]], rapper, producer\n* [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]] (1968\u20132004), rapper\n* [[Papoose (rapper)|Papoose]] (born 1978), rapper\n* [[Floyd Patterson]] (1935\u20132006), boxer\n* [[Martha M. Place]] (1849\u201399), first woman to be put to death in the electric chair<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=18990320&id=C8EhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LZ0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=5226,6178341 \"Put to Death: Mrs. Place Made No Scene in the Electric Chair\"], ''[[The Reading Eagle]]'', March 20, 1899. Accessed October 29, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Jackie Robinson]] (1919\u201372), professional baseball player with the Brooklyn Dodgers<ref>Harpaz, Beth J. [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/guide-exploring-jackie-robinsons-brooklyn \"A Guide to Exploring Jackie Robinson's Brooklyn\"], ''[[The Associated Press]]'', April 10, 2013. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Chris Rock]] (born 1965), actor/comedian.<ref>Osterhout, Jacob E. [http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/chris-rock-new-york-documentary-good-hair-set-open-tour-hometown-article-1.379885 \"Chris Rock's New York: As his documentary 'Good Hair' is set to open, a tour of his hometown\"], ''[[New York Daily News]]'', October 3, 2009. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref> Also made a [[Everybody Hates Chris|TV series about his early life]], with much of it based in Bedford-Stuyvesant.\n* [[Tony Rock]] (born 1974), comedian and younger brother of Chris Rock\n* [[Gabourey Sidibe]] (born 1983), [[Academy Award]]-nominated actress\n* [[Skyzoo]] (born 1982), rapper\n* [[Brandon Stanton]] (born 1984), [[Humans of New York]] author and photographer\n* [[Tek (rapper)|Tek]] (born 1973), one half of [[Smif-N-Wessun]]\n* [[Bill Thompson (New York politician)|Bill Thompson]] (born 1953), New York City 2013 Mayoral candidate<ref name=\"WmThompsonChallenge-BkRail\">[http://www.brooklynrail.org/2003/04/local/william-thompsons-challenges ''William Thompson's Challenges''], in ''The Brooklyn Rail'', April\u2013May 2003.</ref>\n* [[True (artist)|TRUE]] (born 1968), artist\n* [[Mike Tyson]] (born 1966), boxer, lived there with his family until the age of 10.<ref>{{Cite book | url=http://www.bookrags.com/biography/mike-tyson-cri/#gsc.tab=0 |title = Mike Tyson Summary}}</ref>\n* [[Martha Wainwright]] (born 1976), singer\n* [[Dan Washburn]], [[List of American authors|author]] of ''[[The Forbidden Game (non-fiction book)|The Forbidden Game: Golf and the Chinese Dream]]''\n* [[Whodini]], hip-hop group\n* [[Lenny Wilkens]] (born 1937), [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] player and coach<ref>Beck, Howard. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/28/sports/basketball/28knicks.html \"PRO BASKETBALL; Wilkens Denies He Was Asked to Go\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 28, 2005. Accessed November 20, 2007. \"A native of Brooklyn's Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant neighborhood, Wilkens had added motivation to succeed in New York, which made leaving so quickly that much tougher.\"</ref>\n* [[Juan Williams]] (born 1954), journalist and political analyst\n* [[Ted Williams (announcer)|Ted Williams]] (born 1957), voiceover artist\n* [[Vanessa A. Williams]] (born 1963), actress\n{{colend}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\n<!--Please only include entries with reliable sources-->\n* [[Billy Joel]]'s 1980 song \"[[You May Be Right (song)|You May Be Right]],\" from his album ''Glass Houses,'' includes \"I walked through Bedford-Stuy alone\" among the foolhardy things the song's narrator has done.<ref>Barbarino, Al. [https://commercialobserver.com/2014/03/you-may-be-right-about-bedford-stuyvesant/ \"'You May Be Right' About Bedford-Stuyvesant\"], ''Commercial Observer'', March 12, 2014. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"In Billy Joel's 1980 hit, 'You May Be Right,' the singer boasted of his 'crazy' antics crashing parties, riding his motorcycle in the rain and even walking 'through Bedford-Stuy alone.'\"</ref>\n* In her 1980 one-woman film ''[[Gilda Live]],'' [[Gilda Radner]] included a sketch featuring her [[Emily Litella]] character working as a substitute teacher in Bedford-Stuyversant, filling in for a teacher who'd been stabbed by one of his students.<ref>Staff. [https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/73507796/ \"Gilda Live\"], ''[[The Pantagraph]]'', May 15, 1980. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Twittery Emily Litella substitute-teaches in Bedford-Stuyvesant (her use of eraser and chalk stand out in Radner's repertoire of physical gags).\"</ref>\n* ''[[Do the Right Thing]]'', a movie by [[Spike Lee]]<ref>Smith, Rita Webb, & Tony Chapelle, ''The Woman Who Took Back Her Streets'', ''op. cit.'', p.&nbsp;290.</ref>\n* [[Notorious B.I.G.]], a rapper who included Bed\u2013Stuy in his lyrics,<ref name=\"100BestOpenLineRapHistory2-Complex\"/> he \"publicly {{Nowrap|claim[ed]}} Bedford-Stuyvesant as his neighborhood\".<ref name=\"TodayPrideBedStuyBIG-Patch\">[http://bed-stuy.patch.com/groups/around-town/p/today-s-pride-of-bed-stuy-christopher-wallace-aka-the5964734f17 Morris, C. Zawadi, ''Today's Pride of Bed-Stuy: Christopher Wallace aka The Notorious B.I.G.'', in ''Bed-Stuy Patch'', February 29, 2012, 5:00 p.m.], as accessed September 15, 2013 (reprint from February 24, 2011).</ref> A 2009 film, ''[[Notorious (2009 film)|Notorious]]'', about life in Bed\u2013Stuy in the 1990s, emphasized Notorious B.I.G.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/nyregion/20notorious.html?_r=0 Eligon, John, ''Film About a Rapper Captures Bed-Stuy as It Once Was'', in ''The New York Times'', January 19, 2009], accessed September 15, 2013.</ref>\n* The period television sitcom, ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' is set in the Bed-Stuy neighborhood (which is where series creator [[Chris Rock]]\u2019s family lived in during the 1970s and 1980s).<ref>Gill, John Freeman. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/04/nyregion/thecity/wonder-years-by-way-of-bedstuy.html \"''Wonder Years,'' by Way of Bed-Stuy\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 4, 2005. Accessed January 13, 2020. \"This fall, with the new hit UPN television show ''Everybody Hates Chris,'' the country is finally seeing a representation of Bed-Stuy shaped by one of its own: Chris Rock, the show's co-creator and narrator, on whose Decatur Street childhood the program is loosely based. Set in Bed-Stuy in 1982, ''Everybody Hates Chris'' is a nostalgic, warmly illuminated take on the Rock family's tough working-class life in the predominantly black neighborhood.\"</ref> The show occasionally refers to the neighborhood by its often-used nickname \"Bed-Stuy Do or Die.\"\n\n==See also==\n* [[13th Regiment Armory]], former armory in Bed\u2013Stuy\n* [[Magnolia grandiflora (Brooklyn)]], a landmark tree in Bed\u2013Stuy\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Brooklyn/Bedford-Stuyvesant and Flatbush|Bedford-Stuyvesant and Flatbush}}\n\n{{NeighbouringCommunities\n | NORTHWEST=\n | NORTH=[[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]]\n | NORTHEAST=\n | WEST=[[Clinton Hill, Brooklyn|Clinton Hill]]\n | TEXTORPICTURE= Bedford-Stuyvesant\n | EAST=[[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]]/[[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]]\n | SOUTHWEST=\n | SOUTH=[[Crown Heights, Brooklyn|Crown Heights]]/[[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]]\n | SOUTHEAST=\n}}\n\n{{Brooklyn}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Brooklyn| ]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Dutch place names in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant\n| settlement_type                 = [[Neighborhoods of Brooklyn|Neighborhood of Brooklyn]]\n| image_skyline                   = Bedstuybrownstone1.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image                           = <!-- other image (specify File: or Image: namespace) -->\n| nickname                        = Bed-Stuy, Do or Die\n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = {{maplink|frame=y|plain=y|frame-align=center|zoom=12|type=shape|from=Neighbourhoods/New York City/Bedford-Stuyvesant.map}}<!--{{maplink|frame=y|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.705|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.687|-73.941}}}}-->\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location in New York City\n| pushpin_map                     = <!--USA New York City#USA New York#USA-->\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = <!--Location-->\n<!-- location ------------------>| coordinates                     = {{coord|40.687|-73.941|type:city_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|New York}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[City]]\n| subdivision_name2               = {{flagicon image|Flag of New York City.svg}} [[New York City]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name3               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Borough of Brooklyn.png}} [[Brooklyn]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Community boards of Brooklyn|Community District]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Brooklyn Community Board 3|Brooklyn 3]],<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/3|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Brooklyn Community Board 8|Brooklyn 8]]<ref name=\"NYCPlanning8\">{{cite web |title=NYC Planning {{!}} Community Profiles|url=https://communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov/brooklyn/8|website=communityprofiles.planning.nyc.gov|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- area ---------------------->| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604003-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-3-bedford-stuyvesant-puma-ny|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 2.782\n<!-- population ---------------->| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"stats\"/>\n| population_total                = 157,530\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_density_km2          = <!-- for automatic calculation of any density field, use: auto -->\n| population_density_sq_mi        = auto\n| population_note                 = \n| population_demonym              = <!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1              = Ethnicity\n| demographics1_footnotes         = \n| demographics1_title1            = Black\n| demographics1_info1             = 49%\n| demographics1_title2            = White\n| demographics1_info2             = 27%\n| demographics1_title3            = Hispanic\n| demographics1_info3             = 19%\n| demographics1_title4            = Asian\n| demographics1_info4             = 3%\n| demographics1_title5            = Others\n| demographics1_info5             = 2%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->| demographics_type2              = Economics\n| demographics2_footnotes         = <ref name=\"CB3PUMA\"/>\n| demographics2_title1            = [[Median household income|Median income]]\n| demographics2_info1             = $51,907\n<!-- postal codes, area code --->| timezone1                       = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset1                     = \u22125\n| timezone1_DST                   = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST                 = \u22124\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code                     = 11205, 11206, 11216, 11221, 11233, 11238\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 718, 347, and 929|718, 347, 929]], and [[Area code 917|917]]\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u025b|d|f|\u0259r|d||\u02c8|s|t|a\u026a|v|\u0259|s|\u0259n|t}}), colloquially known as '''Bed\u2013Stuy'''<ref name=\"woodsworth\">{{cite book| last = Woodsworth| first = Michael| title = Battle for Bed-Stuy: The Long War on Poverty in New York City| publisher = Harvard University Press| edition = illustrated| date = May 6, 2016| url = https://books.google.com/?id=rZK-CwAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9780674545069}}</ref>, is a [[neighborhood]] in the north-central portion of the [[New York City]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]]. Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is bordered by [[Flushing Avenue]] to the north (bordering [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]]), Classon Avenue to the west (bordering [[Clinton Hill, Brooklyn|Clinton Hill]]), [[Broadway (Brooklyn)|Broadway]] to the east (bordering [[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]] and [[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]]), and [[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]] to the south (bordering [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn|Crown Heights]] and [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]]).<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/lucds/bk3profile.pdf \"Brooklyn Community District 3\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514131351/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/lucds/bk3profile.pdf |date=May 14, 2008 }} (pdf). ''[[New York City Department of City Planning]]''. December 2007. Accessed April 25, 2008.</ref>   The main shopping street, Fulton Street runs east\u2013west the length of the neighborhood and intersects high-traffic north-south streets including [[Bedford Avenue]], [[Nostrand Avenue]], and Stuyvesant Avenue. Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant contains four smaller neighborhoods: Bedford, Stuyvesant Heights, [[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]], and [[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] (also part of Crown Heights). Part of [[Clinton Hill, Brooklyn|Clinton Hill]] was once considered part of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant has the largest collection of intact and largely untouched Victorian architecture in the country, with roughly 8,800 buildings built before 1900.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/13/realestate/bedford-stuyvesant-diverse-and-changing.html|title=Bedford-Stuyvesant: Diverse and Changing|last=Gregor|first=Alison|date=2014-07-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Its building stock includes many historic [[brownstone]]s. These homes were developed for the expanding middle- to upper-middle class from the 1890s to the late 1910s. These homes contain highly ornamental detailing throughout their interiors and have classical architectural elements, such as brackets, [[Quoin (architecture)|quoins]], [[Fluting (architecture)|fluting]], [[finial]]s, and elaborate frieze and cornice banding.\n\nSince the late 1930s the neighborhood has been a major cultural center for [[Brooklyn]]'s [[African American]] population. Following the construction of the [[IND Fulton Street Line|Fulton Street subway line]] ({{NYCS trains|Fulton}})<ref name=\"urbanology\">Echanove, Matias. [http://urbanology.org/BedStuy/ \"Bed-Stuy on the Move\"]. Master thesis. Urban Planning Program. ''Columbia University''. Urbanology.org. 2003.</ref> in 1936, African Americans left an overcrowded [[Harlem]] for greater housing availability in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. From Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, African Americans have since moved into the surrounding areas of Brooklyn, such as [[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]], [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn|Crown Heights]], [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]], and [[Fort Greene, Brooklyn|Fort Greene]]. \n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is mostly part of [[Brooklyn Community Board 3|Brooklyn Community District 3]], though a small part is also in [[Brooklyn Community Board 8|Community District 8]]. Its primary [[ZIP Code]]s are 11205, 11206, 11216, 11221, 11233, and 11238.<ref name=\"NYCPlanning\"/><ref name=\"NYCPlanning8\"/> Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is patrolled by the 79th and 84th Precincts of the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"NYPD 79th Precinct\"/><ref name=\"NYPD 81st Precinct\"/> Politically it is represented by the New York City Council's 36th District.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n===Founding{{anchor|Early history}}===\n\nThe neighborhood's name combines the names of the [[Political subdivisions of New York State#Village|Village]] of Bedford and the Stuyvesant Heights neighborhoods.  ''Stuyvesant'' is derived from [[Peter Stuyvesant]], the last governor of the colony of [[New Netherland]].\n\n====17th and 18th centuries====\nIn the second half of the 17th century, the lands which constitute the present neighborhood belonged to three Dutch settlers: Dirck Janse Hooghland, who operated a ferryboat on the East River, and farmers Jan Hansen, and Leffert Pietersen van Haughwout. In pre-[[American Revolutionary War|revolutionary]] Kings County, Bedford was the first, major settlement east of the Village of Brooklyn on the ferry road to the town of [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]] and eastern [[Long Island]]. Stuyvesant Heights, however, was farmland; the area became a community after the American Revolutionary War.\n\nFor most of its early history, Stuyvesant Heights was part of the outlying farm area of the small hamlet of Bedford, settled by the Dutch during the 17th century within the incorporated town of Breuckelen. The hamlet had its beginnings when a group of Breuckelen residents decided to improve their farm properties behind the Wallabout section, which gradually developed into an important produce center and market. The petition to form a new hamlet was approved by Governor Stuyvesant in 1663. Its leading signer was Thomas Lambertsen, a carpenter from Holland. A year later, the British capture of New Netherland signaled the end of Dutch rule. In [[Richard Nicolls|Governor Nicolls']] Charter of 1667 and in the Charter of 1686, Bedford is mentioned as a settlement within the Town of Brueckelen. Bedford hamlet had an inn as early as 1668, and, in 1670, the people of Breuckelen purchased from the [[Canarsie Indians]] an additional area for common lands in the surrounding region.\n\nBedford Corners, approximately located where the present [[Bedford Avenue]] meets [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]], and only three blocks west of the present Historic District, was the intersection of several well traveled roads. The Brooklyn and Jamaica Turnpike, constructed by a corporation founded in 1809 and one of the oldest roads in Kings County, ran parallel to the present Fulton Street, from the East River ferry to the village of Brooklyn, thence to the hamlet of Bedford and on toward Jamaica via Bed\u2013Stuy. Farmers from New Lots and Flatbush used this road on their way to Manhattan. Within the Stuyvesant Heights Historic District, the Turnpike ran along the approximate line of Decatur Street. Cripplebush Road to Newtown and the Clove Road to Flatbush also met at Bedford Corners. Hunterfly Road, which joined the Turnpike about a mile to the east of Clove Road, also served as a route for farmers and fishermen of the Canarsie and New Lots areas.\n\nAt the time of the Revolution, Leffert's son Jakop was a leading citizen of Bedford and the town clerk of Brooklyn.  His neighbor, Lambert Suydam, was captain of the Kings County cavalry in 1776. An important part of the [[Battle of Long Island]] took place in and near the Historic District. In 1784, the people of the Town of Brooklyn held their first town meeting since 1776.\n\n====19th century{{anchor|Establishment as an urban neighborhood}}====\n[[File:MacDonoughStreetSH.jpg|thumb|287px|right|Row houses on MacDonough Street]]\nIn 1800, Bedford was designated one of the seven districts of the Town of Brooklyn, and, in 1834, it became part of the seventh and ninth wards of the newly incorporated City of Brooklyn. With the building of the [[Brooklyn and Jamaica Railroad]] in 1833, along [[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]], Bedford was established as a railroad station near the intersection of current Atlantic Avenue and Franklin Avenues. In 1836, the Brooklyn and Jamaica Railroad was taken over by the [[Long Island Rail Road]] (LIRR), which in 1878 would gain a connection to the [[BMT Brighton Line|Brooklyn, Flatbush and Coney Island Railway]]'s northern terminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Early_Rapid_Transit_in_Brooklyn,_1878-1913#The_Brooklyn.2C_Flatbush_and_Coney_Island_Railroad_.28The_Brighton_Line.29.2FThe_New_York_and_Manhattan_Beach_Railroad|title=The Brooklyn, Flatbush and Coney Island Railroad (The Brighton Line)/The New York and Manhattan Beach Railroad|work=nycsubway.org|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> The [[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] subsection, founded in 1838, was recognized as one of the first, free [[African American|African-American]] communities in the United States.<ref>Ramirez, Anthony.[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/05/nyregion/05weeksville.html?_r=1&oref=slogin \"Haven for Blacks in Civil War Riots Now Safeguards History\"], ''The New York Times'', June 5, 2005. Accessed November 17, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe present [[street grid]] was laid out in 1835, as shown by the Street Commissioners map of 1839, and the blocks were divided into lots  The new [[street grid]] led to the abandonment of the Brooklyn and Jamaica Turnpike in favor of a continuation of Brooklyn's Fulton Street, though the lands for the street grid were not sold to the City of Brooklyn until 1852. When Charles C. Betts purchased Maria Lott's tract of land the same year, this marked the end of two centuries of Dutch patrimonial holdings. Most of the streets were not opened until the 1860s, at which point Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's streets were named after prominent figures in American history. The Dripps Map of 1869 shows that the area was still largely rural with a few freestanding houses mostly on MacDonough Street. The real development of the district began slowly at first, accelerating between 1885 and 1900, and gradually tapering off during the first two decades of the 20th century.\n\n[[File:Brooklyn brownstones in Stuyvesant Heights built between 1870-1899.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Along Stuyvesant Avenue]]\n\nConstruction of masonry row houses in the 1870s began to transform the rural district into an urban area. The first row of masonry houses in Stuyvesant Heights was built in 1872 on MacDonough Street for developer Curtis L. North. In the 1880s and 1890s, more rows were added, most of the Stuyvesant Heights north of Decatur Street looked much as it does today. Stuyvesant Heights was emerging as a neighborhood entity with its own distinctive characteristics. The houses had large rooms, high ceilings and large windows, and were built primarily by German immigrants.<ref name=\"Gregor 2014\">{{cite web |last=Gregor |first=Alison |title=Bedford-Stuyvesant: Diverse and Changing |website=The New York Times |date=July 13, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/13/realestate/bedford-stuyvesant-diverse-and-changing.html |access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> The people who bought these houses were generally upper-middle-class families, mostly lawyers, shopkeepers, and merchants of German and Irish descent, with a sprinkling of English people; there were also a few professionals. A contemporary description calls it a very well kept residential neighborhood, typical of the general description of Brooklyn as \"a town of homes and churches.\"\n\nBuilt in 1863, the [[Capitoline Grounds]] were the home of the [[Brooklyn Atlantics]] baseball team.<ref name=\"covehurst\">{{cite web |url=http://www.covehurst.net/ddyte/brooklyn/capitoline.html |title=Capitoline Grounds |last=Ross |first=Andrew |author2=David Dyte |publisher=covehurst.net |accessdate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> The grounds were bordered by Nostrand Avenue, Halsey Street, Marcy Avenue, and Putnam Avenue.<ref name=covehurst/> During the winters, the operators would flood the area and open an ice-skating arena. The grounds were demolished in 1880.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n[[File:Ch of Pilgrim Holiness 24 Arlington Pl Bk jeh.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Macon Street and Arlington Place]]\n\nIn 1890, the [[city of Brooklyn]] founded another subsection [[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]], a working-class predominantly Italian enclave. In the last decades of the 19th century, with the advent of electric [[tram|trolleys]] and the [[Kings County Elevated Railway|Fulton Street Elevated]], Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant became a [[working class|working-class]] and [[middle class|middle-class]] [[commuter town|bedroom community]] for those working in downtown Brooklyn and [[Manhattan]] in New York City. At that time, most of the pre-existing wooden homes were destroyed and replaced with [[brownstone]] [[Terraced house|rowhouses]].\n\n===20th century===\n\n====1900s to 1950s====\nIn 1907, the completion of the [[Williamsburg Bridge]] facilitated the immigration of Jews and Italians from the [[Lower East Side]] of Manhattan.<ref name=\"rfk\">{{cite book |last=Newfield |first=Jack |title=Robert Kennedy: A Memoir |publisher=Penguin Group |edition=reprint |date=1988 |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyme000newf/page/87 87\u2013109] |isbn=0-452-26064-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyme000newf/page/87 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1930s, major changes took place due to the [[Great Depression]] years. Immigrants from the American South and the [[Caribbean]] brought the neighborhood's black population to around 30,000, making it the second largest [[Black people|Black]] community in the city at the time. During [[World War II]], the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]] attracted many black New Yorkers to the neighborhood as an opportunity for employment, while the relatively prosperous war economy enabled many of the Jewish and Italian residents to move to Queens and Long Island. By 1950, the number of black residents had risen to 155,000, comprising about 55 percent of the population of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.<ref name= rfk/> In the 1950s, [[real estate agents]] and [[Speculation|speculators]] employed [[blockbusting]] to turn a profit. As a result, formerly middle-class white homes were being turned over to poorer black families. By 1960, eighty-five percent of the population was black.<ref name= rfk/>\n\n====1960s====\n[[File:Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant riot of 1964.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Confrontation between black protesters and police at Fulton Street and Nostrand Avenue during the 1964 riot]]\nGang wars erupted in 1961 in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, and Alfred E. Clark of ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to it as \"Brooklyn's Little [[Harlem]].\"<ref>Clark, Alfred E. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1961/05/02/archives/gang-wars-upset-area-in-brooklyn-bedford-stuyvesant-tense-following.html GANG WARS UPSET AREA IN BROOKLYN; Bedford&nbsp;\u2013 Stuyvesant Tense Following Two Slayings].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. Tuesday May 2, 1961. Page 31. Retrieved on January 22, 2010.</ref> One of the first urban [[riot]]s of the era took place there due to [[Society|social]] and [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] divisions in the city contributed to the tensions. Race riots  between the NYPD and the city's black community were strained due to perceptions of the NYPD as being oppressive and racially biased, and at that time, few black policemen were present on the force.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873963-6,00.html \"No Place Like Home\"]. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]].'' July 31, 1964.</ref> Predominantly black neighborhoods received disproportionate rates of arrests and prosecutions for drug-related crimes, and the NYPD's 79th Precinct in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant was one of the only three police precincts in the NYPD where black police officers were allowed to patrol.<ref>Darien, Andrew. [http://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/CLD_RLR_s00_police.pdf \"Police Fraternity and the Politics of Race and Class in New York City, 1941\u20131960\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021083109/http://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/CLD_RLR_s00_police.pdf |date=October 21, 2013 }}. ''Regional Labor Review''. Spring 2000.</ref> Race riots followed in 1967 and 1968, as part of the [[political]] and racial tensions in the United States of the era, aggravated by continued high unemployment among blacks, continued [[de facto]] [[segregation in housing]], and the failure to enforce [[civil rights]] laws.\n\n[[File:Kennedy discusses school with young Ricky Taggart.jpg|thumb|250px|Senator [[Robert F. Kennedy]] speaks with a boy while touring Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant]]With the help of local activists and politicians, such as Civil Court Judge [[Thomas R. Jones (judge)|Thomas Jones]], grassroots organizations of community members and businesses willing to aid were formed and began the rebuilding of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. In 1965, [[Andrew W. Cooper]], a journalist from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, brought suit under the [[Voting Rights Act]] against racial [[gerrymandering]]<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2002_Jan_30/ai_82336550 |title=The City Sun Editor-in-Chief Andrew W. Cooper dies |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |date=January 30, 2002 |publisher=Business Wire}}</ref> under the grounds that Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant was divided among five [[congressional district]]s, each with a white [[United States House of Representatives|representative]].<ref name=\"Answers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.answers.com/topic/andrew-w-cooper |title=Andrew W. Cooper |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |publisher=Answers.com}}</ref> It resulted in the creation of [[New York's 12th Congressional District]] and the election in 1968 of [[Shirley Chisholm]], the [[List of African-American firsts|first black woman]] and [[West Indian American]] ever elected to the [[United States Congress|US Congress]].<ref name=\"Lueck\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/30/nyregion/andrew-w-cooper-74-pioneering-journalist.html |title=Andrew W. Cooper, 74, Pioneering Journalist |accessdate=January 30, 2009 |last=Lueck |first=Thomas J. |date=January 30, 2002 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, [[Robert F. Kennedy]], U.S. senator for New York state, launched a study of problems facing the urban poor in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, which received almost no federal aid and was the city's largest non-white community.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paul F. O'Rourke |title=A Health Project for Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant |quote= |newspaper=RFK Senate Legislature Papers (SLP), Box 11, [[JFK Library]] |year=1968 |pages= |url=https://www.zotero.org/andrewcummins/items/itemKey/M4ZFRHE5 |accessdate=February 5, 2012|author-link=Paul F. O'Rourke }}</ref><ref>Schlesinger, Arthur{{cite book |title=Robert Kennedy and his times |page=[https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyhis01schl/page/786 786] |isbn=0-618-21928-5 |last1=Schlesinger |first1=Arthur Meier |year=2002 |url=https://archive.org/details/robertkennedyhis01schl/page/786 }}</ref> Under Kennedy's leadership and with the help of activists, the [[Bedford Stuyvesant Restoration Corporation]] was established as the United States\u2019 first community development corporation.<ref name=\"Spellen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.brownstoner.com/history/walkabout-savin-3/ |title=Bed Stuy Brooklyn History |work=Brownstoner |author=Spellen, Suzanne |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2016}}</ref> The Manhattan-based Development and Services Corporation (D&S) was established with business, banking and professional leaders which advised and raised private funding for the BSRC's projects.<ref name=\"Spellen\" /> The abandoned Sheffield Milk bottling plant on Fulton Street was turned into the BSRC offices in 1967,<ref name=Spellen /> and the BSRC bought and renovated many housing units as well as administered a $73 million mortgage assistance program to encourage African-American homeownership.<ref name=Spellen /> The BSRC also implemented a controversial plan by [[I.M. Pei]] to close off St. Marks Avenue and Prospect Place, between Kingston and Albany Avenues, and convert these into community spaces.<ref name=\"Spellen\" />\n\n====1970s and 1980s====\n[[File:Children at Kosciusko pool.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Youth play in an adventure playground at the \"K-pool\" public swimming pool in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant in July 1974.  Photo by [[Danny Lyon]].]]\n\nIn the late 1980s, resistance to illegal drug-dealing included, according to Rita Webb Smith, following police arrests with a civilian [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]] 40-day patrol of several blocks near a mosque, the same group having earlier evicted drug sellers at a landlord's request, although that also resulted in arrests of the Muslims for \"burglary, menacing and possession of weapons\", resulting in a [[probation]]ary sentence.<ref>Smith, Rita Webb, & Tony Chapelle, ''The Woman Who Took Back Her Streets: One Woman Fights The Drug Wars And Rebuilds Her Community'' (Far Hills, New Jersey: New Horizon Press, 1991 ({{ISBN|0-88282-065-6}})), pp.&nbsp;289\u2013291 (quoting p.&nbsp;290) (author Smith leader of a [[Harlem]] anti-drug campaign).</ref>\n\n=== Recent history{{anchor|Recent trends}} ===\n====2000s{{anchor|Early 2000s gentrification}}====\nBeginning in the 2000s, the neighborhood began to experience [[gentrification]].<ref name=urbanology/> The two significant reasons for this were the affordable housing stock consisting of [[brownstone]] [[Terraced house|rowhouses]] located on quiet tree-lined streets, as well as the marked decrease of crime in the neighborhood. Many properties were renovated after the start of the 21st century, and new retailers began moving to the neighborhood. There was a belief that neighborhood change would benefit all residents of the area, bringing with it greater neighborhood safety, more local jobs, and retail demand on major commercial strips. As such, both the Fulton Street and Nostrand Avenue commercial corridors became part of the Bed-Stuy Gateway Business Improvement District, bringing along with it a beautification project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.restorationplaza.org/about/news/beautification-of-bed-stuy|title=Beautification of the Bed-Stuy Gateway streetscape receives major financial support - Bedford Stuyvesant Restoration|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806221226/http://www.restorationplaza.org/about/news/beautification-of-bed-stuy|archive-date=August 6, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Through a series of \"wallscapes\" (large outdoor [[mural]]s), the campaign honored famous community members, including community activist and poet [[June Jordan]], activist [[Hattie Carthan]], and rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]<ref>Notorious B.I.G.'s residence: {{cite news|url=http://www.theinsider.com/news/1548004_Much_change_in_Biggie_Smalls_neighborhood|title=Much change in Biggie Smalls' neighborhood|last=Franklin|first=Marcus|date=January 17, 2009|accessdate=October 10, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212112344/http://www.theinsider.com/news/1548004_Much_change_in_Biggie_Smalls_neighborhood|archivedate=February 12, 2010|publisher=The Insider|agency=Associated Press}}<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;Other than Notorious B.I.G.'s residence: [https://web.archive.org/web/20060303221200/http://gothamgazette.com/community/36/news/1340 Grace, Melissa, ''New P.R. Campaign: \"Bed-Stuy and Proud of it\"'', in ''Gotham Gazette'', March 10, 2005, from ''Daily News'', at ''Wayback Machine'', March 3, 2006, 10:12:00 p.m.], as accessed October 20, 2013.</ref> The campaign sought to show off the area's positive accomplishments.<ref>Grace, Melissa, ''New P.R. Campaign: \"Bed-Stuy and Proud of it\"'', ''op. cit.''</ref>[[File:Bedstuybrownstone1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A row of brownstones on Jefferson Avenue between Lewis and Stuyvesant Avenues in Bedford Stuyvesant, 2006]]\n\nSeveral long-time residents and business owners expressed concern that they would be priced out by newcomers, whom they disparagingly characterize as \"[[yuppie]]s and [[buppie]]s [black urban professionals]\", according to one neighborhood blog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2013/01/bed_stuy_billboards.html|title=Series of Brooklyn Billboards Put Racial Inequity on Display|last=admin|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> They feared that the neighborhood's ethnic character would be lost. However, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's population has experienced much less displacement of the black population than other areas of Brooklyn, such as [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]] and [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn|Cobble Hill]].<ref>http://66.111.110.102/newyork/DetailsAr.do?file=features/499/499.thebattlefor.html {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928055859/http://66.111.110.102/newyork/DetailsAr.do?file=features%2F499%2F499.thebattlefor.html |date=September 28, 2007 }}  \"The Battle for Bed-Stuy: The Price of Art\" [[Time Out (company)|Time Out New York]] April 2005</ref> Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant saw more foreign-born [[Afro-Caribbean]] and [[Ethnic groups of Africa|African]] residents as well as  [[upwardly mobile]] [[middle class|middle-income]] [[African-American|African American]] families, as well as immigrants from [[Africa]] and the [[Caribbean]]. Surrounding neighborhoods in northern and eastern Brooklyn have a combined population of about 940,000 and are roughly 82% black, making them the largest concentration of African Americans in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=ChangeGeoContext&geo_id=86000US11203&_geoContext=01000US%7C04000US36%7C05000US36047&_street=&_county=&_cityTown=&_state=04000US36&_zip=11203&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=010&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null%3Anull&_keyword=&_industry= |title=American FactFinder |publisher=Factfinder.census.gov |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2005, the NYPD designated the Fulton Street\u2013Nostrand Avenue business district in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant as an \"Impact Zone\", which directed significantly increased levels of police protection and resources to the area for two consecutive 6-month periods, resulting in a 15% decrease in crime within one year. Despite the improvements and increasing stability of the community, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant has continued to be stigmatized in some circles. In March 2005 a campaign was launched to supplant the \"Bed-Stuy, Do-or-Die\" slogan with \"Bed-Stuy, and Proud of It\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Grace|first=Melissa|title=Say It Loud: Bed-stuy And Proud|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2005-03-10/local/18287657_1_new-slogan-bed-stuy-proud|publisher=NY Daily News|accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> Violent crime also remains a problem in the area, and the two precincts that cover Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant reported a combined 37 murders in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs079pct.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220350/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs079pct.pdf |archivedate=May 27, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs081pct.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140917190508/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs081pct.pdf |archivedate=September 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lafayette Patchen jeh.JPG|thumb|right|220px|The view southeast across Lafayette Avenue, looking toward Patchen Avenue]]\n\n====2010s{{anchor|Early 2010s gentrification}}====\nDespite the [[Great Recession|largest recession]] to hit the United States in the last 70 years, gentrification continued steadily, and the blocks north of the Nostrand Avenue/Fulton Street intersection and west of Fulton Street and Stuyvesant Avenue were particularly impacted. In 2011, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant listed three [[Zagat]]-rated restaurants for the first time. Today there are over ten Zagat-rated establishments,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zagat.com/search/place/?text=bedford-stuyvesant |title=Best Places in New York City &#124; Foodie, Nightlife & Shopping News |publisher=Zagat.com |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> and in June 2013, 7 Arlington Place, the setting for [[Spike Lee]]'s 1994 film ''[[Crooklyn]],'' was sold for over its asking price, at $1.7 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130617/bed-stuy/crooklyn-house-sells-for-17m-reflection-of-bed-stuy-real-estate-boom|title='Crooklyn' House Sells for $1.7M, a Reflection of Bed-Stuy Real Estate Boom|date=June 17, 2013|publisher=DNAinfo.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324033710/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130617/bed-stuy/crooklyn-house-sells-for-17m-reflection-of-bed-stuy-real-estate-boom|archivedate=March 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA diverse mix of students, [[hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipsters]], artists, creative professionals, architects, and attorneys of all races continue to move to the neighborhood. A business improvement district has been launched along the Fulton and Nostrand Corridor with a redesigned streetscape to include new street trees, street furniture, [[paver (flooring)|pavers]], and signage and improved cleanliness in an effort to attract more business investment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycedc.com/project/bedford-stuyvesant-streetscape-project |title=Bedford-Stuyvesant Streetscape Project |publisher=NYCEDC |date=January 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Major infrastructure upgrades have been performed or are in progress, such as [[Select Bus Service]] [[bus rapid transit]] on the {{NYC bus link|B44}} route along Nostrand and Bedford Avenues, which began operating in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/brt/html/routes/nostrand.shtml |title=Bus Rapid Transit - Nostrand/Rogers Avenues |publisher=Nyc.gov |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Other infrastructure upgrades in the neighborhood includes major sewer and water modernization projects,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkanplumbing.com/new-sewer-water-lines-brooklyn-ny-installation/ |title=New Brooklyn Sewer Connections, New Brooklyn Water Lines |publisher=Balkanplumbing.com |date=October 10, 2012 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> as well as fiber-optic and cable service upgrades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newscenter.verizon.com/press-releases/verizon/2010/verizon-continues-rollout-of.html |title=Verizon &#124; Verizon Continues Rollout of FiOS TV in New York City |publisher=Newscenter.verizon.com |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Improved natural and organic produce continue to become available at local delis and grocers, the farmer's market on Malcolm X Boulevard, and through the Bed-Stuy Farm Share.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bed Stuy Farm Share |url=http://www.bedstuyfarmshare.org/ |title=Bed Stuy Farm Share |publisher=Bed Stuy Farm Share |date= |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> [[FreshDirect]] services the neighborhood, and a large member constituency of the adjacent Greene-Hill Food Coop are from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant.\n\n==Subsections==\n\n===Neighborhoods===\nBedford is located toward the western end of Bedford-Stuyvesant. Before the [[American Revolutionary War]] times, it was the first settlement to the east of the [[Political subdivisions of New York State|Village]] of Brooklyn. It was originally part of the old village of Bedford, which was centered near today's Bedford Avenue\u2013Fulton Street intersection. The area \"extends from Monroe Street on the north to Macon Street and Verona Place on the south, and from just east of Bedford Avenue eastward to Tompkins Avenue,\" according to the Landmarks Preservation Commission.<ref>[http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2514.pdf Bedford Historic District: Designation Report], December 8, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/05/nyregion/in-bedford-stuyvesant-a-black-stronghold-a-growing-pool-of-whites.html|title=Striking Change in Bedford-Stuyvesant as the White Population Soars|author=Sam Roberts|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 4, 2011|quote=The extent of racial integration, so far, has been mixed in the more rapidly changing Bedford section, which the city's Planning Department defines roughly as bounded by Throop, Classon and Flushing Avenues and Fulton Street.}}</ref> Bedford is adjacent to Williamsburg, Crown Heights, and Clinton Hill.<ref name=\"Freudenheim\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RuUCDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA64#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Brooklyn Experience: The Ultimate Guide to Neighborhoods & Noshes, Culture & the Cutting Edge|author=Ellen Freudenheim|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2016|page=64|isbn=9780813577456}}</ref>\n\nStuyvesant Heights is located toward the southern-central section of Bedford-Stuyvesant. It has historically been an African-American enclave. It derives its name from Stuyvesant Avenue, its principal thoroughfare. It was originally part of the outlying farm area of Bedford for most of its early history. A low-rise residential district of three- and four-story masonry row houses and apartment buildings with commercial ground floors, it was developed mostly between 1870 and 1920,<ref name=\"Freudenheim\" /><ref>[http://home2.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/STUYVESANT_HEIGHTS_HISTORIC_DISTRICT.pdf Stuyvesant Heights Historic District: Designation Report], September 14, 1971.</ref><ref>[https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/plans/bedford-stuyvesant/bed_stuy.pdf Bedford-Stuyvesant South Rezoning - Approved!]</ref> mainly between 1895 and 1900.<ref name=\"Expanded\" /> The Stuyvesant Heights Historic District is located within the area bounded roughly by Tompkins Avenue on the west, Macon and Halsey Streets on the north, [[Utica Avenue|Malcolm X Boulevard]] on the east, and [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]] on the south.<ref name=\"Expanded\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/28/archives/-real-nice-community-now-historic.html|title='Real Nice' Community Now 'Historic'|author=Michael J. Hall|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 28, 1971}}</ref>\n\n[[Ocean Hill, Brooklyn|Ocean Hill]] is located toward the eastern end Ocean Hill received its name in 1890 for being slightly hilly. Hence it was [[Subdivision (land)|subdivided]] from the larger community of Stuyvesant Heights. From the beginning of the 20th century to the 1960s Ocean Hill was an Italian enclave. By the late 1960s Ocean Hill and Bedford-Stuyvesant proper together formed the largest [[African American]] community in the [[United States]].\n\n[[Weeksville, Brooklyn|Weeksville]] is located toward the southeast. Weeksville was named after an ex-slave<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/save-americas-treasures/success-stories/weeksville.html |title=Plan your next trip with the National Trust &#124; National Trust for Historic Preservation |accessdate=April 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222185205/http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/save-americas-treasures/success-stories/weeksville.html |archivedate=December 22, 2014 }}</ref> from [[Virginia]], who in 1838<ref name=\"nytimes_20050605\">{{cite news |last=Ramirez |first=Anthony |title=Haven for Blacks in Civil War Riots Now Safeguards History |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 5, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/05/nyregion/05weeksville.html |accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> bought a plot of land and founded Weeksville.\n\n===Historic district===\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Stuyvesant Heights Historic District\n| nrhp_type      = hd\n| image          = Decatur Stuyvesant Heights HD 2.JPG\n| caption        = On Decatur Street\n| location       = Roughly bounded by Macon, Tompkins, Decatur, Lewis, Chauncey, and Stuyvesant, [[New York, New York]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|40|40|52|N|73|56|14|W|display=inline}}\n| locmapin       = New York City\n| built          = 1870\n| architecture   = Italianate, Queen Anne, Romanesque\n| added          = December 4, 1975\n| area           = {{convert|42|acre|sigfig=2}}\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum         = 75001193<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Stuyvesant Heights Historic District (Boundary Increase)\n| embed          = yes\n| nrhp_type      = hd\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| location       = Roughly, Decatur St. from Tompkins to Lewis Aves., [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| architect      = multiple\n| architecture   = Italianate, Second Empire, Queen Anne\n| added          = November 15, 1996\n| area           = {{convert|10|acre|sigfig=2}}\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum         = 96001355<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n| nocat          = yes\n}}\n}}\nThe Stuyvesant Heights [[Historic district (United States)|Historic District]] in Bedford-Stuyvesant comprises 577 contributing residential buildings built between about 1870 and 1900.  The district encompasses 17 individual blocks (13 identified in 1975 and four new in 1996).  The buildings within the district primarily comprise two- and three-storey [[Terraced houses|rowhouses]] with high basements, with a few multiple dwellings and institutional structures. The district includes the [[Our Lady of Victory Church (Brooklyn, New York)|Our Lady of Victory Catholic Church]], the [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Romanesque Revival]] style Mount Lebanon Baptist Church, and St. Phillip's Episcopal Church.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3289|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Stuyvesant Heights Historic District|date=August 1972|accessdate=March 19, 2011|author=Stephen Lash and Betty Ezequelle|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019112759/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3289|archivedate=October 19, 2012}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3287|title=Accompanying nine photos|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924141549/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3287|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3359|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:Stuyvesant Heights Historic District (Boundary Increase)|date=September 1996|accessdate=March 19, 2011|author=Peter D. Shaver|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019112822/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3359|archivedate=October 19, 2012}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3360|title=Accompanying seven photos|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924141629/http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3360|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1975 and expanded in 1996.<ref name=\"nris\"/> Bedford Stuyvesant/Expanded Stuyvesant Heights Historic District was designated on April 16, 2013 and extended the district north to Jefferson Ave, east to Malcolm X Blvd, and west to Tompkins Avenue.<ref name=\"Expanded\">{{cite web|url = http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2496.pdf|title = Bedford Stuyvesant/Expanded Stuyvesant Heights Historic District \u2013 Designation Report|date = April 16, 2013|accessdate = April 20, 2015|website = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160313091831/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2496.pdf|archive-date = March 13, 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"100px\">\nFile:Miracle Temple Brooklyn.JPG|Miracle Temple\nFile:Decatur Stuyvesant Heights HD 1.JPG|On Decatur Street\nFile:200 block Decatur Brooklyn.JPG |On Decatur Street\nFile:St Philips Brooklyn.JPG|St. Phillip's Episcopal Church\nFile:Mt Lebanon Brooklyn 2.JPG |Mt. Lebanon Baptist Church\nFile:Mt Lebanon Brooklyn 1.JPG |Mt. Lebanon Baptist Church\nFile:On Lewis Brooklyn.JPG|On Lewis Street\n</gallery>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nThe entirety of Community Board 3 had 152,403 inhabitants as of [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|NYC Health]]'s 2018 Community Health Profile, with an average life expectancy of 76.8 years.<ref name=\"CHP2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/data/2018chp-bk3.pdf|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant (Including Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Kensington and Ocean Parkway)|last=|first=|date=2018|website=nyc.gov|publisher=NYC Health|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>{{Rp|2, 20}} This is lower than the median life expectancy of 81.2 for all New York City neighborhoods.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/tcny/community-health-assessment-plan.pdf|title=2016-2018 Community Health Assessment and Community Health Improvement Plan: Take Care New York 2020|last=|first=|date=2016|website=[[government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]]|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|53 (PDF p. 84)}}<ref>{{cite web | title=New Yorkers are living longer, happier and healthier lives | website=New York Post | date=June 4, 2017 | url=https://nypost.com/2017/06/04/new-yorkers-are-living-longer-happier-and-healthier-lives/ | access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Most inhabitants are middle-aged adults and youth: 24% are between the ages of 0\u201317, 33% between 25\u201344, and 22% between 45\u201364. The ratio of college-aged and elderly residents was lower, at 10% and 11% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|2}}\n\nAs of 2016, the median [[household income]] in Community Board 3 was $51,907.<ref name=\"CB3PUMA\">{{cite web|url=http://censusreporter.org/profiles/79500US3604003-nyc-brooklyn-community-district-3-bedford-stuyvesant-puma-ny/|title=Census profile: NYC-Brooklyn Community District 3--Bedford-Stuyvesant PUMA, NY|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, an estimated 23% of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant residents lived in poverty, compared to 21% in all of Brooklyn and 20% in all of New York City. One in eight residents (13%) were unemployed, compared to 9% in the rest of both Brooklyn and New York City. Rent burden, or the percentage of residents who have difficulty paying their rent, is 53% in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, higher than the citywide and boroughwide rates of 52% and 51% respectively. Based on this calculation, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is considered to be [[gentrification|gentrifying]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|7}}\n\n===Demographic trends===\nThe 1790 census records of Bedford lists 132 freemen and 72 slaves. Rapid population growth followed major improvements to public transportation. By 1873, Bed-Stuy's (predominantly white) population was 14,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theweeklynabe.com/2012/06/23/bed-stuy-brooklyn-a-very-brief-history/|title=Bed-Stuy: a very brief history|last=Williams|first=Keith|website=The Weekly Nabe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> In the early 1900s, prosperous black families began buying up the mansions of Bed-Stuy, many of which were designed by prominent architects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.6sqft.com/bed-stuy-from-harlem-and-hip-hop-to-hipsters-hassids-and-high-rents/|title=Bed-Stuy: From Harlem and Hip-Hop to Hipsters, Hassids and High Rents|website=6sqft|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> The population was quick to grow, but it wasn\u2019t until the 1930s that Bed-Stuy\u2019s black population boomed. Following the introduction of the IND Fulton Street Line (a.k.a. the A/C line) in 1936, African-Americans left crowded Harlem in search of better housing opportunities. Bed-Stuy quickly became the second destination for black New Yorkers and the ''New York Times'' even dubbed it \u201cLittle Harlem\u201d in 1961.\n\nAfter a large decline during the 1970s (mirroring the citywide decline), the population in Bedford Stuyvesant grew by 34 percent between 1980 and 2015 (faster than the citywide growth rate of 21 percent) to reach 150,900 residents. The population has increased by 25 percent in just the past 15 years, more than three times faster than the citywide rate. The ethnic and racial mix of the population has undergone dramatic changes in the past 15 years as the neighborhood has attracted new residents. According to data from the U.S. Census Bureau, three-quarters of the residents identified as black or African-American in 2000, but this share had declined to less than half of the population by 2015. In 2015 (the latest year for which census data are available), one-quarter of the residents were white and nearly one-fifth were Hispanic. By comparison, in 2000, less than 3 percent of the population was white (the Hispanic share of the population has remained relatively unchanged). The Asian population has grown, but remains relatively small, making up less than 3 percent of the neighborhood<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osc.state.ny.us/osdc/rpt5-2018.pdf|title=An Economic Snapshot of the Bedford-Stuyvesant Neighborhood|last=DiNapoli|first=Thomas P.|date=September 2017|website=Office of the New York State Comptroller|access-date=August 8, 2019}}</ref> According to the US Census Bureau, in 2016 the population was 49% Black, 27% [[Non-Hispanic whites|White]], 19% Hispanic, 3% Asian, and 2% other or from two or more races.<ref name=\"CB3PUMA\"/>\n\n== Politics ==\nThe neighborhood is part of [[New York's 8th congressional district]],<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012c/CD_map_rep_08.pdf Congressional District 8], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012c/CD_nyc.pdf New York City Congressional Districts], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> represented by Democrat [[Hakeem Jeffries]] {{as of|2013|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. House Election Results 2018 | website=The New York Times | date=January 28, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-house-elections.html | access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref> It is also part of the 18th and 25th [[New York State Senate|State Senate]] districts,<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_map_rep_18.pdf Senate District 18], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_map_rep_25.pdf Senate District 25], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012s/SD_nyc.pdf 2012 Senate District Maps: New York City], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed November 17, 2018.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Julia Salazar]] and [[Velmanette Montgomery]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/district/18|title=NY Senate District 18|author=|date=|website=NY State Senate|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/district/25|title=NY Senate District 25|author=|date=|website=NY State Senate|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> and the 54th, 55th, and 56th [[New York State Assembly|State Assembly]] districts,<ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_054.pdf Assembly District 54], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_055.pdf Assembly District 55], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.\n*[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_map_rep_056.pdf Assembly District 56], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.latfor.state.ny.us/maps/2012a/AD_nyc.pdf 2012 Assembly District Maps: New York City], New York State Legislative Task Force on Demographic Research and Reapportionment. Accessed November 17, 2018.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Erik Dilan]], [[Latrice Walker]], and [[Tremaine Wright]].<ref>{{cite web | title=New York State Assembly Member Directory | website=Assembly Member Directory | url=https://nyassembly.gov/mem/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Bed-Stuy is located in the [[New York City Council]]'s 36th and 41st districts,<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dc/downloads/pdf/brooklyn.pdf Current City Council Districts for Kings County], [[New York City]]. Accessed May 5, 2017.</ref> represented respectively by Democrats [[Robert Cornegy]] and [[Alicka Ampry-Samuel]].<ref>{{cite web | title=District 36 | website=[[New York City Council]] | date=March 25, 2018 | url=https://council.nyc.gov/district-36/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=District 41 | website=[[New York City Council]] | date=March 25, 2018 | url=https://council.nyc.gov/district-41/ | access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Police and crime ==\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is patrolled by two precincts of the [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Find Your Precinct and Sector - NYPD | website=www.nyc.gov | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/find-your-precinct.page | access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref> The 81st Precinct is located at 30 Ralph Avenue, serving the area east of Marcus Garvey Boulevard,<ref name=\"NYPD 81st Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/81st-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 81st Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> and the 79th Precinct is located at 263 Tompkins Avenue, serving the area west of Marcus Garvey Boulevard.<ref name=\"NYPD 79th Precinct\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/patrol/precincts/79th-precinct.page|title=NYPD \u2013 79th Precinct|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nyc.gov|access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe area collectively covered by the 79th and 81st Precincts ranked 62nd safest out of 69 patrol areas for per-capita crime in 2010. While total crime has decreased since the 1990s, it is still higher in Bed-Stuy than in much of the rest of the city.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/bedford-stuyvesant|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant \u2013 DNAinfo.com Crime and Safety Report|website=www.dnainfo.com|access-date=October 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430140105/http://www.dnainfo.com/crime-safety-report/brooklyn/bedford-stuyvesant/|archive-date=April 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, in 2016, major crime dropped 11 percent in the 81st Precinct, marking the greatest reduction in north Brooklyn's 10 precincts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170113/bed-stuy/safety-eastern-bed-stuy-stuyvesant-heights-81st-precinct|title=Bed-Stuy Precinct Leads North Brooklyn in Major Crime Decrease, Police Say|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=2019-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716045938/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20170113/bed-stuy/safety-eastern-bed-stuy-stuyvesant-heights-81st-precinct/|archive-date=July 16, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>  With a non-fatal assault rate of 117 per 100,000 people, Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant's rate of violent crimes per capita is greater than that of the city as a whole. The incarceration rate of 1,045 per 100,000 people is higher than that of the city as a whole.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\nThe 79th Precinct has a lower crime rate than in the 1990s, with crimes across all categories having decreased by 78.8% between 1990 and 2018. The precinct saw 9 murders, 27 rapes, 309 robberies, 343 felony assaults, 301 burglaries, 484 grand larcenies, and 72 grand larcenies auto in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-079pct.pdf|title=79th Precinct CompStat Report|date=|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The 81st Precinct had a relatively smaller crime decrease of 73.9% between 1990 and 2018. The precinct saw 10 murders, 25 rapes, 234 robberies, 274 felony assaults, 218 burglaries, 399 grand larcenies, and 48 grand larcenies auto in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/nypd/downloads/pdf/crime_statistics/cs-en-us-081pct.pdf|title=81st Precinct CompStat Report|date=|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Fire safety ==\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] (FDNY) operates seven fire stations in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant:<ref>{{cite web | title=NYPD Precincts & Firehouses - Brooklyn CB 3 | website=Welcome to NYC.gov | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/brooklyncb3/resources/nypd-precincts-firehouses.page | access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite FDNY locations}}</ref>\n* Ladder Co. 102 \u2013 850 Bedford Avenue \n* Engine Co. 230 \u2013 701 Park Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 230 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e230.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Battalion 57/Engine Co. 235 \u2013 206 Monroe Street<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 235/Battalion 7 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e235.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 217 \u2013 940 DeKalb Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 217 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e217.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 214/Ladder Co. 111 \u2013 495 Hancock Street<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 214/Ladder Company 111 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e214.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Battalion 37/Engine Co. 222 \u2013 32 Ralph Avenue<ref>{{cite web | website=FDNYtrucks.com | title=Engine Company 222/Battalion 37 | url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e222.htm | access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Engine Co. 233/Ladder Co. 176/Field Comm Unit 1 \u2013 25 Rockaway Avenue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fdnytrucks.com/files/html/brooklyn/e233.htm|title=Engine Company 233/Ladder Company 176/Field Comm Unit 1|website=FDNYtrucks.com|access-date=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Health ==\n[[Preterm birth|Preterm]] and teenage births are more common in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant than in other places citywide. In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, there were 95 preterm births per 1,000 live births (compared to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and 26.9 teenage births per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide).<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|11}} Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant has a relatively low population of residents who are [[Health insurance coverage in the United States|uninsured]], or who receive healthcare through [[Medicaid]].<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.health.ny.gov/health_care/medicaid/redesign/dsrip/pps_applications/docs/maimonides_medical_center/3.8_maimonides_cna.pdf New York City Health Provider Partnership Brooklyn Community Needs Assessment: Final Report], [[New York Academy of Medicine]] (October 3, 2014).</ref> In 2018, this population of uninsured residents was estimated to be 11%, which is slightly lower than the citywide rate of 12%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|14}}\n\nThe concentration of [[particulates|fine particulate matter]], the deadliest type of [[air pollution|air pollutant]], in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant is {{convert|0.0081|mg/m3|oz/ft3}}, higher than the citywide and boroughwide averages.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|9}} Nineteen percent of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant residents are [[Smoking|smokers]], which is higher than the city average of 14% of residents being smokers.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, 29% of residents are [[Obesity|obese]], 13% are [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetic]], and 34% have [[hypertension|high blood pressure]]\u2014compared to the citywide averages of 24%, 11%, and 28% respectively.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|16}} In addition, 22% of children are obese, compared to the citywide average of 20%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|12}}\n\nEighty-four percent of residents eat some fruits and vegetables every day, which is slightly lower than the city's average of 87%. In 2018, 76% of residents described their health as \"good,\" \"very good,\" or \"excellent,\" slightly less than the city's average of 78%.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|13}} For every supermarket in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, there are 57 [[convenience store|bodegas]].<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|10}}\n\nThere are several hospitals in the Bed-Stuy area, including the [[Woodhull Medical Center]] and the [[Interfaith Medical Center]].<ref name=\":14\"/>{{rp|19\u201320}}\n\n== Post offices and ZIP codes ==\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is covered by four primary [[ZIP Code]]s (11206, 11216, 11221, 11223) and parts of three other ZIP Codes (11205, 11213, and 11233). The northern part of the neighborhood is covered by 11206; the central part, by 11221; the southwestern part, by 11216; and the southeastern part, by 11223. In addition, the ZIP Code 11205 covers several blocks in the northwestern corner of Bed-Stuy, and 11213 includes several blocks in the extreme southern portion of the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bedford-Stuyvesant, New York City-Brooklyn, New York Zip Code Boundary Map (NY) | website=United States Zip Code Boundary Map (USA) | url=https://www.zipmap.net/New_York/Kings_County/Z_Bedford-Stuyvesant.htm | access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] operates four post offices nearby: the Restoration Plaza Station at 1360 Fulton Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Location Details: Restoration Plaza | website=USPS.com | url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1379126&locationName=RESTORATION+PLAZA&address2=&address1=1360+FULTON+ST+STE+1 | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> the Shirley A Chisholm Station at 1915 Fulton Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Location Details: Shirley A Chisholm | website=USPS.com | url=https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1383815&locationName=SHIRLEY+A+CHISHOLM&address2=&address1=1915+FULTON+ST | access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> the Bushwick Station at 1369 Broadway,<ref>{{cite web|title=Location Details: Bushwick|url= https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1356467&locationName=BUSHWICK&address2=&address1=1369+BROADWAY|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> and the Halsey Station at 805 MacDonough Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=Location Details: Halsey|url= https://tools.usps.com/go/POLocatorDetailsAction!input.action?locationTypeQ=po&address=11225&radius=20&locationType=po&locationID=1366006&locationName=HALSEY&address2=&address1=805+MACDONOUGH+ST|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant generally has a lower ratio of college-educated residents than the rest of the city. While 35% of residents age 25 and older have a college education or higher, 21% have less than a high school education and 43% are high school graduates or have some college education. By contrast, 40% of Brooklynites and 38% of city residents have a college education or higher.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} The percentage of Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant students excelling in reading and math has been increasing, with reading achievement rising from 32 percent in 2000 to 37 percent in 2011, and math achievement rising from 23 percent to 47 percent within the same time period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://furmancenter.org/files/sotc/BK_03_11.pdf|title=Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant \u2013 BK 03|last=|first=|date=2011|website=|publisher=[[Furman Center for Real Estate and Urban Policy]]|access-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant's rate of elementary school student absenteeism is higher than the rest of New York City. In Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, 30% of elementary school students missed twenty or more days per [[school year]], compared to the citywide average of 20% of students.<ref name=\":21\" />{{Rp|24 (PDF p. 55)}}<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}} Additionally, 70% of high school students in Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant graduate on time, lower than the citywide average of 75% of students.<ref name=\"CHP2018\" />{{Rp|6}}\n\n=== Schools ===\n[[File:PS93 Prescott Nostrand Av Herkimer St jeh.jpg|thumb|PS 93, Prescott School|alt=]]\nSeveral public schools serve Bedford-Stuyvesant. The zoned high school for the neighborhood is [[Boys and Girls High School]] on [[Fulton Street (Brooklyn)|Fulton Street]]. The Brooklyn Brownstone School, a public elementary school located in the MS 35 campus on MacDonough Street, and was developed in 2008 by the Stuyvesant Heights Parents Association and the New York City Board of Education. At the eastern edge of the neighborhood is [[Paul Robeson High School for Business and Technology]].\n\nMany public schools are named after prominent African-Americans and, as stated by [[Nikole Hannah-Jones]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'', were  \"intended to evoke black uplift\".<ref name=HannahJonesneighbsch>{{cite web|author=Hannah-Jones, Nikole|authorlink=Nikole Hannah-Jones|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/12/magazine/choosing-a-school-for-my-daughter-in-a-segregated-city.html?_r=0|title=Choosing a School for My Daughter in a Segregated City|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2016-06-09|accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref> Hannah-Jones wrote in 2016 that many wealthier residents choose to use [[magnet schools]] or [[private schools]] instead of neighborhood schools.<ref name=HannahJonesneighbsch/>\n\nFor the early grades Ember Charter School for Mindful Education and [[Success Academy Charter Schools|Success Academy Bed-Stuy 1 and 2]] are charter schools. Bed-Stuy is also home to the [[Brooklyn Waldorf School]], which moved to Claver Castle (at 11 Jefferson Avenue) in 2011.\n\nOther institutions include:\n* [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High School]]\n* [[Girl's High School]]\n* [[Pratt Institute]]\n* [[Brooklyn Brownstone Elementary School]]\n* [[Weeksville Heritage Center]]\n* [[Bedford Academy High School]]\n\n=== Libraries ===\nThe [[Brooklyn Public Library]] (BPL) has four branches in Bedford-Stuyvesant:\n* The Bedford branch and Bedford Learning Center, at 496 Franklin Avenue near Fulton Street. The branch opened in 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/bedford|title=Bedford Library|date=August 17, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Marcy branch, at 617 DeKalb Avenue near Nostrand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/marcy|title=Marcy Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Macon Library|Macon branch]], at 361 Lewis Avenue near Macon Street. The branch is a [[Carnegie library]] that opened in 1907. It contains the Dionne Mack-Harvin Center, a collection dedicated to African American culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/macon|title=Macon Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Saratoga branch, at 8 Thomas S. Boyland Street near Macon Street. The branch is a Carnegie library that opened in 1909.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bklynlibrary.org/locations/saratoga|title=Saratoga Library|date=August 22, 2011|website=Brooklyn Public Library|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Bedford-Nostrand_Avenues_-_Queens_Bound_Platform.jpg\n|caption1=The [[Bedford\u2013Nostrand Avenues station]] of the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Crosstown Line]]\n|image2=LIRR 9944 (6029110921).jpg\n|caption2=The [[Nostrand Avenue station (LIRR)|Nostrand Avenue station]] of the [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n}}\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is served by the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Fulton Street Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Fulton}}), which opened in 1936. This underground line replaced the earlier, elevated [[BMT Fulton Street Line]] on May 31, 1940. The [[IND Crosstown Line]] ({{NYCS trains| Crosstown}}), running underneath Lafayette Avenue and Marcy Avenue, opened for service in 1937. The elevated [[BMT Jamaica Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Jamaica west}}) also serves the neighborhood, running alongside its northern boundary at Broadway. Additionally, the elevated [[BMT Lexington Avenue Line]] served Lexington Avenue until 1950 and the elevated [[BMT Myrtle Avenue Line]] served [[Myrtle Avenue]] to the north until 1969.\n\nBedford\u2013Stuyvesant is also served by the [[Nostrand Avenue (LIRR station)|Nostrand Avenue]] station of the [[Long Island Rail Road]].\n\nSeveral bus routes, operated by [[MTA Regional Bus Operations]], run through Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant. The {{NYC bus link|B7|B15|B43|B44|B44 SBS|B46|B46 SBS|B47|B48|B60|prose=y}} routes run primarily north to south through the neighborhood, while the {{NYC bus link|B25|B26|B38|B52|B54|prose=y}} run primarily west to east, and the {{NYC bus link|Q24}}, B46, and B47 run northwest to southeast on Broadway.<ref>{{Cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n<!-- Add only people from Bed-Stuy itself, not people who only say they are. Add only if notable, in other words, qualified for their own article in Wikipedia; see [[WP:REDLINK]] for more information. -->\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em|small=yes|rules=yes}}\n* [[Aaliyah]] (1979\u20132001), Grammy-nominated singer.<ref>Farley, Christopher John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=rwlBoSSahkYC&pg=PA20 ''Aaliyah: More Than a Woman''], p. 20. Accessed July 2, 2016. [[Simon and Schuster]], 2002. {{ISBN|9780743455664}}. \"She was born on January 16, 1979, in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood of Brooklyn, but, at the age of four, her parents relocated to the Motor City where Aaliyah spent her formative years.\"</ref>\n* [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]] (born 1994), drag queen and performer\n* [[Big Daddy Kane]] (born 1968), rapper.<ref>Gill, Lauren. [http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/39/27/dtg-bb-big-daddy-kane-concert-2016-07-01-bk.html \"Legendary Bed-Stuy rapper Big Daddy Kane performs outside former Albee Square Mall\"], ''[[The Brooklyn Paper]]'', June 28, 2016. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"Legendary Bedford-Stuyvesant-born rapper Big Daddy Kane entertained shoppers and commuters with a free show on Fulton Mall on Friday, and the wordsmith showed off just as much charisma as when he used to spit his rhymes in rap battles in Kings County\u2019s streets, according to organizers.\"</ref>\n* [[Memphis Bleek]] (born 1978), rapper.<ref>Avalone, Blake. [http://www.dubmagazine.com/home/stars/item/8449-memphis-bleek-and-the-young-gunz \"Memphis Bleek and the Young Gunz\"], ''[[DUB (magazine)]]'', May 16, 2005. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"For years, fans came to recognize the gritty Bleek as an heir to Jay\u2019s throne. With consistently impressive rhymes focusing on the contrast between the grim realities of the Bedford Stuyvesant streets and the glitz and glamour of a recording career, Memphis Bleek did not disappoint.\"</ref>\n* [[Mark Breland]] (born 1963), boxer.<ref>[[Ira Berkow|Berkow, Ira]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/28/sports/boxing-breland-returns-to-ring-modestly-in-brooklyn.html \"BOXING; Breland Returns to Ring Modestly in Brooklyn\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 28, 1996. Accessed July 2, 2016. \"Breland was back in Brooklyn, where he had started his career, coming out of the tough Tompkins projects in Bedford-Stuyvesant and going on to become a five-time New York Golden Gloves champion, the 1984 Olympic gold-medal champion, and twice the world's welterweight champ.\"</ref>\n* [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]] (born 1978), rapper{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n* [[Lil Cease]] (born 1977), rapper<ref>http://www.mtv.com/artists/lil-cease/ Lil' Cease], [[MTV]]. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Rapper Lil' Cease was born and raised in Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant area, at age 15 becoming a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of the Notorious B.I.G.\"</ref>\n* [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), congresswoman<ref>http://history.house.gov/People/Listing/C/CHISHOLM,-Shirley-Anita-(C000371)/ CHISHOLM, Shirley Anita], [[United States House of Representatives]] History, Art & Archives. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Elected in 1968 because of her roots in the Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant neighborhood, Chisholm was catapulted into the national limelight by virtue of her race, gender, and outspoken personality.\"</ref>\n* [[Imani Coppola]] (born 1978), singer-songwriter<ref>Lester, Paul. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/03/bandoftheday.culture \"No 344: Little Jackie; Today's new artist sounds like Lily Allen meets Lauryn Hill - seriously, what's not to like?\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 3, 2008. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Coppola's songs are as idiosyncratically infectious as Allen's, only instead of observations about life in LDN she's focused on the antics and mores of the Big Apple in general and the area surrounding her Bedford-Stuyvesant (Chris Rock's old stomping ground) apartment in particular.\"</ref>\n* [[Alan Dale (singer)|Alan Dale]] (1925\u20132002), singer and star of [[The Alan Dale Show]]<ref>O'Kane, Jim. Jefferson Avenue: Stories from a Brooklyn Boyhood 1941-1958. New York: Createspace, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Deemi]] (born 1980), singer<ref>Hamilton, Tiffany. [http://allhiphop.com/2005/09/23/deemi-diamond-in-the-rough/ \"Deemi: Diamond In The Rough\"], [[AllHipHop]], September 23, 2005. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Although she is from the streets, Deemi is not an emcee \u2013 and she's definitely not your usual R&B diva. Born and raised in Bedford Stuyvesant, the 24-year-old songstress definitely has a story to tell.\"</ref>\n* [[Desiigner]] (born 1997), rapper<ref>Weiner, Natalie. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7400285/desiigner-on-panda-difficult-past-kanye-west-advice \"Desiigner on His Difficult Past and How His No. 1 Hit 'Panda' Gave Him a Way Out\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)]]'', June 9, 2016. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"'Out' means out of Bedford-Stuyvesant, the Brooklyn neighborhood where Desiigner grew up.\"</ref>\n* Nelson Erazo (born 1977), professional wrestler better known by his ring name [[Homicide (wrestler)|Homicide]]{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Fabolous]] (born 1977), rapper<ref>Vasquez, Emily. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/18/nyregion/18rapper.html \"Brooklyn-Born Rapper Is Arrested After Being Shot\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 18, 2005. Accessed October 7, 2007. \"Mr. Jackson, raised in the Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, became famous in late 2001 with his debut single, \"I Can\u2019t Deny It.\"\"</ref>\n* [[Bobby Fischer]] (1943\u20132008), eleventh [[World Chess Championship|World Chess Champion]]{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[William Forsythe (actor)|William Forsythe]] (born 1955), actor\n* [[Jackie Gleason]] (1916\u201387), actor, comedian<ref>[http://www.upi.com/topic/Jackie_Gleason/ \"Jackie Gleason\"], ''[[United Press International]]''. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Carl Gordon (actor)|Carl Gordon]] (1932\u20132010), actor<ref>[[Margalit Fox|Fox, Margalit]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/23/arts/23gordon.html \"Carl Gordon, a Late-Blooming Actor, Dies at 78\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 23, 2010. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Rufus Carl Gordon Jr. was born on Jan. 20, 1932, in Goochland, Va.; he later jettisoned the 'Rufus.' When he was a child his family moved to Brooklyn, where he grew up in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.\"</ref>\n* [[Kadeem Hardison]] (born 1965), actor, portrays [[Dwayne Wayne]] on ''[[A Different World]]''<ref>Staff. [http://humormillmag.com/on-this-day-in-comedy-in-1965-kadeem-hardison-was-born/ \"On This Day In Comedy\u2026 In 1965 Kadeem Hardison Was Born!\"], Humor Mill, July 24, 2015. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Actor, director, Kadeem Hardison was born in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn New York.\"</ref>\n* [[Richie Havens]] (1941\u20132013), musician and poet<ref>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/23/arts/music/richie-havens-guitarist-and-singer-dies-at-72.html \"Richie Havens, Folk Singer Who Riveted Woodstock, Dies at 72\"], ''[[The New York Times]]', April 22, 2013. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Richard Pierce Havens was born on Jan. 21, 1941, in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, where he grew up.\"</ref>\n* [[Connie Hawkins]] (1942-2017), [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] player<ref>Segal Jonathan B. [https://www.nytimes.com/1972/03/26/archives/foul-the-connie-hawkins-story-by-david-wolf-400-pp-new-york-holt.html \"Foul!\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 26, 1972. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"To fill in the details a bit, Hawkins, the subject of ''Foul!,'' was a great black schoolyard basketball player from New York's Bedford\u2010Stuyvesant section who became, in the jivin', hand\u2010slapping, pressure\u2010cooker world of ghetto ball, a revered figure for his spectacular and flashy play.\"</ref>\n* [[Lena Horne]] (1917\u20132010), actress and singer<ref>Gavin, James. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/19/books/excerpt-stormy-weather.html \"'Stormy Weather'\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 17, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"'I came from what was called one of the First Families of Brooklyn,' Horne explained. They shunned discussing the slave ancestry that had spawned them all \u2014 'yet it was the rape of slave women by their masters which accounted for our white blood, which, in turn, made us Negro \"society.\"' Home was an immaculate four-story brownstone in Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant section.\"</ref>\n* [[Jay Z|Shawn \"Jay-Z\" Carter]] (born 1969), rapper, who lived in the [[Marcy Houses|Marcy Housing Projects]] for most of his childhood<ref>Pareles, Jon. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/arts/music/13pare.html \"An Overdog to Root For\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 9, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"His songs have told and retold the poverty-to-bling story of Shawn Carter, Jay-Z\u2019s real name, who grew up in the tough Marcy Houses in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, and dealt drugs before turning to hip-hop.\"</ref>\n* [[Jaz-O]] (born 1964), rapper{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Joey Badass]] (born 1995), rapper<ref>Tempey, Nathan. [http://gothamist.com/2015/06/06/joey_badass_is_not_excited_about_ge.php \"Interview: Joey Badass Is Not Excited About Gentrification\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025124441/http://gothamist.com/2015/06/06/joey_badass_is_not_excited_about_ge.php |date=October 25, 2016 }}, [[Gothamist]], June 6, 2015. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Joey Badass grew up Jo-Vaughn Scott in Bedford-Stuyvesant.\"</ref>\n* [[Norah Jones]] (born 1979), singer<ref>Eldredge, Barbara. [http://www.brownstoner.com/brooklyn-life/norah-jones-eat-pray-love-house-brooklyn-172-pacific-street-renovation/ \"Norah Jones Is Renovating Her Movie-Worthy, Landmarked Cobble Hill Carriage House\"], Brownstoner, March 8, 2016. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Famous musician and Bed Stuy native Norah Jones is renovating the sweet Pacific Street stable she bought last fall.\"</ref>\n* [[June Jordan]] (1936\u20132002), Caribbean American poet, novelist, journalist, biographer, dramatist, teacher and activist<ref>Lee, Felicia R. [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/04/books/a-feminist-survivor-with-the-eyes-of-a-child.html \"A Feminist Survivor With the Eyes Of a Child\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 4, 2000. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Ms. Jordan grew up in Harlem and Brooklyn, reading Shakespeare and Edgar Allan Poe before she turned 5, she says. Her family moved from a Harlem housing project to the Bedford-Stuyvesant area in Brooklyn because it seemed like a better place to raise a family.\"</ref>\n* [[Wee Willie Keeler]] (1872\u20131923), Baseball Hall-of-Famer<ref>[http://thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_K/Keeler.Willie.Obit.html \"Willie Keeler Dies of Heart Disease\"\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 2, 1923. Accessed October 29, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Brian Kokoska]] (born 1988), artist{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Talib Kweli]] (born 1975), emcee{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Lil' Kim]] (born 1974), rapper<ref>Ogunnaike, Lola. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/nyregion/20kim.html \"A Flourish, and Lil' Kim Goes From Star to Inmate\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 20, 2005. Accessed October 19, 2007. \"Ms. Jones spoke about her rise from Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, to stardom and about her deepening relationship with God.\"</ref>\n* [[Maino]] (born 1973), rapper<ref>Mlynar, Phillip. [http://www.villagevoice.com/music/qanda-maino-on-growing-up-in-bed-stuy-hearing-rumors-about-himself-and-his-song-that-isnt-about-lil-kim-6620028 \"Q&A: Maino On Growing Up In Bed-Stuy, Hearing Rumors About Himself, And His Song That Isn't About Lil Kim\"], ''[[Village Voice]]'', February 27, 2012. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"For the early part of his career, the Bedford-Stuyvesant-born Maino was better known as another New York City rapper with a nefarious background (he saw out a ten year jail bid for attempted kidnap) who traded in block-corner crime rhymes to the extent that he was as much someone in the street who also happened to rap as anyone approaching an artist.\"</ref>\n* [[Masta Ace]] (born 1966), rapper{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Frank McCourt]] (1930\u20132009), a writer, and [[Malachy McCourt]] (born 1931), an actor, writer and politician. Frank's autobiographical bestseller ''[[Angela's Ashes]]'' describes their early childhood life in a working-class apartment building on Classon Avenue.<ref>[[William Grimes (journalist)|Grimes, William]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/20/books/20mccourt.html \"Frank McCourt, Whose Irish Childhood Illuminated His Prose, Is Dead at 78\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 19, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Francis McCourt was born Aug. 19, 1930, on Classon Avenue on the edge of the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, where his Irish immigrant parents had hoped to make a better life.\"</ref>\n* [[Frank Mickens]] (1946\u20132009), educator<ref>Hevesi, Dennis. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/11/nyregion/11mickens.html \"Frank Mickens, Who Brought Success to a Tough Brooklyn High School, Dies at 63\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 10, 2009. Accessed May 1, 2017. \"Frank Nathaniel Mickens was born in Bedford-Stuyvesant on June 22, 1946, the only child of John and Hortense Mickens.\"</ref>\n* [[Stephanie Mills]] (born 1957), singer\n* [[Sauce Money]], rapper\n* [[Tracy Morgan]] (born 1968), comedian and actor<ref>Staff. [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=114009203 \"Tracy Morgan On Being 'The New Black'\"], [[National Public Radio]], October 22, 2009. Accessed July 23, 2010.</ref>\n* [[Mos Def]] (aka [[Yasiin Bey]]) (born 1973), rapper\n* [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (born 1970), DJ, producer and member of [[A Tribe Called Quest]]<ref>Torres, Andre. [https://linearlabsmusic.com/artist/ali-shaheed-muhammad/ \"Ali Shaheed Muhammad \u2013 About\"], Linear Labs, Accessed February 27, 2019. \"The soft-spoken and contemplative Brooklyn native began a life of music at an early age, spending years DJing parties in his Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood before co-founding Tribe in 1985.\"</ref>\n* [[Jack Newfield]] (1938\u20132004), journalist<ref name= rfk/>\n* [[Harry Nilsson]] (1941-1994), musician, songwriter and author<ref>Staff. [http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/harry-nilssons-childhood-home \"Harry Nilsson's Childhood HomeThe childhood home of one of America's greatest unsung troubadours still stands in a much changed Brooklyn neighborhood\"], ''[[Atlas Obscura]]''. Accessed June 17, 2017. \"The crooner was born to a poor family in the Bed-Stuy section of Brooklyn on June 15th, 1941. He lived on the top floor of 762 Jefferson Avenue, a simple Romanesque Revival-style apartment building constructed in 1901, until the family fled to California a decade later.\"</ref>\n* [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] (1972\u201397), rapper, grew up near the Clinton Hill-Bed Stuy border, previously considered part of the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.<ref name=\"100BestOpenLineRapHistory2-Complex\">[http://www.complex.com/music/2013/02/the-100-best-opening-lines-in-rap-history-part-2-50-1/notorious-big-unbelievable \"The 100 Best Opening Lines in Rap History, Part 2: 50 - 1\"], in ''ComplexMusic'', February 21, 2013, as accessed September 15, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"Biggie's 'One-Room Shack' in Bed-Stuy Now up for Sale\">{{cite web|author=Bed-Stuy |url=http://bed-stuy.patch.com/groups/real-estate/p/biggie-s-one-room-shack-in-bed-stuy-now-up-for-sale |title=Biggie's 'One-Room Shack' in Bed-Stuy Now up for Sale - Real Estate - Bed-Stuy, NY Patch |publisher=Bed-stuy.patch.com |date=April 3, 2013 |accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Oddisee]], rapper, producer\n* [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]] (1968\u20132004), rapper\n* [[Papoose (rapper)|Papoose]] (born 1978), rapper\n* [[Floyd Patterson]] (1935\u20132006), boxer\n* [[Martha M. Place]] (1849\u201399), first woman to be put to death in the electric chair<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=18990320&id=C8EhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LZ0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=5226,6178341 \"Put to Death: Mrs. Place Made No Scene in the Electric Chair\"], ''[[The Reading Eagle]]'', March 20, 1899. Accessed October 29, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Jackie Robinson]] (1919\u201372), professional baseball player with the Brooklyn Dodgers<ref>Harpaz, Beth J. [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/guide-exploring-jackie-robinsons-brooklyn \"A Guide to Exploring Jackie Robinson's Brooklyn\"], ''[[The Associated Press]]'', April 10, 2013. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Chris Rock]] (born 1965), actor/comedian.<ref>Osterhout, Jacob E. [http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/chris-rock-new-york-documentary-good-hair-set-open-tour-hometown-article-1.379885 \"Chris Rock's New York: As his documentary 'Good Hair' is set to open, a tour of his hometown\"], ''[[New York Daily News]]'', October 3, 2009. Accessed October 25, 2013.</ref> Also made a [[Everybody Hates Chris|TV series about his early life]], with much of it based in Bedford-Stuyvesant.\n* [[Tony Rock]] (born 1974), comedian and younger brother of Chris Rock\n* [[Gabourey Sidibe]] (born 1983), [[Academy Award]]-nominated actress\n* [[Skyzoo]] (born 1982), rapper\n* [[Brandon Stanton]] (born 1984), [[Humans of New York]] author and photographer\n* [[Tek (rapper)|Tek]] (born 1973), one half of [[Smif-N-Wessun]]\n* [[Bill Thompson (New York politician)|Bill Thompson]] (born 1953), New York City 2013 Mayoral candidate<ref name=\"WmThompsonChallenge-BkRail\">[http://www.brooklynrail.org/2003/04/local/william-thompsons-challenges ''William Thompson's Challenges''], in ''The Brooklyn Rail'', April\u2013May 2003.</ref>\n* [[True (artist)|TRUE]] (born 1968), artist\n* [[Mike Tyson]] (born 1966), boxer, lived there with his family until the age of 10.<ref>{{Cite book | url=http://www.bookrags.com/biography/mike-tyson-cri/#gsc.tab=0 |title = Mike Tyson Summary}}</ref>\n* [[Martha Wainwright]] (born 1976), singer\n* [[Dan Washburn]], [[List of American authors|author]] of ''[[The Forbidden Game (non-fiction book)|The Forbidden Game: Golf and the Chinese Dream]]''\n* [[Whodini]], hip-hop group\n* [[Lenny Wilkens]] (born 1937), [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] player and coach<ref>Beck, Howard. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/28/sports/basketball/28knicks.html \"PRO BASKETBALL; Wilkens Denies He Was Asked to Go\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 28, 2005. Accessed November 20, 2007. \"A native of Brooklyn's Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant neighborhood, Wilkens had added motivation to succeed in New York, which made leaving so quickly that much tougher.\"</ref>\n* [[Juan Williams]] (born 1954), journalist and political analyst\n* [[Ted Williams (announcer)|Ted Williams]] (born 1957), voiceover artist\n* [[Vanessa A. Williams]] (born 1963), actress\n{{colend}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\n<!--Please only include entries with reliable sources-->\n* [[Billy Joel]]'s 1980 song \"[[You May Be Right (song)|You May Be Right]],\" from his album ''Glass Houses,'' includes \"I walked through Bedford-Stuy alone\" among the foolhardy things the song's narrator has done.<ref>Barbarino, Al. [https://commercialobserver.com/2014/03/you-may-be-right-about-bedford-stuyvesant/ \"'You May Be Right' About Bedford-Stuyvesant\"], ''Commercial Observer'', March 12, 2014. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"In Billy Joel's 1980 hit, 'You May Be Right,' the singer boasted of his 'crazy' antics crashing parties, riding his motorcycle in the rain and even walking 'through Bedford-Stuy alone.'\"</ref>\n* In her 1980 one-woman film ''[[Gilda Live]],'' [[Gilda Radner]] included a sketch featuring her [[Emily Litella]] character working as a substitute teacher in Bedford-Stuyversant, filling in for a teacher who'd been stabbed by one of his students.<ref>Staff. [https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/73507796/ \"Gilda Live\"], ''[[The Pantagraph]]'', May 15, 1980. Accessed July 6, 2016. \"Twittery Emily Litella substitute-teaches in Bedford-Stuyvesant (her use of eraser and chalk stand out in Radner's repertoire of physical gags).\"</ref>\n* ''[[Do the Right Thing]]'', a movie by [[Spike Lee]]<ref>Smith, Rita Webb, & Tony Chapelle, ''The Woman Who Took Back Her Streets'', ''op. cit.'', p.&nbsp;290.</ref>\n* [[Notorious B.I.G.]], a rapper who included Bed\u2013Stuy in his lyrics,<ref name=\"100BestOpenLineRapHistory2-Complex\"/> he \"publicly {{Nowrap|claim[ed]}} Bedford-Stuyvesant as his neighborhood\".<ref name=\"TodayPrideBedStuyBIG-Patch\">[http://bed-stuy.patch.com/groups/around-town/p/today-s-pride-of-bed-stuy-christopher-wallace-aka-the5964734f17 Morris, C. Zawadi, ''Today's Pride of Bed-Stuy: Christopher Wallace aka The Notorious B.I.G.'', in ''Bed-Stuy Patch'', February 29, 2012, 5:00 p.m.], as accessed September 15, 2013 (reprint from February 24, 2011).</ref> A 2009 film, ''[[Notorious (2009 film)|Notorious]]'', about life in Bed\u2013Stuy in the 1990s, emphasized Notorious B.I.G.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/nyregion/20notorious.html?_r=0 Eligon, John, ''Film About a Rapper Captures Bed-Stuy as It Once Was'', in ''The New York Times'', January 19, 2009], accessed September 15, 2013.</ref>\n* The period television sitcom, ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' is set in the Bed-Stuy neighborhood (which is where series creator [[Chris Rock]]\u2019s family lived in during the 1970s and 1980s).<ref>Gill, John Freeman. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/04/nyregion/thecity/wonder-years-by-way-of-bedstuy.html \"''Wonder Years,'' by Way of Bed-Stuy\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 4, 2005. Accessed January 13, 2020. \"This fall, with the new hit UPN television show ''Everybody Hates Chris,'' the country is finally seeing a representation of Bed-Stuy shaped by one of its own: Chris Rock, the show's co-creator and narrator, on whose Decatur Street childhood the program is loosely based. Set in Bed-Stuy in 1982, ''Everybody Hates Chris'' is a nostalgic, warmly illuminated take on the Rock family's tough working-class life in the predominantly black neighborhood.\"</ref> The show occasionally refers to the neighborhood by its often-used nickname \"Bed-Stuy Do or Die.\"\n\n==See also==\n* [[13th Regiment Armory]], former armory in Bed\u2013Stuy\n* [[Magnolia grandiflora (Brooklyn)]], a landmark tree in Bed\u2013Stuy\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Brooklyn/Bedford-Stuyvesant and Flatbush|